<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE VIEW CAN CHANGE, BUT NOT THE MOUNTAINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA _ To the relief of those who worry the new owner will
completely ruin Santa Anita Park, Frank Stronach revealed Saturday
that there is a limit to his imagination.
</P>
<P>
   It ends at the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mountains will stay,'' Stronach said with aplomb when
someone asked which _ if any _ of Santa Anita's distinctive
features he !ital!wouldn't!off! consider changing. ``There's no
question about that.''
</P>
<P>
   So that's good news: The mighty San Gabriels will always be part
of a day at Santa Anita. As for everything else that makes racing
here special, the message is wait and see.
</P>
<P>
   Stronach has proposed sweeping changes for the 64-year-old
track, which his Magna International Developments purchased two
weeks ago for $126 million. And that lent a bittersweet atmosphere
to the opening day of the four-month season.
</P>
<P>
   For those in the crowd of 42,000 who follow the racing industry
news, it was impossible not to linger over favorite places in the
320-acre park, wondering if they'll still be here by the day after
Christmas in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   For me, there's the Seabiscuit statue, honoring Santa Anita's
first superstar; the odds board up near the roof on the back of the
grandstand, beckoning the real sportsmen among the fancy people in
the walking ring; the footpaths to and from the paddock, upon which
even a 1/100th owner of a $10,000 claimer feels like a billionaire
walking between staring fans; the giant ``Shoe Wants You'' poster
that adorns a grandstand stairwell, recalling a classic old ad
campaign; Clockers' Corner, one of sports' great gathering spots;
the elegant main room of the clubhouse; the clubhouse mezzanine
where the jockeys' agents and other sharpies gather; and the
underground Paddock Room that's still thick with down-and-dirty
atmosphere if no longer with cigarette smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Some, or most, or all of those might be gone if Stronach goes
ahead with his head-spinning array of plans for the tradition-bound
track and its precious real estate: Construction of Citywalk-style
stores, restaurants and amusements in an area partially covered by
the paddock gardens, building luxury suites and condominiums and a
hotel, the last project to require lopping off part of the
clubhouse; installing a second turf course after removing the
hillside portion of the existing turf course, and underground
parking.
</P>
<P>
   And Stronach, born in Austria 66 years ago, said nothing
Saturday in his first press conference as Santa Anita's chairman to
indicate there's anything iffy about any of this. He repeated his
proposals of the past two weeks, firmed up some of them, and added
at least one, suggesting vaguely that he'll purchase more U.S.
tracks and make Santa Anita part of a ``network.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he hopes to implement ``in a few weeks'' a plan to
basically eliminate the current $5 general-admission price by
charging $6 and giving each patron a $4 food voucher and a $2
betting credit.
</P>
<P>
   He said he has budgeted about $50 million for ``immediate''
architectural changes, which he'd like to begin as soon as the end
of the meet in April, pending City of Arcadia approval.
</P>
<P>
   He said major projects like the complete reconstruction of the
barns could be accomplished in five years.
</P>
<P>
   It all sounds like progress. It all sounds like good thinking in
a sport that's suffered from too little imagination.
</P>
<P>
   And Stronach does promise that for every garden that is taken
away, a prettier garden will be added.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's going to be a little pain, isn't there?
</P>
<P>
   I don't know if opening day felt more like a rebirth, the start
of something big; or a funeral, the death of something grand. Maybe
what it felt like was a bris.
</P>
<P>
   At one point Saturday afternoon, Stronach was seen strolling
with a lieutenant through the crowded mezzanine. Every few yards,
he'd pause and gesture toward some nook or cranny of the massive
structure, pointing out an area of potential improvement.
</P>
<P>
   It was a slow walk. Lots of stops. But no, he never once pointed
at the mountains. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
