<SLUG> BC-HKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NHL TO NBA: DON'T GO THERE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ It's an unsettling feeling for more than a
few NHL players, to be on the outside looking in as the holidays of
NBA players are turned upside down and shaken, just to see if their
resolve will fall like snow in one of those kitschy plastic domes.
</P>
<P>
   When NBA commissioner David Stern recently declared a drop-dead
date in the league's protracted labor dispute, it triggered
flashbacks to the 1994 yuletide season for the likes of Phoenix
forward Bob Corkum and Kings defenseman Rob Blake.
</P>
<P>
   Chestnuts-on-an-open fire kind of memories, they were not. A
Christmas tree catching on fire in mid-carol is closer to it. The
family fir didn't go up in flames but a year of their precious
careers nearly did.
</P>
<P>
   The prospects of any games being played in 1995 seemed bleak to
Blake at this time four years ago. Corkum, then the
player-representative for the Mighty Ducks of Anaheim, was
conflicted over taking care of future generations of players and
tending to the day-to-day needs of his growing family. But each got
by and now their bottom lines are better than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Neither carries any visible scars from the lockout, just the
usual ones from sticks to the face. Indeed, all the players on the
Forum ice Saturday who had sweated out the 104-day work stoppage
would be able to block out the whole sorry saga if not for that
eerie feeling of deja vu they keep getting whenever they pick up a
newspaper or turn on the television.
</P>
<P>
   A deadline declared in the dead of December.
</P>
<P>
   Verbal volleys exchanged between the two negotiating principals
with no face-to-face follow-ups.
</P>
<P>
   A union-organized charity game.
</P>
<P>
   Growing fan disillusionment.
</P>
<P>
   A Christmas that was a paler shade of green, owing to the
tightening of purse strings.
</P>
<P>
   Like Gus Van Sant's remake of ``Psycho'', the NBA version of ``A
Lockout'' has been faithful to the original NHL script.
</P>
<P>
   ``The similarities that do exist are overwhelming,'' Corkum said
before the Coyotes' game against the Kings. ``It is like living it
all over again and just for that reason, it is (unsettling).''
</P>
<P>
   What a role player such as Corkum or even a standout like Blake
who is as decorated on defense as Dikembe Mutombo, can't relate to
is the high-end salaries in the NBA. Kevin Garnett's salary would
pay for a line of Wayne Gretzkys and the profits that are at the
center of the tug-of-war between the NBA and its players' union
would have a giddy NHL incredulously double-checking its figures.
</P>
<P>
   It's all relative, though, which is why Corkum doesn't wince
when Dallas Mavericks millionaire Kurt Thomas' quote of a couple of
days ago _ the one that made us choke on our gruel _ is relayed to
him. In case you missed it, Thomas said the lockout hasn't affected
him, really, because he lives as though he makes ONLY $120,000.
</P>
<P>
   Corkum presumes that Thomas didn't mean to put down the large
percent of the population for whom a six-figure salary would be a
princely wage. Just as he can appreciate (if not relate to) the
comfort zone Kenny Anderson was coming from when he went on about
having to maybe sacrifice one or two of his eight luxury
automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get used to a certain lifestyle and your monthly bills
reflect that,'' said Corkum, who in 1994 listened to many a player
relate acute financial concerns during NHLPA conference calls.
</P>
<P>
   The difference was the players for the most part kept the
hardship stories to themselves, having been reminded ad nauseum by
the executive of the players' union, Bob Goodenow, that whining
would win them no public sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   Evidently NBA union rep Billy Hunter forgot to mention that to
his membership. ``You've got to be so careful what you say,'' said
Kings defenseman Garry Galley, who was a player rep in Philadelphia
in 1994-95. ``Because what you say can determine how people
perceive your cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake put it more bluntly: ``You don't want to look like greedy
people.''
</P>
<P>
   That's but one piece of advice Blake has passed on to
ex-Clippers guard Brent Barry. As an impending free agent, Barry's
immediate future hangs tenuously in the balance of the ongoing
dispute. He has kept in regular contact with Blake, seeking his
advice not only as a friend but per Blake's role as the NHLPA vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA is inside two weeks of the deadline imposed by Stern.
The NHL reached a settlement after its so-called drop-dead date. Of
course, in the end it wasn't really the number that mattered as
much as it was the sense of urgency that came attached to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can remember as the date got closer guys saying, `We've got
to be careful. This game is loved by a lot of people and we're
jeopardizing that,''' Galley said.
</P>
<P>
   The final deal, which was ratified by 85 percent of the
membership in time to salvage a 48-game season, didn't set well
with Corkum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still giving them more than we should,'' he said at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday Corkum admitted that time has sort of smoothed over
his ruffled feathers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four years later, looking at the way salaries have escalated,
you have to say it was a good deal,'' Corkum said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, anyone who has been through a war knows there are no
winners, just survivors.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's true,'' Corkum said, and by the tone of his voice it
was clear he meant it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
