<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES DEFEAT KINGS AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ With their Christmas break behind them, the
Kings were looking Saturday night to build on the momentum they'd
generated with consecutive road victories earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
   But with the usual combination of an inept power play and an
untimely defensive breakdown, consider the momentum gone.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Adams' goal with 2:33 to play was the difference in a 2-1
victory by the Phoenix Coyotes before a crowd of 13,898 at the
Forum.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings (10-21-3), who are 0-3 against the Coyotes (20-6-4)
this season, now face the daunting task of visiting Phoenix on
Monday night. The Coyotes are 10-1-1 at home.
</P>
<P>
   Adams scored the game-winner when he took a Shane Doan pass at
the blue line, skated around Kings defenseman Doug Bodger, drove to
the net and swatted the puck into the net while falling to the ice.
</P>
<P>
   But the game had been lost _ or at least it had not been won _
earlier in the third period, when the Kings could make nothing out
of three power-play chances. As has so often been the case, the
Kings not only didn't get any goals with the man advantage, they
didn't even manage to produce any serious scoring opportunities. In
fact, they often struggled to get the puck out of their own end of
the ice, at times because of the checking of the persistent
Coyotes, but at other times because of their own sloppy passing.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, why should the power play have been any different on
a night when zeroes dominated the Kings' thoughts?
</P>
<P>
   The Kings entered the game with zero victories and zero points
against their own division, the only team in the NHL still able to
claim such a dubious distinction.
</P>
<P>
   And with the Coyotes in town, it brought to mind another zero
that left the Kings with an empty feeling.
</P>
<P>
   In their first meeting with Phoenix this season, the Kings were
3-0 losers. In the next meeting, Phoenix won 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   For the first 11:30 Saturday, the Kings weren't worried about
getting a goal. They were worried about getting a (begin
ital)shot(end ital) on goal.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, rookie Pavel Rosa managed to put a long shot at Coyotes
goalie Nikolai Khabibulin, who easily made the save. Then, at
12:03, Rosa stole the puck along the right boards in the Coyotes'
zone and passed it to Vladimir Tsyplakov, who fired the puck over
Khabibulin's glove and into the net, ending Phoenix's shutout hex
of the Kings at 139 minutes, 22 seconds dating to last season.
</P>
<P>
   But it was one of the few offensive highlights in the first two
periods for the Kings, who managed just 10 shots on goal in the
opening 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Kings were fortunate to hang onto the lead
against the Coyotes, who were playing without star left wing Keith
Tkachuk, who is sidelined with a sprained knee.
</P>
<P>
   With seven minutes left in the first period, Rob Blake cleared a
loose puck out of the crease just before the Coyotes' Jeremy
Roenick could swat it past goalie Jamie Storr.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix trailed after one period despite outshooting the Kings,
14-4, but 4:08 into the second period, the Coyotes got on the board
when Blake was trapped deep in the offensive zone. On the resulting
2-on-1, Roenick appeared to lose control of the puck in front of
the Kings' net, but when defenseman Mattias Norstrom couldn't clear
it, Roenick was able to poke it in. It was the first goal allowed
by the Kings in 114:14, a span that began in their 4-1 victory in
Chicago a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   The next goal they allowed was the one by Adams, which forced
the Kings to pull Storr in the last minute for an extra skater. But
the Kings could not get the equalizer and fell to 0-7 against
Pacific Division teams.
</P>
</TEXT>
