<HEADER>
A7464 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FIESTA-JUNKER-AZR     12-27 1354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-JUNKER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAN BEHIND THE BOWL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - He has been in charge of one of the Valley's
oldest sports franchises for nearly 10 years, leading it through
crises that threatened its survival and nurturing it into one of
the leaders in its industry.
</P>
<P>
   Yet few Valley sports fans could pick John Junker, the executive
director of the Fiesta Bowl, out of a lineup. ``That's very healthy
and good,'' Junker said of his anonymity in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Most bowl officials fit the stereotype of loud, boisterous
people who press flesh and hand out business cards. The short,
43-year-old Junker looks more like a Wal-Mart manager than one of
the most powerful men in college football.
</P>
<P>
   His influence is wielded behind the scenes. He does his
homework, builds consensus, and if he goes out on a limb, it's
always the strongest one he can find.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sort of blends into the background,'' said Don Meyers, a
Phoenix lawyer and one of the bowl's founders. ``Some of the other
bowl directors who were loud, who were always out in front, who
were all talk and no action, have disappeared.''
</P>
<P>
   Junker's understated approach is never more evident than each
spring when the bowl sponsors a golf outing that attracts coaches,
athletic directors and conference commissioners to the Valley. Amid
the movers and shakers of the sport, Junker looks like a guy who
cleans golf clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very low-profile,'' said Roy Kramer, the commissioner of
the Southeastern Conference and one of the designers of the current
Bowl Championship Series. ``One of John's great traits is that he's
been able to . . . bring that innovative approach to other bowls
without them feeling he's trampling on them or being overbearing.''
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible to question Junker's effectiveness. In his
nearly 10 years as executive director, he has led the bowl through
hard times, sponsorship difficulties and social upheaval over a
Martin Luther King holiday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in a survival mode all the time,'' Junker said.
</P>
<P>
   There were times during those years that there were serious
doubts that the bowl would prosper. Yet today, it's one of the top
four bowls in the country and will host a game Jan. 4 between No.
1-ranked Tennessee and No. 2 Florida State that should determine
the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   It's no small accomplishment, but Junker wants little credit for
it. He points to the bowl's 2,500 volunteers. He credits his staff
of 21 full-time employees. He praises the community for making it
possible. But he won't ever say that John Junker is a major reason
the bowl is where it is today.
</P>
<P>
   ``The volunteer aspect of the Fiesta Bowl is really the untold
story of what this bowl is about,'' Junker said.
</P>
<P>
   Not really. Junker is the untold story, and he would prefer to
keep it that way.
</P>
<P>
   He is a graduate of Arizona State University and was assistant
sports information director there for two years. Those were glory
days at ASU, when Frank Kush coached football.
</P>
<P>
   That's where Junker's love of college football blossomed, and
Kush made things more interesting than most coaches. Today, Junker
and Kush are good friends, and Junker can still do a decent
imitation of the old coach.
</P>
<P>
   More than once, Kush asked Junker to vote for him in the old
coaches' poll run by United Press International.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say, `Well, Coach, we're playing real well, we have to be
in the top five or six,' '' Junker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Frank would say, `What the hell are you talking about!
Don't even put us on that damn thing.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Junker, who has a journalism degree, was hired at the Fiesta
Bowl in 1980 by Bruce Skinner, then the executive director.
</P>
<P>
   His main duties, as one of four employees, were to handle the
bowl's public relations, but the job developed into much more than
that.
</P>
<P>
   He helped negotiate a sponsorship with Sunkist. It was the first
agreement of its kind in the bowl business.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, Junker left the bowl to become the executive director
of the John Hancock Bowl in El Paso, but a year later Skinner left
to start his own business.
</P>
<P>
   Junker was wooed back to the Fiesta Bowl, but not before a
meeting of the bowl's board of directors, who were divided between
Junker and Kirk Hendrix, an assistant at the Fiesta Bowl at that
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people claim, erroneously, that the decision was made
in front of the fireplace at my house,'' lawyer Meyers said. ``But
we recognized we had the votes to get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   The task facing Junker was daunting. The bowl was in financial
trouble after it sponsored a festival that flopped badly. Junker
had to make cuts, including eliminating some jobs. The employees
who remained were overworked and underpaid.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sure wasn't pleasant, and in retrospect I have some
regrets,'' Junker said. ``I wish I had dealt with people better in
some ways.`
</P>
<P>
   The challenges continued. In 1990, the Fiesta Bowl suffered
through difficult times while Arizona grappled with the King
holiday issue. Many colleges that normally would have accepted bids
to the bowl refused because the state lacked a King holiday, and
the bowl settled for inviting two lesser teams, Louisville and
Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   In the ensuing years, there seemed to be a crisis every year.
Three times, the bowl had to search for new sponsors. For two
years, it lacked a title sponsor and survived thanks to local
sponsors that filled the gap.
</P>
<P>
   And when some of the top conferences in the country talked about
forming a coalition, guaranteeing their champions berths in the top
bowl games, Fiesta officials had to move quickly to work their way
into the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   As the coalition developed into the bowl alliance and now the
Bowl Championship Series, the Fiesta Bowl kept pace, and through a
bid process, earned the right to host this year's title game, the
first under the BCS agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'm not shocked the Fiesta Bowl went from the smallest
to the largest,'' said Alex Crutchfield, the bowl's president in
1987. ``We've had an awful lot of good people who have worked in
this bowl. Somehow, we were always on the cutting edge, and John
has continued that.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Crutchfield and Junker worked together often,
traveling to sponsorship meetings or to watch games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was quiet and I was overbearing and a loudmouth,''
Crutchfield said. ``Once in a while he would have a beer, and I,
once in a while, would not have a beer. But he was fun and I
watched him grow from an honest, caring young kid into a man.''
</P>
<P>
   Running a bowl is crisis management, and through the years,
Junker learned a key lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``You begin to realize you are not in control of things,''
Junker says. ``It helped me get my life priorities in place. Faith
and family and those things are more important.''
</P>
<P>
   While Junker still works long hours, he carves out more time at
home with his wife, Susan, and two children, Lucy, 6, and Michael
Dale, 3, than he used to.
</P>
<P>
   Junker readily admits he's still not particularly easy to work
for.
</P>
<P>
   He is notoriously late for appointments, and if you wanted to
torture him, you would force him to show up at the airport an hour
early for a flight. That's what happened a few weeks ago, when he
was traveling with the bowl's president, Herman Frazier.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me, `Herman, if you told my staff we were here an hour
before the plane was leaving, they wouldn't believe it,' '' Frazier
said. ``If there is a knock on him, it's that whenever it's time to
go somewhere, you have to pull him out of the office and get
going.''
</P>
<P>
   When Junker has time for lunch, the meal isn't a long, drawn-out
affair. If Junker picks the place, you're liable to end up at a
small sub shop next to a coin laundry just off Van Buren, a short
drive from the Fiesta Bowl office in Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   Junker likes the place because it's quick, it's good and few
people recognize him. In that way, it's just about like any other
place in the Valley. &QL; 
Kent Somers can be reached at 602-444-8335 or at
kent.somers(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
