r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FIESTA-MONEY-AZR &LR;      12-27 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-MONEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIESTA BOWL: BIG GAME, LITTLE CASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - College football fans weren't the only ones
trying to figure out how the Bowl Championship Series was going to
work in its inaugural season.
</P>
<P>
   Folks over at the Tostitos Fiesta Bowl, which is hosting the
BCS' first championship game this season, have done a lot of
brainstorming, number crunching and brow wiping trying to figure
out how the whole thing would work out financially.
</P>
<P>
   The BCS formula that rates the top teams in the country is
complicated enough. Try figuring out how a bowl will survive
financially despite losing revenue from television and title
sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
   That is the daunting task that's faced John Junker, the Fiesta
Bowl's executive director, and his staff for the past two years as
the BCS has taken form.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a stressful couple years getting ready for it,''
Junker said. ``But I think we'll be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   The BCS has dramatically changed the way its participating bowls
_ the Fiesta, Sugar, Orange and Rose _ do business. Under the new
agreement, which runs for four years, all money from title
sponsorship goes to ABC, which is televising the four games each
year.
</P>
<P>
   The payouts to the participating teams, about $13 million each,
are made by ABC from one big pool. (Most of the money is
distributed among the teams' conferences.)
</P>
<P>
   That's a dramatic departure from the past, when bowls were free
to negotiate their own deals with title sponsors and networks and
were responsible for determining their own payouts.
</P>
<P>
   The Fiesta Bowl thrived under that free market. It was the first
bowl to acquire a title sponsor (Sunkist), and it helped
revolutionize the sports marketing industry.
</P>
<P>
   Now, those revenue streams are as dry as the Salt River bed, but
the four bowls still have to find ways to raise the $4 million
payment they each make to the BCS pool each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little tougher than it used to be,'' Junker said, ``and
sometimes it's a lot tougher than it used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   When the BCS was being formed, Fiesta Bowl officials knew they
wanted to be a part of it. Anything less would have been a step
down for the bowl, which will have its fourth national championship
game Jan. 4 when No. 1 Tennessee plays No. 2 Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   The question was: What would it cost the bowl?
</P>
<P>
   There was some discussion, Junker said, of becoming a bare-bones
operation and cutting back dramatically on the number of events
that were staged and the level of service provided to participating
teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really thought about it,'' he said. ``It was apparent that
wasn't in congress with our identity. We didn't want to be in the
business of telling teams, `Hey, we'll see you on game day.' That's
not the kind of community we're from. Everybody here has people
from all over the country coming to visit. Hospitality is a way of
life around here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be an incredible experience to one day wake up and
find yourself the owner of the Cardinals, the Suns, the
Diamondbacks or the Coyotes. That's not going to happen. But there
are a tremendous number of people who really do own the Fiesta
Bowl. It's as much community-owned as anything I've seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowl officials, who work with about 2,500 volunteers, looked at
their alternatives. The largest locally generated revenue source
available to bowls comes from ticket sales. So the Fiesta Bowl
hiked prices from an average of $80 last year to about $135 for
this upcoming game.
</P>
<P>
   They looked at sponsorship money. Tostitos nows pays ABC
directly for the title sponsorship rights to the Fiesta Bowl. But
Tostitos is still contributing to the bowl directly by sponsoring
other activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had to play to our strengths even more so now,'' said
Herman Frazier, who holds the bowl's presidency, a voluntary
position. ``We have to be innovative to come up with some things.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fiesta is still sponsoring 51 annual events ranging from a
band pageant to a duck race to a parade. Some events, like the duck
race, are designed as fund-raisers. With other events, organizers
say silent prayers that they will finish in the black.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parades, band pageants, those kinds of things can be sources
of revenue,'' Junker said. ``But there is also a pretty fair amount
of risk with them. If it rains on your parade or block party, or
you have a sponsorship (deal) that has a last-minute
complication.''
</P>
<P>
   The BCS benefits the Fiesta Bowl in one big way: Every four
years, it guarantees the bowl of a game featuring the top two teams
in the country.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't possible in the old days when bowls made deals
behind the scenes to try to secure the best matchups. And it wasn't
possible under the agreements that preceded the BCS because the
Rose Bowl wasn't a part of it, meaning the Pac-10 and Big 10
champions were not in the mix.
</P>
<P>
   There are some business drawbacks to the BCS, however. ABC has
exclusive agreements with companies in some sponsorship categories,
meaning the bowls are not free to negotiate with competitors in
those categories.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a complaint,'' Junker said. ``It's just one of the
things we've had to go through that have made it more of a
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   In its long-term projections, the bowl expects to lose money in
three of the four years of the agreement, making money this year.
Those projections are conservative, said Junker.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the margin for error is small, and with a big game like
this one, it's tempting to spend more than budgeted, Junker said.
``And you don't have to be a large percentage over in any one area.
When you do it cumulatively, you can have a big financial
hangover.''
</P>
<P>
   Staying financially viable is one of the bowl's biggest
challenges in the years to come. That's why Junker and bowl's board
of directors have met with Cardinals officials and heard their
pitch for a proposed domed facility east of Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Attracting the Fiesta Bowl would be a major acquisition for
those pushing the new stadium, and the opportunity to make more
money through things such as seats and skyboxes would be attractive
to bowl officials.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Junker is non-committal about his views about the
proposed facility, saying only that it's something the bowl has to
monitor closely, particularly in these financial times.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very few sure things in our business,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-98 0155EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
