<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-27 01:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7466 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-KINGS-AZR     12-27 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-KINGS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADAMS SPARKS COYOTES  
 GOAL IN 3RD PERIOD DECISIVE VS. KINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The last time the Coyotes were seen in Tinseltown,
they were flying high and completing an unbeaten November with a
10-0-1 record, which most teams only dream about.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, they are finally done flying after putting on 11,624
air miles while playing 11 of their past 13 on the road and coming
away with a 7-4-2 record after Saturday night's 2-1 victory over
the Los Angeles Kings.
</P>
<P>
   After taking a dominating 23-10 shot advantage entering the
third period and seeing it reduced to 25-23 in the next 15 minutes,
it could be suggested that the Coyotes are tired, especially
considering that those numbers came against a Kings team that has
been outscored, 38-25, in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the late-game heroics of veteran left wing Greg Adams,
who scored at 17:27 of the final period, they can open a five-game
homestand Monday against the Kings in a good frame of mind.
</P>
<P>
   Adams picked a pass off the boards from Shane Doan and deked
goalie Jamie Storr out of position for the game winner.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes penalty kill returned to its early-season
brilliance, snuffing five L.A. power plays, three in the third
period, while giving up only two shots. And they had goaltender
Nikolai Khabibulin, who, after sailing calm waters in the first two
periods, was brilliant in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Khabibulin had little work to do for much of the first period as
Phoenix dominated in every area except one _ goals, which is the
reason they play the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes' forecheck held the Kings without a shot for the
first 11:26 of the game and only four for the first period, while
taking 14 against Kings goalie and former Roadrunner Storr. By 7:55
of the second period, the shot total was a lopsided 21-6.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Phoenix, the Kings' Vladimir Tsyplakov scored
on their second shot at 12:03 of the first. Khabibulin, who blanked
the Kings, 3-0 and 4-0, at the Great Western Forum in November, saw
a shutout streak over the Kings that dated back to last season and
had lasted for a hockey eternity _ 136 minutes, 54 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why I have so much success against the Kings,''
said Khabibulin, who stopped 26 shots. ``It just happens that way
against some teams.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason is that Khabibulin is rested, having made his 20th
start in the 30th game. Last year he had 27 starts in the first 30
games. It's a product of design, as Coyotes Coach Jim Schoenfeld
wants him rested and ready later in the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, so good,'' Khabibulin said. ``The team isn't losing.
Maybe the rest will help later in the season. I don't know, because
I've never been in this position before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I accepting it? I'm accepting it and I have no choice. As
long as we win, it's all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Tysplakov barely beat Oleg Tverdovsky to a weak pass from Pavel
Rosa. Finding himself wide open in the slot, he lifted a shot over
Phoenix defenseman Keith Carney's block attempt and beat
Khabibulin's gloveside at the shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Phoenix, assistant captain Jeremy Roenick
countered Tysplakov's goal at 4:08 of the second period on a
brilliant but far from picturesque play.
</P>
<P>
   He scored while sliding into the crease to knock home his own
rebound after taking a pass from Dallas Drake. He used Drake's
position on the wing perfectly to keep the lone defender honest
before firing on Storr from point-blank range.
</P>
<P>
   It extended Roenick's scoring streak to six games, during which
he has had five goals and three assists. In his last 20 games, he's
had 10 goals and 28 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, if I get a chance, I feel I can bury it,'' Roenick
said of his hot play. ``It's just a matter of getting the chances
that makes me nervous. You gotta take it to the hole because it
creates a lot of havoc and turmoil. Anything can happen then.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
