</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUDETTE HEARTENS KINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ At 5 feet 8, 184 pounds,  &UR; Donald Audette could get
lost in the tall forest that is the Los Angeles Kings, but he
hasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Since he joined the Kings two games ago from Buffalo for a
second-round draft choice after holding out most of the season,
L.A. is 2-0, and Coach  &UR; Larry Robinson credits him for adding heart
to his team.
</P>
<P>
   On his very first shift against Chicago, Audette crashed the net
and knocked home a rebound at 1:36 of the first period.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys on the bench saw him and said, `Hell, if he's going
to the net, we can, too,' '' Robinson said at Saturday morning's
skate. ``That's what has made Phoenix so successful this year,
going to the net for rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last couple of games, we've shown patience in our own zone
defensively. We're not causing needless turnovers, like Phoenix has
been doing. Most goalies in this league are going to stop the first
shot. That's why it's important to crash the net for rebounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes forward  &UR; Rick Tocchet thanks Robinson for the
compliment, but he wishes it was better deserved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry is giving us too much credit,'' Tocchet said. ``We have
and haven't done it well. It's one thing the captains, especially
 &UR; Keith
 &UR; Tkachuk, are constantly all over guys (about). We could be a better
team going to the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't have just two or three guys doing it. We have to
sacrifice for each other, especially on the road. It's takes
courage to go in there, because you've got to take a shot to the
head.'' &QL; 
Yahoo, Juha &QL; 
Entering his 30th game Saturday against the Kings, forward
 &UR; Juha &UR; Ylonen had already topped his entire rookie output in 55
games last year by one with 13 points, and quadrupled his goal
output with four, including one in each of the last three games.
</P>
<P>
   He credits his improvement to ice time and playing with forwards
Tocchet and  &UR; Greg Adams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still playing my game (defense),'' Ylonen said. ``But if
you get more ice time, you get more chances. My confidence is also
much better. I still think defense first, but playing with more
offensive guys like Rick and Greg helps.''
</P>
<P>
   Fellow Finn  &UR; Teppo Numminen takes the analysis a step farther.
</P>
<P>
   ``More ice time helps, but when (the puck) starts going in, you
play more relaxed. You don't think about scoring and do what you
know how to do.'' &QL; 
Ice chips &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Numminen, too, has been on a tear, scoring five goals and
totaling 15 points in his last 12 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea why,'' he explained. ``It's just later in the
season, I guess, and I've had a lot of power-play time. I've always
been a slow starter.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
