<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981227.0008 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-27 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7468 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YEAR-REVIEW-BICKLEY-A     12-27 2031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YEAR-REVIEW-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YEAR OF HIGH DRAMA, LOW COMEDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - You were like the child at Christmas. And like the
parent who lost the spirit in traffic jams and Furby searches.
</P>
<P>
   You were awed by the comets of history. And disgusted by stars
drifting further and further from our universe.
</P>
<P>
   You were treated to feats without peer, legitimate moments that
will stand like skyscrapers in the city of memories. And you spent
too much time in the back alleys, drawn in by the trash bins and
recycling containers of sport.
</P>
<P>
   To be a fan in 1998 was an exercise in cynicism and wonderment,
a relentless game of emotional Ping-Pong, a year that stretched
both ends to the extreme.
</P>
<P>
   A year, as any referee will attest, that was both heads and
tails.
</P>
<P>
   A year you followed in amazement. Or threw up your arms and
said, ``Luckett!``
</P>
<P>
   THE KINGS: Michael Jordan, Mark McGwire, Sammy Sosa, John Elway.
</P>
<P>
   THE JOKERS: The NBA.
</P>
<P>
   You want history? You got history.
</P>
<P>
   The world stopped for baseball, to watch two men conquer the
summer, the ghosts and the lingering bitterness infecting their
sport. McGwire and Sosa. Sosa and McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   Our All-American hero _ Divorced, but loves his child; uses
andro but will stop if it's deemed illegal; cries at movies but can
hit baseballs to Jupiter.
</P>
<P>
   Our lovable immigrant _ Smiles for everyone; defers to McGwire;
doesn't mind telling you that beisbol been berry, berry good to
him.
</P>
<P>
   One hits 70, the other 66. One saves baseball, the other wins an
MVP award. Two giants on the inside and out, two athletes who
remember how to say thank you and actually mean it.
</P>
<P>
   If that weren't enough, you watched 37-year-old John Elway win a
Super Bowl, flashing his Secretariat smile, holding the trophy in
triumph, admitting with candor that, yeah, he needed this to cement
his legacy.
</P>
<P>
   And the indomitable Michael Jordan, stealing the ball, working
the clock, faking a defender out of his Nikes, winning his sixth
championship with a jump shot that registered as perfection.
</P>
<P>
   Four men, four moments that will actually mean something 50
years from now. You're lucky if you catch one of these every
decade.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand . . .
</P>
<P>
   Chris Webber, twice arrested for marijuana; Alonzo Mourning
goaded into a fight, handing a playoff series to the Knicks, crying
racism among NBA owners; J.R. Rider, complaining that they ``still
hang brothers from trees'' in the remote suburbs of Portland; Kenny
Anderson on the road to bankruptcy; Anthony Mason, showing up at a
disastrous charity game dressed in a full-length mink with his
number sewn on the back. A league that has lost perspective, a
lockout proving that grown men can be idiots.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   SUBJECTS OF VALLEY HYSTERIA: Jake Plummer. The Cardinals. Randy
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   OF DESERT ANGST: Keith Tkachuk. Andre Wadsworth. Jerry
Colangelo.
</P>
<P>
   AND POSSIBLY THE DUMBEST THING I'VE EVER HEARD: See below.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone wants more money. And if you're looking for the hotbed
of economic dissension, the greedy tapeworm growing inside
professional sports, hey, welcome to Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Tkachuk had a contract, but demanded a new one. Andre
Wadsworth wouldn't report to camp without his own mint. And, boy,
does Jay Bell have a contract. Bank you very much.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks opened their roof on March 31, and it was
always about money. The price of beer, the overpaid veterans, that
damn tax. Coolergate, a hike in ticket prices on the weekend of fan
appreciation, a flap over renewal policy. A press conference to
explain the massive costs. And a few others to announce $119
million in free agent payroll.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals shook the money tree for Eric Swann, succumbed to
Wadsworth, and in the apex of a playoff run, did the most
irrationally brilliant, un-Bidwillian thing ever in locking up Jake
Plummer. But the young quarterback must promise to never change his
personality or his wardrobe, never demand his own suite in the new
stadium, never order a fur coat bearing the No. 16.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils gave a raise to Bruce Snyder, who claimed,
without laughing, that he did his best coaching job ever. The
highlight of the Suns' season was when Colangelo killed
pay-per-view. And the Coyotes gave in to Tkachuk who, of course, is
once again scoring goals and hearing cheers. But to his credit,
Tkachuk has spearheaded one of the most dramatic one-year face
lifts ever displayed by an organization. Or, since Bill Parcells
took over the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Strange fact about the Valley: In terms of passion, the negative
far outweighs the positive. So while there were plenty of good
things, fortunately, there was plenty to complain about.
</P>
<P>
   Especially one of Randy Johnson's agents, who after negotiating
a $53 million contract, explained how overwhelming it was to have a
client take such a enormous stand on principles, to place family
over money. Doh!
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   THE BEST TEAM: The Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   THE WORST TEAM: The U.S. Olympic hockey team.
</P>
<P>
   POSSIBLY THE FUNNIEST THING I'VE HEARD: See below.
</P>
<P>
   There were memorable endings. To Cal Ripken's streak. To Eric
Swann's season. To Harry Caray's life.
</P>
<P>
   To David Wells' perfect game. To Kevin Johnson's career with the
Suns. To Phil Jackson's run with the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   And possibly Jordan's groundbreaking, breathtaking career.
</P>
<P>
   To a season in which Arizona's basketball team may have smiled
once, but not after taking the silencer from Utah and Rick Majerus.
To a Coyotes' season that ended in ugly self-analysis, the catalyst
for where they are today.
</P>
<P>
   An end to the Same Old Cardinals. To a World Cup in which the
last-place, no-winning, coach-hating U.S. squad treated us to 32nd
place. To the nightmare in Nagano when some ill-tempered hockey
players tossed dignity and a few chairs out the dormitory window.
</P>
<P>
   There were profound beginnings. Like Tubby Smith and Kentucky.
The emergence of Mark O'Meara. The new Jeremy Roenick. And the
you-ain't-going-to-fool-me era of Rob Evans.
</P>
<P>
   Like Kerry Wood (Kid Whiff), Jason Kidd (All-Star) and Randy
Moss (the real MVP). And, of course, Travis Lee and Pat Tillman.
One blessed, one obsessed. Two guys who come to work on bicycles.
</P>
<P>
   There were things that wouldn't go away. Dennis Rodman. The
suddenly annoying Karl Malone. A sit-down chat with Tonya and
Nancy. Phil Luckett and other whistles of incompetence, referees
who need glasses ``and'' hearing aids. And most of all, spiraling
salaries, a year in which baseball joined basketball in awarding
one man over $100 million. The latest being Kevin Brown, who
finally relented after snagging 12 free flights and a luxury suite.
</P>
<P>
   And to symbolize it all, in light of baseball's impending crisis
came the trade of the century, the dismantling of a World Series
champion, and a Marlins' team that held on to Mike Piazza for seven
days. When asked about his experience in Miami, Piazza shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really enjoyed my time there,'' Piazza said. ``Tuesday was
very nice.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   DEFINITELY ``IN'': Jake Plummer. Travis Lee. Teppo Numminen.
Antonio McDyess.
</P>
<P>
   DEFINITELY ``OUT'': Devon White. Eric Swann. Dennis Scott. Randy
Johnson's hair style, and believe me, I know this well.
</P>
<P>
   GIVE THAT MAN A MUZZLE: Rich Dozer.
</P>
<P>
   Some things don't fit into categories.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Miller's mind-numbing personality _ she almost cheered
her team to the WNBA title. Buck Showalter's intentional walk with
the bases loaded. Bob Ferguson's spectacular vision and belly full
of charm. The lightning rod known as Pat Murphy and an ASU baseball
team that nearly climbed a mountain.
</P>
<P>
   The competitive fire of Danny Ainge, who will nonetheless take a
mulligan on his guarantee of a three-game comeback against the
Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of Larry Centers. The entertainment value of Rex
Chapman. The audio from Jeremy Roenick.
</P>
<P>
   The wit of Brian Anderson, who wondered how he could injure his
elbow during a cab ride, finally realizing that it had something to
do with ``Saving Private Ryan,'' the movie he saw later the same
night. ``So realistic it was scary,'' Anderson said. ``I figured
that some of the shrapnel must've hit me in the elbow.''
</P>
<P>
   Some things, of course, were simply too strange.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire, a broken scoreboard and a home run that sailed
through the open shutters at BOB. The porn star who showed up in
Flagstaff, along with her director who happens to be a Cardinal
groupie. The power outage at Sun Devil Stadium that only confirmed
the television trucks should've been in Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, the new blond-and-spiked hairstyle of Steve
Nash, who began to resemble a local Mercury star, so much that
Ainge saw him in the weight room over the summer and panned:
``Hello, Michelle.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's wishing that next year is half as fun. That Marv Albert
keeps his teeth clean. That Phil Mickelson wins a major. That Bobbi
Olson wins her fight with cancer.
</P>
<P>
   That 1999 won't constantly be framed party music from the artist
formerly known as Prince. And may the drama continue, with a few
less bad actors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   THE PSEUDO-LEGEND: El Duque.
</P>
<P>
   THE REAL HERO: Ryan Hines, a 12-year-old boy from Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it was a tough year for heroes. A Canadian snow boarder was
temporary stripped of his medal when his drug test was mistaken for
Bob Marley's. Upon instructions from the Lord, Reggie White
un-retired and spewed a blizzard of stereotypes in a speech for
civility. A speech intended for idiots that hate, that sounded like
it came from one.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Tyson lost his temper in front of a review board in New
Jersey, allegedly attacked a couple of motorists, and registered in
Phoenix as a sex offender.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Greene bull-rushed a coach. Evander Holyfield fathered
three children, one actually delivered by his wife. Ryan Leaf
turned out to be the first successful cloning experiment in the
NFL, except the DNA belonged to Scott Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   Humiliation at Notre Dame. Point shaving scandals everywhere. An
Olympic gymnast who sued her parents and fled from her father, who
expressed remorse by saying she should really come home and resume
her training.
</P>
<P>
   A minor-league hockey player in Phoenix was arrested and banned
for life after bludgeoning an opponent with his stick. The color of
ignorance was pink, as in bellies. And you'd better check your
mail, because Latrell Sprewell might be suing you.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing comes close to Orlando Hernandez, the pitcher we
glorified for his daring escape from Cuba. A pitcher who never
refuted the myth, that he shared a raft, fended off sharks, put his
life on the line in a perilous race for freedom. And now we hear he
crossed over on a 20-foot boat.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, but he did endure three days on a tiny island. No Gilligan,
and definitely no hero.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there were moments of inspiration. The Cubs winning one for
Harry. The tragic story of Sheldon Kennedy and his monstrous coach.
The Red Wings handing the Stanley Cup to a paralyzed Vladimir
Konstantinov. The tale of Casey Martin, who shined at the U.S.
Open, teaching golfers that there is more to life than manicured
fairways and the 19th hole. And the wonderful, horrible story of
Ryan Hines.
</P>
<P>
   He is 12 years old with a swollen, dying leg. He has Casey
Martin's disease in its worst version, but last summer, he played
in a basketball league. Despite the pain, both emotional and
physical, he fights back with optimism. He smiles and laughs, so
much that it breaks your heart.
</P>
<P>
   And two days before Christmas, this note arrived from his
mother:
</P>
<P>
   ````Wanted to keep you up to date with Ryan and his health. It
took a'' ``bad swing yesterday. A vein in his leg ruptured and now
his leg is'' ``infected. He is on serious doses of antibiotics and
bed rest, then'' ``surgery next week. His basketball days are over.
So it is pretty sad'' ``here today. My neighbor said you wrote
something on him last week. I'' ``missed it, but thanks for
thinking of Ryan as a trooper. He is one''.``''
</P>
<P>
   `` Tracy''''
</P>
<P>
   God bless you, Ryan. From all of us. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
