<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI FRUS TRATES W. VIR GINIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. _ Ever since Larry Smith was hired at Missouri in
1994, the Tigers' football fortunes have been taking a steady climb
up.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri and Smith can now add a bowl victory to the dramatic
turnaround this program has taken during the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers held off a furious and inspired comeback by West
Virginia to beat the Mountaineers, 34-31, in the 10th Insight.com
Bowl game Saturday night at a half-empty Arizona Stadium, where the
announced crowd was 36,147.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not one to ever sit and rest on my laurels,'' said Smith,
who successfully returned to the city where he turned the
University of Arizona into winners. ```But it's obvious that a
program must think it's a winner before it can win consistently.
Still, you have to turn the corner every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Missouri's players believe they have finally reached a point
where the Tigers' program won't necessarily be on auto-pilot, but
the foundation for consistent winning has definitely been laid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most definitely this program has to be taken seriously now,''
said senior Devin West, Missouri's first All-American at any
position since 1986 and first All-America running back since Bob
Steuber in 1942. ``I'm not sure about the younger players, but I
know the juniors here now are mentally ready to take the next
step.''
</P>
<P>
   That step, according to Smith, is a Big 12 Conference
championship. Missouri last won a conference title when the 1969
team finished in a tie for the then-Big 8 championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We up our goals every year,'' Smith said. ``We wanted to
improve our record and win a bowl game this year, no matter what
the bowl game. We did both of those things.''
</P>
<P>
   Missouri's victory capped the Tigers first eight-victory season
since the 1981 team also finished 8-4. West Virginia has now lost
an NCAA-record eight consecutive bowl games _ all under its most
successful coach, Don Nehlen _ breaking a tie it had held with
Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   West Virginia's last bowl victory came in the now-defunct
Bluebonnet Bowl in 1984 when the Mountaineers beat up on Texas
Christian, 31-14. Missouri hadn't won a bowl game since beating
Southern Mississippi, 19-17, in the 1981 Tangerine (now the Citrus)
Bowl. But the Tigers were appearing in just their third bowl game
since that victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of frustration because we really wanted it for
the seniors and for Coach Nehlen,'' said West Virginia receiver
David Saunders. ``We didn't talk about the streak too much, but we
knew it was there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mountaineers, who took the opening kickoff and drove down
the field with relative ease, started the game looking as though
their infamous streak would finally die.
</P>
<P>
   They successfully blended six running plays with five passes
during the 5 minute, 43 second drive, but Jay Taylor's 40-yard
field goal attempt was low and easily blocked by Jeff Marriott's
outstretched hands. Junior cornerback Carlos Posey scooped up the
bouncing ball and returned it 70 yards for the game's first score.
Posey was never touched during the return.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri eventually built a 24-3 halftime lead and appeared
headed toward an easy victory. But the Mountaineers emerged from
the halftime locker room ready to scale the 21-point deficit.
</P>
<P>
   West Virginia quarterback Marc Bulger, the game's offensive most
valuable player, moved the Mountaineers from their 27 to Missouri's
5 before a fourth down pass to Khori Ivy was broken up by Harold
Piersey, killing the drive but not West Virginia's determination.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers watched the Mountaineers comeback, which saw
Missouri's lead cut to 31-24 with 10:27 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri's offense then put a wide smile on Smith's face when
the Tigers took nearly seven minutes off the clock on a
time-consuming drive that culminated with an 18-yard field goal.
The Tigers ran 13 plays during the drive, all of them runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love that kind of football,'' Smith said. ``That would have
made Woody Hayes proud, there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mountaineers managed to drive down the field and score a
touchdown. West Virginia, however, could not get a hold of the
ensuing onside kickoff and Missouri ran out the clock to end the
game. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
