<SLUG> BC-FBC-INSIGHT-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI BACKUP GETS CHANCE, CAPTURES MVP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. - Two days earlier, sophomore  &UR; Julian Jones was
preparing for his usual role as Missouri's best special-teams
player.
</P>
<P>
   This morning he awakes as the Most Valuable Player of Saturday
night's Insight.com Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   In a strange twist of events, Jones went from a backup
cornerback to being thrust into the starting defensive secondary
after first-string cornerback
 &UR; Wade Perkins was suspended for his final game because he broke an
undisclosed team rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was waiting all year for my chance,'' Jones said. ``I wanted
to take advantage of it if it ever came.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, making his first collegiate start, played the game of his
life. He had an interception, blocked a punt, broke up a handful of
passes and returned three kicks for 72 yards, including a 39-yard
kickoff return in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the MVP?'' Missouri Coach  &UR; Larry Smith asked. ``He should
be. He played a heck of a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Perkins, a senior, was a second-team All-Big 12 selection. He
was sent home to Las Vegas on Christmas Eve by Smith, known as a
stickler for rules. &QL; 
Insight-ful record
</P>
<P>
   By most accounts, the biggest reason for the sparse crowd at the
10th Insight.com Bowl was being locked into a Dec. 26 game.
</P>
<P>
   Insight officials conceded this year's game was a tough sell
because the day after Christmas is a difficult time to get many
fans to travel to watch a bowl game.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri fans bought about 3,000 tickets, while West Virginia's
fans bought around 2,000. An amended figure of 36,147 was announced
more than 30 minutes after an initial report of 33,888. The actual
attendance, by most estimates, was somewhere near 30,000.
</P>
<P>
   This was the second-smallest attendance in the history of the
bowl, formerly known as the Copper Bowl. The previous low was set
on Dec. 31, 1991, when 35,751 showed up to watch Indiana beat
Baylor, 24-0. &QL; 
A time for reflecting
</P>
<P>
   With 57 seconds remaining in the first half and Missouri at West
Virginia's 2-yard line, the Tigers took a timeout. Then West
Virginia took a timeout. And then another, to make it three
straight timeouts without a play taking place.
</P>
<P>
   The Mountaineers didn't adjust enough during their back-to-back
timeouts as Missouri quarterback  &UR; Corby Jones then ran in for his
second touchdown of the game on an option play. &QL; 
Before the extra point, Missouri took another timeout, decided to
go for a two-point conversion that gave the Tigers a 24-3 lead. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
