<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-VOLS-ARRIVE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENNESSEE ENDS BREAK, TOUCHES DOWN IN VALLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - They arrived earlier than usual for a bowl game, but
nobody is faulting the Tennessee Volunteers for being eager to get
here.
</P>
<P>
   Only a national championship is at stake.
</P>
<P>
   The Volunteers, who came to Phoenix from different parts of the
country Saturday after spending Christmas with their families, go
back to work today at Scottsdale Community College in preparation
for the Jan. 4 Fiesta Bowl against Florida State at Sun Devil
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   No. 2 Florida State (11-1) arrives today and begins workouts
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to let them go for Christmas to have some time, but
we told them we want to get back to work,'' Coach Phillip Fulmer
said. ``I didn't want to make them stay out a lot longer than we
did.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer, who arrived on a charter plane Saturday evening with his
family and a large Tennessee group, didn't let up too much before
Christmas, as the weather turned cold in Knoxville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer said his team had nine practices, including four days of
two-a-days, before taking a break.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were short, crisp practices,'' he said. ``We got a lot
out of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the 12-0 record and top ranking, Tennessee comes here,
in some people's eyes, an underdog.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an unusual role for our team,'' Fulmer said. ``This
team has responded to those kinds of challenges, and I would hope
that they will respond again.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida State has been in these scenarios under Coach Bobby
Bowden with the national title on the line before. The Seminoles
won the national championship after beating Nebraska in the 1994
Orange Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee, which got rocked by Nebraska, 42-17, in last year's
Orange Bowl, has its first 12-win season in school history. The
Volunteers did it despite having to replace players at key
positions, including quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   There were close calls along the way. A season-opening 34-33
victory over Syracuse, followed by a 20-17 overtime win over
Florida _ both decided by Jeff Hall's foot. A 28-24 win over
Arkansas, thanks to a Razorbacks fumble in the last two minutes.
And a 24-14 victory over Mississippi that put the Volunteers in the
BCS national championship game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go find a national championship game that has two teams
playing in it that weren't a little fortunate along the way,''
Fulmer said.
</P>
<P>
   They want to make more history.
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer believes the BCS works and that the two best teams in
America will be playing Jan. 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're glad to be part of a history-making game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer has talked to his team about the Super Bowl-like hype
that will surround the game. He doesn't feel it will be a
distraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been ranked first for six straight weeks, so we're not
unaccustomed to dealing with the media and the hype,'' he said. ``I
think our experience from last year, playing against Nebraska,
helps. I think our players are very adept at handling this. They'll
do fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer said he'll let the players enjoy the week's festivities,
but he wants to make sure football is the focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not your typical reward, go to a bowl game and have a
good time,'' he said. ``We're one of only two schools in the whole
country with this opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure our focus is good, that our preparation
and concentration are good, that we eat well, we rest well as we
approach the bowl game.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-98 0303EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
