<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Jan. 3) 
(lb) 
 By SCOTT VEALE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; CIRCUMNAVIGATION &LR;  By Steve Lattimore. Houghton Mifflin, $12.
The author's first collection of short stories is populated by
disaffected Californians stuck with menial jobs, empty lives and
dead-end relationships. In 1997 the New York Times reviewer Scott
Bradfield called this a ``funny, moving book'' that in its best
moments is ``about the various jangled ways in which broken
families manage to operate.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SLAVES IN THE FAMILY &LR;  By Edward Ball. Ballantine, $15.95.
Searching for the descendants of slaves owned by his ancestors in
South Carolina, the author confronts his heritage and the moral
consequences of slavery. His account, which won a National Book
Award last year, took him across America and to Africa, and
involved extensive interviews and research. ``There is much to
admire in Ball's very willingness to challenge the generations of
silence in his white family and to search out black kin whose
reactions he had every reason to fear,'' Drew Gilpin Faust wrote in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TO 'JOY MY FREEDOM: SOUTHERN BLACK WOMEN'S LIVES AND LABORS
AFTER THE CIVIL WAR &LR;  By Tera W. Hunter. Harvard University, $15.95.
A history professor explores the valuable political and social role
played by black women after Emancipation. In 1997 the same reviewer
called this a ``celebration of struggle and resistance.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE COCKROACH BASKETBALL LEAGUE &LR;  By Charley Rosen. Seven
Stories, $13.95. This hymn to minor-league basketball follows a
team of misfits and whining wannabes as they ply their trade in the
shadow of the big time. The result is ``a racily entertaining
novel'' that ``skillfully induces the reader to join `the
Brotherhood of the Sacred Hoop,''' Michael Anderson wrote in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GEORGE ELIOT: A LIFE &LR;  By Rosemary Ashton. Penguin, $15.95. This
revisionist biography combines the social context of Eliot's
fiction and a detailed analysis of her novels. ``Ashton is a
serious, persistent scholar, and the picture she gives of Eliot's
intellectual and emotional life is convincing,'' William S.
Peterson wrote in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JANE AUSTEN: A LIFE &LR;  By David Nokes. University of California,
$19.95. This reveals how the novelist wielded irony and razor-sharp
observation as weapons to skewer the constraining society in which
she lived. In 1997 the reviewer Claude Rawson praised the author
for leaning heavily on Austen's letters, which ``are wonderfully
revealing, especially strong on the texture of relationships and
the tang of social encounters.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PRINCE OF PEACE &LR;  By James Carroll. Mariner/Houghton Mifflin,
$13. This densely plotted novel tells the parallel tales of an
American priest who gets caught up in the anti-Vietnam War movement
and what is portrayed as the metamorphosis of the Roman Catholic
Church in the United States into a cynically run corporation. ``The
stories are nearly irresistible,'' Webster Schott wrote in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ASPHALT NATION: HOW THE AUTOMOBILE TOOK OVER AMERICA, AND HOW
WE CAN TAKE IT BACK &LR;  By Jane Holtz Kay. University of California,
$16.95. In this cranky polemic, an architecture critic describes
how unchecked motorized sprawl is threatening the nation's cities
and towns, its economy and its health. She ``largely succeeds in
proving that it is possible to get where we are going without
destroying where we live,'' Kenneth T. Jackson wrote in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EATING CHINESE FOOD NAKED &LR;  By Mei Ng. Washington Square/Pocket
Books, $14. Ruby Lee is a restless college graduate whose
protective love for her mother draws her back to her father's
laundry in Queens. Last year the reviewer Lynn Karpen called this
an ``affecting first novel'' that ``conveys the complexities of
family life with vibrant color and luminosity.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOBBY REX'S GREATEST HIT &LR;  By Marianne Gingher. Louisiana State
University, $14.95. It's 1961 in Greensboro, N.C., and Pally
Thompson is about to marry a man who wants to know how far she went
with a local country-music crooner whose hit song is all about his
romance with her. This ``richly detailed, often charming first
novel ... lovingly evokes Pally's journey from innocence to
maturity in a town where gossip flourishes and ambitions fade,''
Ellen Pall wrote in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CITIZEN SOLDIERS: THE U.S. ARMY FROM THE NORMANDY BEACHES TO
THE BULGE TO THE SURRENDER OF GERMANY. JUNE 7, 1944-MAY 7, 1945 &LR;  By
Stephen E. Ambrose. Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $16. In this
sequel to ``D-Day,'' the author's 1994 best seller about the
Normandy landing, he once again uses the experiences of ordinary
soldiers to recreate the bloody, often nameless battles that led to
the Nazi defeat. ```Citizen Soldiers' is an unforgettable testament
to the World War II generation,'' Carlo D'Este wrote in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GOD'S SNAKE &LR;  By Irini Spanidou. Vintage International, $13. A
girl chronicles her anguished coming of age in Greece in the 1950s
as the daughter of an inflexible military officer who treats her as
if she were one of his recruits. This first novel ``freshly evokes
the beauties and terrors of childhood,'' Nicholas Bromell wrote in
1986.
</P>
</TEXT>
