<HEADLINE>
BEST SELLERS: PAPERBACK BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
 (For release on Sunday, Jan. 03.) 
(Eds: This file is the abbreviated best-seller list for paperback
books. Please see BESTSELLERS-PAPER-L-NYT for the full version that
includes how many weeks each book has been on the list.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rankings reflect sales figures for the week ending Dec. 19,
1998, at almost 4,000 bookstores plus wholesalers serving 60,000
other retailers, statistically weighted to represent sales in all
such outlets nationwide. The number of titles within the two
subdivisions of nonfiction can change from week to week, reflecting
changes in book buying.
</P>
<P>
   An (x) following a book's ranking indicates that a book's sales
are barely distinguishable from those of the book above. A (b)
indicates that some bookstores report receiving bulk orders for a
book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. INNER HARBOR, by Nora Roberts. (Jove, $7.50.)
</P>
<P>
   The final volume of a trilogy about three brothers
</P>
<P>
   contending with a crisis in their family's life.
</P>
<P>
   2. WHERE THE HEART IS, by Billie Letts. (Warner, $12.)
</P>
<P>
   A pregnant teen-ager, left stranded in a small
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma town, finds help and caring from its
</P>
<P>
   inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
   3. FEAR NOTHING, by Dean Koontz. (Bantam, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A man whose health forces him to live at night
</P>
<P>
   witnesses mysteries only he can solve.
</P>
<P>
   4. DIVINE SECRETS OF THE YA-YA SISTERHOOD,
</P>
<P>
   by Rebecca Wells (Harper Perennial, $13.50.) Three
</P>
<P>
   generations of Southern women.
</P>
<P>
   5. MIDWIVES, by Chris Bohjalian. (Vintage, $13.)
</P>
<P>
   Trouble, legal and moral, haunts a midwife who may have
</P>
<P>
   killed a woman while trying to save the baby's life.
</P>
<P>
   6. THE GHOST, by Danielle Steel. (Dell, $7.50.) On a
</P>
<P>
   trip to New England, a troubled man finds answers to
</P>
<P>
   his problems in diaries in an old trunk.
</P>
<P>
   7. COLD MOUNTAIN, by Charles Frazier. (Vintage, $13.)
</P>
<P>
   A wounded Confederate soldier journeys home toward
</P>
<P>
   the end of the Civil War to meet an old love and a
</P>
<P>
   new world.
</P>
<P>
   8. TOM CLANCY'S POWER PLAYS: RUTHLESS.COM, created by
</P>
<P>
   Tom Clancy and Martin Greenberg. (Berkley, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   America is imperiled by computer-based terrorism
</P>
<P>
   in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   9. THE WINNER, by David Baldacci. (Warner Vision, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   The tribulations of a poor woman who participates in a scam
</P>
<P>
   to win the lottery.
</P>
<P>
   10. SWEET ANGER, by Sandra Brown. (Warner, $6.50.) A
</P>
<P>
   television newscaster is obsessed with the man who
</P>
<P>
   shattered her late husband's life.
</P>
<P>
   11. SURVIVAL OF THE FITTEST, by Jonathan Kellerman.
</P>
<P>
   (Bantam, $7.50.) Alex Delaware pursues the killer
</P>
<P>
   of a diplomat's daughter.
</P>
<P>
   12. NUMBERED ACCOUNT, by Christopher Reich. (Dell, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A young man joins the Swiss banking world in an effort to
</P>
<P>
   find his father's murderer.
</P>
<P>
   13. LITTLE ALTARS EVERYWHERE, by Rebecca Wells. (Harper
</P>
<P>
   Perennial, $13.) An account of earlier experiences of the
</P>
<P>
   Ya-Ya sisterhood.
</P>
<P>
   14. CAT &AMP; MOUSE, by James Patterson. (Warner, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Alex Cross contends with two serial killers
</P>
<P>
   determined to take his life.
</P>
<P>
   15. THE NOTEBOOK, by Nicholas Sparks. (Warner Vision,
</P>
<P>
   $5.99.) A World War II veteran meets an old flame who
</P>
<P>
   is about to be married.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NON-FICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. THE SEAT OF THE SOUL, by Gary Zukav.
</P>
<P>
   (Fireside/S&AMP;S, $12.) How daily activities can
</P>
<P>
   be enhanced by feelings of meaning and purpose.
</P>
<P>
   2. THE PERFECT STORM, by Sebastian Junger.
</P>
<P>
   (Harper Paperbacks, $6.99.) The story of the
</P>
<P>
   nor'easter of 1991, focusing on a crew of
</P>
<P>
   fishermen from Gloucester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   3. INTO THIN AIR, by Jon Krakauer. (Anchor/Doubleday, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Ascending Mount Everest in 1996, the deadliest season in
</P>
<P>
   history.
</P>
<P>
   4.(x) THE MAN WHO LISTENS TO HORSES, by Monty Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   (Ballantine, $7.99.) The memoirs of a professional
</P>
<P>
   horse trainer.
</P>
<P>
   5. A CIVIL ACTION, by Jonathan Harr. (Vintage, $14)
</P>
<P>
   A lawsuit brought by Massachusetts householders
</P>
<P>
   against industrial polluters. (b)
</P>
<P>
   6. 'N SYNC: The Official Book, by 'N Sync with
</P>
<P>
   K.M. Squires. (Dell, $9.95.) A profusely
</P>
<P>
   illustrated account of the pop group.
</P>
<P>
   7.(x) THE MILLIONAIRE NEXT DOOR, by Thomas J. Stanley
</P>
<P>
   and William D. Danko. (Pocket, $14.) An analysis
</P>
<P>
   of the lives of wealthy Americans. (b)
</P>
<P>
   8. CITIZEN SOLDIERS, by Stephen E. Ambrose.
</P>
<P>
   (Touchstone/S&AMP;S, $16.) The U.S. Army, from Normandy
</P>
<P>
   to Germany's surrender.
</P>
<P>
   9. UNDAUNTED COURAGE, by Stephen E. Ambrose.
</P>
<P>
   (Touchstone/S&AMP;S, $16.) Lewis and Clark's
</P>
<P>
   exploration of the West. (b)
</P>
<P>
   10. UNDER THE TUSCAN SUN, by Frances Mayes.
</P>
<P>
   (Broadway, $13.) A celebration of life in the
</P>
<P>
   Italian countryside.
</P>
<P>
   11. INTO THE WILD, by Jon Krakauer.
</P>
<P>
   (Anchor/Doubleday, $12.95.) How a young man's
</P>
<P>
   obsession with the wilderness had a tragic end
</P>
<P>
   in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   12.(x) THE END OF THE DREAM, by Ann Rule. (Pocket, $7.99)
</P>
<P>
   Four true crime cases in which people's dreams were
</P>
<P>
   destroyed by acts of violence.
</P>
<P>
   13. 'N SYNC: Tearin' Up the Charts, by Matt Netter.
</P>
<P>
   (Pocket, $4.99.) The story of the pop group.
</P>
<P>
   14. ADVENTURES OF A PSYCHIC, by Sylvia Browne and
</P>
<P>
   Antoinette May. (Hay House, $12.95.) A psychic
</P>
<P>
   tells her life story.
</P>
<P>
   15. THE VIRTUES OF AGING, by Jimmy Carter.
</P>
<P>
   (Library of Contemporary Thought/Ballantine, $9.95.)
</P>
<P>
   Reflections on the problems and rewarding
</P>
<P>
   opportunities of old age by the former president. (b)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ADVICE, HOW-TO, AND MISCELLANEOUS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. CHICKEN SOUP FOR THE TEENAGE SOUL II, compiled by Jack
</P>
<P>
   Canfield, Mark Victor Hansen and Kimberly Kirberger.
</P>
<P>
   (Health Communications, $12.95.) Inspirational stories. (b)
</P>
<P>
   2. DON'T SWEAT THE SMALL STUFF ... AND IT'S ALL SMALL STUFF,
</P>
<P>
   by Richard Carlson. (Hyperion, $10.95.) How to enjoy life
</P>
<P>
   more and contribute to the world we live in. (b)
</P>
<P>
   3. CHICKEN SOUP FOR THE TEENAGE SOUL, compiled by Jack
</P>
<P>
   Canfield, Mark Victor Hansen and Kimberly Kirberger. (Health
</P>
<P>
   Communications, $12.95.) Inspiration. (b)
</P>
<P>
   4. A SECOND CHICKEN SOUP FOR THE WOMAN'S SOUL,
</P>
<P>
   compiled by Jack Canfield et al.
</P>
<P>
   (Health Communications, $12.95.) Inspiration. (b)
</P>
