<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATL-FBC-FIESTA28 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vols-FSU a clash of destinies
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ There are a number of very good reasons why No. 1
Tennessee feels it will beat No. 2 Florida State in the Fiesta Bowl
and win its first national championship since 1951. But the most
compelling reason, say the Volunteer players, has nothing to do
with offense, defense or kicking.
</P>
<P>
   Some are calling it Fate. Others are calling it Destiny. Still
others can't put a name to it. They just know how they feel. After
everything Tennessee has overcome this season to go 12-0 and reach
the national championship game, they simply believe _ right down to
the core of their Big Orange soul _ that it is meant to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I believe in destiny. I believe in it a lot,'' said
Tennessee linebacker Al Wilson, who arrived here with his teammates
on Dec. 26 to get ready for the Jan. 4 game. ``If you've watched
this team since last spring and summer, when we were pushing each
other in the weight room, you'd understand why we think this team
is special. We think we were meant to be here and win this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Even coach Phillip Fulmer, who is not prone to overstatement,
believes this a special team. Because of the adversity it has
survived, the whole, Fulmer says, is greater then the sum of its
parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them in the spring that we didn't have to be the best
team in the country,'' said Fulmer. ``We just had to be the best
team on the 12 or 13 days that we played. And that is exactly what
this team has done. They have always gotten the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee began this season without the greatest quarterback in
its history, Peyton Manning.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Vols found a way to win:
</P>
<P>
   _ Jeff Hall kicked a 27-yard field goal as time expired to give
Tennessee a 34-33 win at Syracuse in the opener. The Vols drove the
length of the field to set up the winning score.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hall's 41-yard field goal in overtime beat Florida 20-17,
snapping a five-game losing streak to the Gators.
</P>
<P>
   Then, four weeks into the 1998 campaign, the Volunteers lost
their best offensive player, running back Jamal Lewis, to a knee
injury. The Vols kept winning:
</P>
<P>
   _ In their first game without Lewis, the Volunteers went on the
road and dominated No. 7 Georgia, 22-3. The defense held Georgia to
59 yards rushing.
</P>
<P>
   _ When Arkansas quarterback Clint Stoerner fumbled with less
than two minutes left, Tennessee drove and scored a touchdown with
28 seconds remaining to beat the Razorbacks 28-24.
</P>
<P>
   _ Trailing 14-10 to Mississippi State with 8:43 to go,
quarterback Tee Martin threw touchdown passes for 41 and 26 yards
to beat the Bulldogs 24-14 in the SEC championship game.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much stuff has happened to this team but we never quit,''
said wide receiver Peerless Price. ``We always believe we're going
to win. We still believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   But wait a minute, said Florida State coach Bobby Bowden, who
thinks his No. 2 Seminoles have a little destiny on their side as
well.
</P>
<P>
   What else do you call it when a team gets embarrassed on Sept.
12 (with a 24-7 loss to N.C. State) and almost four months later is
playing for all the marbles?
</P>
<P>
   What else do you call it when a team loses its quarterback
(Chris Weinke, neck injury) on Nov. 7, but is still favored against
the No. 1 team in the land?
</P>
<P>
   And what else do you call it when you're ranked No. 4 on the
last day of the regular season, and both No. 2 (Kansas State) and
No. 3 (UCLA) are upset?
</P>
<P>
   ``When we lost to N.C. State I figured it we had no shot of
getting back into this thing,'' said Bowden, who is 16-4-1 in bowl
games and 2-0 in the Fiesta Bowl. ``But I remembered what happened
to Florida in 1996. I told our guys `let's keep winning so we'll be
there in case an opportunity presents itself.' And that's exactly
what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Florida lost its regular-season finale to Florida State
but got into position to win the national title due to a series of
upsets.
</P>
<P>
   After the loss to N.C. State, Florida State proceeded to win 10
straight games against the nation's No. 4-rated schedule. The
Seminoles had not played since Nov. 21 when Kansas State and UCLA
lost on Dec. 5. Bowden went to bed that Saturday night knowing he
was about to be given an unexpected Christmas gift.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get an opportunity like this, something this
unexpected, you really want to take advantage of it,'' said Bowden,
whose only national title came in 1993. ``But it feels like we were
meant to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
