<HEADER>
A7543 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POOR-PAY-INSURANCE28-     12-27 1678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POOR-PAY-INSURANCE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Austin's poor pay more for insurance
 &HT;    By Juan B. Elizondo Jr.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Vehicles owned by people in poorer parts of
Austin are twice as likely as those in more affluent areas to be
covered by higher-cost auto insurance, even though there's little
evidence that lower-income people are worse drivers,
American-Statesman research has found.
</P>
<P>
   Companies selling those higher-priced policies also appear to be
gaining market share in more affluent parts of the city, the
research shows.
</P>
<P>
   Those companies, called county mutuals, generally sell insurance
to people with poor driving records. Their rates are not regulated
by the state. So-called standard and preferred companies, whose
rates are regulated, generally sell lower-cost policies to better
drivers.
</P>
<P>
   On average, county mutual policies in 1997 cost $1,300 for a
year's coverage, $500 more than those offered by preferred and
standard companies, according to the Texas Department of Insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Insurers and their representatives strongly deny any deliberate
tie between their customers' income and the policies and prices
they are offered. They say the findings might boil down to a simple
coincidence that people in lower- and moderate-income areas more
often have less-than-perfect driving records.
</P>
<P>
   ``That seems to be where the people with the most tickets and
accidents happen to live,'' said Jerry Johns, president of
Southwestern Insurance Information Service, an industry trade
group.
</P>
<P>
   But Birny Birnbaum, an insurance data analyst who has conducted
similar research, says it's unlikely that the difference between
the number of county mutual policies sold in low-income areas and
those sold in more affluent areas happens by chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``These results are not random,'' Birnbaum said. ``There is a
clear and statistically powerful relationship between the
availability of standard coverage and where you live. Whether it is
intentional or unintentional, it has the same result, which is to
systematically deny standard, low-cost coverage to those who most
need it.''
</P>
<P>
   Like consumer advocates, Southeast Austin resident Jack Straube
believes there might be some intentional discrimination based on
people's income and where they live. Straube thought he was getting
a good rate from his insurer, a small county mutual, before finding
out that he could do better.
</P>
<P>
   Insurers say they do their best to give good rates to good
drivers. At the same time, companies refuse to release information
about their sales and cancellations. They contend that if insurers
knew each other's strategies and sales, competition would be
compromised, ultimately hurting consumers. Research results The
American-Statesman's study relied on industrywide insurance sales
records, which are public. Overall, the research showed that in the
ZIP codes with the lowest median after-tax household income, county
mutuals provided liability coverage on almost 33 percent of the
insured vehicles. In the ZIP codes with the highest median incomes,
they covered 16 percent of the insured vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The disparity was even more striking when individual ZIP codes
were examined.
</P>
<P>
   For example, from January to March of this year, county mutuals
covered 121 of every 1,000 insured vehicles in the 78730 ZIP code.
Residents in that part of Northwest Austin and western Travis
County have a median disposable household income of $83,653
annually, among the area's highest, according to 1998 data.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, county mutuals provided liability insurance to
410 of every 1,000 insured vehicles in the 78741 ZIP code in
Southeast Austin, where the median income of $19,043 is among the
city's lowest.
</P>
<P>
   Liability insurance is the only coverage all Texas drivers are
required to purchase.
</P>
<P>
   The often high cost of liability insurance in low-income areas,
which prices some drivers out of the market, should be a concern
for all drivers, consumer advocates say. That's because as many as
one in four drivers doesn't carry liability insurance, according to
estimates from the Department of Insurance.
</P>
<P>
   That means drivers with insurance face higher costs to protect
themselves from under-insured and uninsured drivers.
</P>
<P>
   The Statesman's study also found another concern for drivers in
more affluent areas: County mutuals' share of vehicles throughout
the city grew from the first quarter of 1996 to the same period in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   In the 78730 ZIP code, for example, county mutuals increased
their market share of liability policies from 87 to 121 vehicles
per 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   In the 78741 ZIP code, county mutuals' liability coverage
increased from 308 to 410 vehicles per 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   The apparent growth of county mutual sales could be skewed by a
recent change at USAA insurance. In late 1995 and 1996, the company
moved many of its customers into its county mutual; it said the
reason was to have more flexibility in setting rates. Most of the
people who were shifted continued to get low rates, the company
said, adding that for some, costs dropped.
</P>
<P>
   The company would not release information that would make more
clear what effect its shift of customers had on the overall growth
of county mutuals. Case for county mutuals At Farmers Insurance,
spokesman Mark Toohey said that without exception, its county
mutual insures drivers with tickets and wrecks. They are charged a
higher price because they are more likely to cause more wrecks and
get more tickets, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only litmus test for our county mutual is whether the
driver has a bad driving record,'' Toohey said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that despite the Statesman's findings, Farmers'
preferred company has grown in the past two years. Farmers' county
mutual has fewer customers now than it had in 1996, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Toohey could not say, however, what share of Farmers' county
mutual policies are sold in low- and moderate-income areas and how
that compares with the number of policies sold in more affluent
areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't have that information,'' he said of income data.
``We wouldn't care about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Farmers and other companies do ask customers about their income.
But Toohey and other industry officials said it is not to determine
rates. In many cases, the information is used to determine whether
a customer will be offered a payment plan.
</P>
<P>
   For years, county mutual companies have been the primary
insurers for people who have wrecks and tickets on their record.
Among other things, insurance companies look at Department of
Public Safety records three years back for such problems and
consider the number and severity of wrecks and tickets when
determining the risk a driver poses.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Schneider, a senior policy analyst for Consumers Union, said
that when used properly _ only to insure bad drivers _ county
mutuals play an important role in keeping good drivers from paying
higher rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who have had a lot of wrecks or a DWI ought to pay
according to the risk they pose,'' Schneider said. ``People who
have good driving records don't deserve to pay more for
insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   But consumer advocates say they believe lower-priced insurers
are using county mutuals to dump drivers they don't want, such as
the poor and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, insurers say.
</P>
<P>
   Johns, of Southwestern Insurance Information Service, said
response to the state's Market Assistance Program provides evidence
that low-income and minority Texans don't experience illegal
discrimination. The Texas Department of Insurance program helps
connect good drivers in underserved ZIP codes with companies that
offer better rates. The department defines underserved areas as
those where a disproportionate number of drivers are insured by
county mutuals or the Texas Automobile Insurance Plan, a program
for the worst drivers.
</P>
<P>
   As of Dec. 7, the Department of Insurance said 1,594 Texans had
sought help from the Market Assistance Program, which began in July
in parts of Austin, El Paso and the Rio Grande Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Insurance critics say there are auto insurance availability
problems in Texas, but the poor response to the MAP would indicate
otherwise,'' Johns said. ``For a very small number of Texas
drivers, the MAP is working. But for the majority of people, they
seem well-satisfied with their insurance company.'' Good drivers,
bad rates Straube, a carpenter who lives in the 78741 ZIP code in
Southeast Austin, was not one of those satisfied customers. News
accounts of the Market Assistance Program prompted him to look for
a better rate.
</P>
<P>
   Straube, 53, hasn't had a wreck or gotten a ticket in more than
three years, a standard mark of a good driver.
</P>
<P>
   He was with his last insurance company, Home State County
Mutual, for several years. After shopping around, he found that the
Farm Bureau was able to cut his rate by more than half, from $77 a
month to about $33.
</P>
<P>
   Before switching, Straube initially chose his insurer from the
phone book. He reasoned that agencies and companies with prominent
advertising in the phone book and located in his neighborhood
offered better rates than larger, national companies, Straube said.
</P>
<P>
   A look at Austin's phone book found that many of the most
prominent insurance ads are from independent agencies that
primarily sell county mutual policies.
</P>
<P>
   Straube believes questions about income and where customers live
shouldn't be asked before rates are determined.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see why your income or where you live has anything to
do with your driving record,'' he said. ``They need your ZIP code
to communicate with you, but to give you a rate, they don't need
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Straube encourages others to use the Market Assistance Program
and says laws should be changed to ensure that good drivers get
good rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``They shouldn't be able to determine what a person pays because
of their income or their color or anything,'' Straube said of
insurers. ``It should be determined on your driving record.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
