   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-RELIGION _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Charismatic and
evangelical Christians have become some of the most active
preachers of Y2K awareness and preparedness over the past year.
Christian Internet sites, publications, radio and TV programs,
televangelist videos, seminars and sermons have exploded with Y2K
messages ranging from practical preparedness tips to
apocalypticism. We take a look at some of the trends. (Bennett,
Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   POOR-PAY-INSURANCE _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Vehicles owned by people in
poorer parts of Austin are twice as likely as those in more
affluent areas to be covered by higher-cost auto insurance, even
though there's little evidence that lower-income people are worse
drivers, American-Statesman research has found. (Elizondo, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   KENNEDY-HONORS _ WASHINGTON _ Attire for the Kennedy Center
Honors is always unflinchingly formal, so Willie Nelson arrived in
a spiffy black cowboy hat, shined black boots and black velvet
binding the ends of his braided reddish-gray hair. Along with
Nelson, the Kennedy Center's 21st annual recognition for lifetime
achievement in the performing arts went to Bill Cosby, Shirley
Temple Black, conductor Andre Previn and Broadway composer John
Kander and lyricist Fred Ebb. The star-studded salute to the
honorees was videotaped Dec. 6 and will be broadcast on the CBS
television network on Wednesday (Dec. 30) at 9 p.m. EST. (Dart, Cox
News Service) MOVED Monday, Dec. 21 in (w) Washington and (e)
entertainment categories for release Monday, Dec. 28.
</P>
