<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981227.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-27 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7545 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-RELIGION28-COX     12-27 1824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-RELIGION28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Religious see spiritual omens in predictions
 &HT;    By George Bennett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ At the front of the pulpit at Christian
Family Church in Stuart, the Rev. Scott Scheer displays a digital
clock that counts down the days, hours, minutes and seconds until
Jan. 1, 2000, arrives.
</P>
<P>
   Scheer sees spiritual significance in the warnings of secular
prophets who say the year 2000 computer problem _ also called Y2K
or the millennium bug _ could wreak worldwide chaos by disrupting
utilities, communications, commerce, financial institutions and
governments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely we believe it's going to be a trying time and a
testing time,'' says Scheer, whose charismatic congregation has
about 300 members.
</P>
<P>
   It will be a time when more people seek God, he says.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe, Scheer says, the millennium bug is a harbinger of the
tribulation period he believes will precede the return of Jesus
Christ.
</P>
<P>
   Scheer and other charismatic and evangelical Christians have
become some of the most active preachers of Y2K awareness and
preparedness over the past year. Christian Internet sites,
publications, radio and TV programs, televangelist videos, seminars
and sermons have exploded with Y2K messages ranging from practical
preparedness tips to apocalypticism.
</P>
<P>
   But as Pat Robertson, Jerry Falwell, James Dobson and other
Christian broadcasters spread the Y2K word to millions, secular
veterans of the Y2K circuit have mixed feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Early Y2K alarmist Peter de Jager, who for years was a voice in
the wilderness bemoaning the public's lack of attention to the
problem, now says he's ``very, very nervous'' that Christian
doomsayers will help create unwarranted panic.
</P>
<P>
   Since writing the seminal ``Doomsday 2000'' article in
Computerworld magazine in 1993, de Jager is accustomed to being
branded a scaremonger. But when he appeared at an October Y2K
conference sponsored by Robertson's Christian Broadcasting Network,
his views weren't dire enough for many attendees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Folks have been sold on the idea that this is the end of the
world,'' says de Jager, who does believe Y2K will bring four to six
weeks of worldwide disruptions. ``This is the first audience I've
been in where I was considered a Pollyanna.''
</P>
<P>
   But others say Christian outlets have played a valuable role in
raising awareness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very, very little of what I see is the hard-line, apocalyptic,
end-of-the-world message,'' says Ed Yourdon, who says he has done
as many as 100 interviews with Christian radio and TV programs
while plugging his book Time Bomb 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Jump-started groups
</P>
<P>
   Paloma O'Reilly, founder of a secular Y2K preparedness
information clearinghouse called the Cassandra Project, said she
reluctantly appeared on Robertson's 700 Club when it did a
millennium bug special in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad I did. I can tell you that jump-started a lot of
groups,'' O'Reilly said. ``I know every time they show it (again)
because the numbers jump on the Web site.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson, who regularly features millennium bug news on CBN and
its Internet site, doesn't believe Y2K fits into biblical
end-of-the-world prophecy, a CBN spokeswoman said. He and Christian
groups like Joseph Project 2000 have said the hardships the
millennium bug might cause should be viewed by Christians as an
opportunity to minister to others and spread the gospel.
</P>
<P>
   The year 2000 problem is the notorious programming blind spot
that makes many computers unable to handle the change from 1999 to
2000. Because years are traditionally entered only by their last
two digits, the rollover from 99 to 00 will cause many computers
that haven't been reprogrammed to assume it's 1900 and either shut
down or produce bad information.
</P>
<P>
   Governments and businesses are spending billions of dollars to
address Y2K, but there's little agreement on how successful they
will be.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most widely cited Y2K consultants, Connecticut-based
GartnerGroup, recently said 90 percent of millennium bug problems
should be corrected within three days of Jan. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``A `bomb shelter' mentality is not called for,'' an Oct. 28
report said. But individuals should keep two weeks' salary in cash
on hand and a five-day supply of food, medicine and fuel as a
precaution, the report advised.
</P>
<P>
   Many bracing for the worst
</P>
<P>
   The American Red Cross recently offered similar advice,
recommending that people stock up to a week of disaster supplies
and some extra cash.
</P>
<P>
   Many are bracing for worse. There is a small but growing Y2K
preparedness movement around the nation that began with
survivalists and militia types but has gone mainstream. At meetings
and on the Internet, the concerned share tips on stockpiling food,
storing water and coping with potential disruptions to electricity
and other services.
</P>
<P>
   Blane Land, a computer consultant who runs a secular Y2K Web
site out of Pensacola, says those who are most serious about Y2K
preparation are usually serious about their Christian beliefs as
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of people that I've had direct contact with, and
I'm talking about hundreds, happen to be oriented that way,'' Land
said. ``It's curious to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Scheer, whose church in Stuart has begun hosting millennium bug
preparedness meetings every other Saturday evening, offers an
explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you study the Word, there is that constant awareness of
destruction and tribulation that is coming,'' says Scheer, who says
he doesn't necessarily fit Y2K into an end-time scenario. ``I don't
want to believe it. But I'd rather prepare and have the
insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   Even without the apocalyptic element, the idea of one of
mankind's greatest technological accomplishments being laid low by
simple human shortsightedness carries a spiritual lesson for some.
</P>
<P>
   ``The computer is the most visible symbol of our technological
society and the earthly attempt to create a utopia without God,''
says Stephen O'Leary, a University of Southern California professor
who specializes in religious communication and tracks
turn-of-the-millennium phenomena. He's also on the board of
directors of the Boston-based Center for Millennial Studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This story is almost too delicious for someone who is a
religiously minded critic of secular society,'' O'Leary says.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Falwell has said Y2K may be God's judgment on an immoral
society grown arrogant because of its wealth and technological
might.
</P>
<P>
   ``God may use the year 2000 computer crisis to crush us and
prepare us for revival,'' Falwell says on a $28.95 video collection
of recent sermons called Y2K: A Christian's Guide to the Millennium
Bug.
</P>
<P>
   Falwell lists ammunition among the supplies Christians should
consider stocking in case the worst Y2K scenarios of shortages and
civil unrest come true.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I am blessed with a little food and my family's inside the
house with me, I've got to be sure that I can persuade others not
to mess with us. Now, I wouldn't want to hurt anybody, but I
wouldn't want to let anybody hurt me. So we'd have to pray about
that,'' Falwell says on the video.
</P>
<P>
   Falwell's is one of several Christian Y2K products on the
market. An Illinois megachurch, the Midwest Christian Center,
advertises a $39.95 series of eight Y2K audio tapes. Oregon
docuvangelist Ken Klein sells a $19.95 video explaining Y2K and its
possible prophetic significance, plus a $129.95 follow-up video
series on family Y2K preparedness.
</P>
<P>
   Televangelist Jack Van Impe sells a $24.95 ``emergency video''
called 2000 Time Bomb that ties the millennium bug to end-time
prophecies in the New Testament book of Revelation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the calamities predicted by most of the secular experts
happen, the panic in the aftermath could easily lead to the rise of
the Antichrist, the one-world government, and the `mark of the
beast,' '' Van Impe declared on his Web site in an October Y2K
update. ``Friends, closing time is near! Maranatha _ the Lord is
coming!''
</P>
<P>
   Van Impe is referring to the 13th chapter of Revelation, which
describes the rise of a blasphemous beast who rules the Earth and
forces all mankind to receive a mark on the right hand or forehead
to engage in commerce.
</P>
<P>
   For some apocalypticists, Y2K presents a perfect opportunity for
the beast to emerge as an evil Mr. Fixit who solves the world's
computer problems and consolidates political power in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Many Christians enjoy these scenarios as a kind of wishful
thinking, says Steve Hewitt, an ordained Baptist minister who
publishes Christian Computing magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Y2K almost promises the beginning of a tribulation, which
excites people. . . . The more bad news, the better,'' Hewitt says.
He doesn't believe Y2K is a significant problem _ a view that had
him outnumbered 4-to-1 when he participated in a recent Y2K panel
discussion on Dobson's nationally syndicated Focus on the Family
radio program.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt says too many Christian leaders are preoccupied with Y2K
and that is hurting their attempts to present the gospel to
nonbelievers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happening now is just criminal,'' Hewitt says. ``I
think we're continuing to lose our credibility. We're totally
sidetracked.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Christians who disagree with Hewitt on the severity of the
Y2K problem agree with him about Christians being sidetracked.
</P>
<P>
   Reach out to others
</P>
<P>
   Instead of arguing over interpretations of end-time prophecy or
adopting a bunker mentality, Christians should reach out to others,
says Kate Allen, executive director of the inter-denominational
Joseph Project.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based group takes its name from the Joseph of Old
Testament many-colored coat fame who, after being sold into slavery
in Egypt, foresaw a seven-year famine and advised Pharaoh to
prepare by storing a seven-year supply of grain.
</P>
<P>
   The Joseph Project advises Christians to ``store to reach out to
the community and minister to them in the time of need,'' says
Allen. ``We're urging both individual churches as well as families
to store enough to share.''
</P>
<P>
   The group doesn't take a position on how long a period to
prepare for. But Allen says those who store too much can easily
find places to give it away once the Y2K threat passes.
</P>
<P>
   That's the philosophy of Dave Miller who is laying up a
three-month supply of beans and rice in the utility room of his
suburban West Palm Beach home. He's also rigged up a
water-purification system and plans to stock up on canned goods in
the summer.
</P>
<P>
   An elder at the Grace Christian Fellowship near Palm Springs,
Miller expects Y2K to be a ``significant'' event and a major
opportunity for the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the church should get ready to minister, basically,
and show the love of Christ and not run away,'' he said. ``It's a
lot easier to tell someone about Jesus if you hand them something
to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
