<P>
   &UR; FOR MONDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Monday, Dec. 28:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ATTACK (Podujevo, Yugoslavia) _ As the truce in Kosovo
continues to disintegrate, rebels came down from the hills Sunday
and attacked a large police position along the main road between
Belgrade and Pristina, the provincial capital. By Mike O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   GERM-WARFARE _ A look at the state of germ weapons after the
collapse of the Soviet Union. By William J. Broad and Judith
Miller. (With a map.)
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-SUCCESSION _ Nelson Mandela's designated heir goes to
his home village in an effort to raise his profile. By Suzanne
Daley.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-AIDS-KILLING (Johannesburg, South Africa) _ A volunteer
working to convince South Africans not to discriminate against
HIV-infected people was beaten to death last week by her neighbors,
who accused her of bringing shame on their community by revealing
that she was HIV-positive. By Donald G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-HOSPITALS _ Although the effect of sanctions is evident in
every aspect of Iraqi life, there are few places where it is more
poignantly visible than at hospitals. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRIAL (Beijing) _ The trial of a major dissident continues
as China makes it clear that those who sought political pluralism
will pay the consequences. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-ANNAN (United Nations) _ An interview with the
Secretary-General Kofi Annan, focusing on why he has felt it
helpful to deal with the devil, so to speak, during the crises with
Iraq and in other instances. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-TV-BLONDES (Rome) _ The biggest television phenomenon in
Italy is what they call a ``soubrette,'' borrowing a French term
for a nubile maid in a theatrical comedy. But to Italians, the
ideal TV soubrette doesn't necessarily sing or dance. She is almost
always tall, blond and Californian, and speaks adorably fractured
Italian. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CRIME-DECLINE (Boston) _ The number of people robbed in 1997
dropped a stunning 17 percent, the Justice Department has reported.
That is not only good news, but, criminologists say, provides an
important clue that the main factors behind the decline in crime
over the past seven years may be the withering away of the crack
cocaine market and police efforts to seize handguns from criminals
and juveniles. By Fox Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   MASS-NATIVITY (Boston) _ A profile of Elma Lewis, a 76-year-old
black woman who has run a live nativity show in Boston for decades.
By Sara Rimer.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-OTTERS (San Francisco) _ Southern sea otters, the playful
darlings of the central California coast, appear to be diminishing
in number at a rate that perplexes and worries scientists.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-REPUBS (Washington) _ Depite post-impeachment polls
showing that the Republican Party's standing has sunk to its lowest
level in years, leading Republicans insist they are not worried
that the party will suffer longterm damage, because they expect the
Senate to settle the matter quickly. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-RDP (Washington) _ President Clinton will be tried on
two articles of impeachment, starting as early as next week, but
the likely result will be censure, not conviction and removal from
office, several senators said Sunday. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SAFIRE-COLUMN _ Details to come. By William Safire.
</P>
