<HEADER>
A7630 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-TALK-830(2TAKES     12-27 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-830(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV GUIDE INVESTIGATES A FAILED INVESTIGATION  
 CHANNEL ONE'S AUDIENCE NOW A NIELSEN AUDIENCE  
 ANOTHER GLUM PORTRAIT OF AMERICAN JOURNALISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Bylines follow individual items.) 
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a departure from its usual editorial fare, TV Guide _ the
couch potato's weekly bible that is owned by Rupert Murdoch's News
Corp. _ is running a four-part, 20,000-word investigative series
about CNN and the Tailwind debacle of last summer. It is a far cry
from a recent cover story, ``The Spellbinding Witches of Charmed,''
an article about a television program starring Shannen Doherty as a
witch.
</P>
<P>
   In the first installment of ``Tailwind: Behind the TV Story of
the Year,'' which arrived on newsstands on Dec. 21, almost six
months after CNN broadcast the report, Mary Murphy, a TV Guide
staff reporter, and Dennis McDougal, an investigative journalist
and author, scrutinized in painstaking detail the process by which
April Oliver, a CNN producer, investigated the story.
</P>
<P>
   The authors portrayed Richard Kaplan, the CNN/USA president, as
a man concerned more about ``glitz'' than substance, and wrote that
Tailwind was ``the biggest catastrophe in CNN's history'' and ``the
biggest blunder in its history.''
</P>
<P>
   In the issue that arrives on newsstands Monday, the second
installment states that John Stacks, an executive editor at Time
magazine, was seriously concerned about the truth of Ms. Oliver's
accusations that the United States used nerve gas against its own
troops, and that Pamela Hill, a CNN senior executive producer, had
``specifically forbidden'' CNN's military consultant, Maj. Gen.
Perry Smith, a retired Air Force officer, to work with the CNN
team.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Hill said in an interview last week that she was not
alone in her hesitation to have the coverage vetted by a CNN
consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were others as well as I who had some reservations about
taking the story outside at the time because of its specificity,''
Ms. Hill said about the TV Guide accusation.
</P>
<P>
   Why devote so much manpower and space to a subject that is 6
months old? Murdoch and Ted Turner, the founder of CNN, do not
enjoy the most personable of relations (Turner once compared
Murdoch to Hitler and Murdoch's Fox News channel is a fierce
competitor of CNN). But Steven Reddicliffe, the editor in chief of
TV Guide, defended his magazine's investigation into the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``There hasn't been a news story like this in television in
recent years,'' he said. ``When they do, if your magazine covers
television, you'd better cover it.''
</P>
<P>
   CNN did not respond to the reporters working on the TV Guide
articles. Howard Polskin, a CNN spokesman, said CNN had made a
retraction and an apology to viewers in July, and would not comment
further.
</P>
<P>
   _ ALEX KUCZYNSKI
</P>
<P>
   Channel One's Audience Now a Nielsen Audience
</P>
<P>
   Who pays much attention to Channel One, the 12-minute news
broadcast beamed directly into 12,000 American schools each day,
except perhaps the teen-agers who have to watch it? Certain
advertisers do, because teen-agers are an elusive and very
important audience.
</P>
<P>
   How important? Important enough that advertisers who buy
commercials on Channel One (two minutes' worth in each newscast)
want to know exactly what they are getting for their money, so
Channel One signed a five-year contract earlier this month with
Nielsen Media Research, the company that measures commercial
networks.
</P>
<P>
   After all, advertisers spend a premium to reach Channel One
viewers. The network charges $200,000 for its 30-second commercials
_ more than what is paid for most prime-time broadcast network
shows, and almost as much as was charged for the much hyped season
finale of the teen-agers' favorite ``Dawson's Creek'' on the WB
network last spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we have 8 million kids,'' said Jon Marks, senior vice
president for research at Channel One, a unit of Primedia Inc.
``That's three or four times as many viewers as the No. 1
prime-time show with teen-agers,'' which is ``Dawson's Creek.''
</P>
<P>
   Channel One can reach 8 million teen-agers, but it reaches
somewhat fewer on a given day, because of holidays, teacher
in-service days, school closings, or the contract's wiggle room,
which allows schools to decline the program for up to 10 percent of
school days.
</P>
<P>
   But why Nielsen? With a precise tally of schools under contract,
knowledge of how many students are in each class, and updates on
which days schools are closed, Channel One, it would seem, could
give advertisers a pretty good estimate itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's half the equation, whether school is in session,''
Marks said. ``The other half is: Did the school play the show that
day?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Put yourself in advertisers' shoes,'' he added. ``To them, the
difference between it being 7.3 million kids vs. 7.5 million on a
given day is very significant. It's a couple hundred thousand
viewers, equivalent to what they might get by running an extra spot
on MTV.''
</P>
<P>
   So are they skeptical that schools run Channel One as often as
promised?
</P>
<P>
   ``A little,'' Marks said. ``That's their job, though. We don't
begrudge them their skepticism.''
</P>
<P>
   _ LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Another Glum Portrait of American Journalists
</P>
<P>
   Journalists are too concerned with covering sex and are less
concerned with accuracy, fairness and avoiding bias, reports a
study released by the American Society of Newspaper Editors.
</P>
<P>
   Titled ``Why Newspaper Credibility Has Been Dropping,'' the
study was based on telephone interviews with 3,000 Americans in
April and May and followed up with meetings of 16 focus groups. It
reports that readers say the credibility of all news media has
suffered in what is perceived to be a ceaseless chase after the
saucy, sexy story.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the statement ``Journalists chase sensational
stories because they think it'll sell papers, not because they
think it's important news,'' 53 percent of the study's respondents
agreed and 27 percent strongly agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Among the study's more intriguing findings: Journalists can be
manipulated by people in powerful positions, 78 percent of the
respondents said; journalists do not demonstrate consistent respect
for their readers and communities, three-quarters said; and the
people who say that journalists do not slant their reporting to
suit their own political beliefs are more likely to be Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that the public regards journalists as
motivated and intelligent. The bad news, according to some in the
focus groups: Journalists ``like to see adverse things happen to
people.'' They enjoy their ``power.'' Saddest of all, perhaps, is
the belief of one focus-group participant: ``You wouldn't be a good
reporter if you were a nice person.''
</P>
<P>
   But print reporters can take heart in the finding that only 23
percent of respondents see print reporters as the worst
perpetrators of bias, while 42 percent see another, more pervasive
purveyor of bias: television.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to address the situation, the editors' group has
introduced the Journalism Credibility Project, a program that will
encourage eight daily newspapers _ including The Philadelphia
Inquirer, The Austin American-Statesman in Texas and The San Jose
Mercury News in California _ to build reader trust by focusing on
accuracy, trying to connect with readers and seriously weighing
which subjects are purely sensational and which are necessary news
items.
</P>
<P>
   The program will begin in the spring, but Lee Stinnett, the
executive director of the editors' group, said he was still
determining the specific ways in which newspapers can work on
accuracy and fairness _ presumably, goals they struggle to achieve
every day anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've just sent out the study, and we're soliciting ideas
about how to achieve those goals,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ ALEX KUCZYNSKI
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
