<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981227.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-27 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7633 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BALLPARK-DEVELOPMENT-     12-27 1606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALLPARK-DEVELOPMENT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JOHN WILLIAMS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1998 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The Hiransomboon family moved here from Thailand in
1976, shortened their surname and began working at a variety of
businesses, including wholesaling flowers on Fannin Street.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, they bet on downtown redevelopment by purchasing an
empty lot across Texas Avenue from the aging Union Station. They
hoped, in time, to emulate the success of such immigrant families
as the Pappas or Fertitta clans. When the Ballpark at Union Station
was announced three years later, brothers Bruce and Nick Hiran
boldly envisioned a Thai restaurant-and-sports-bar, a taqueria and
a cafe to be called Home Plate BBQ.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of being on the verge of cashing in on the
ballpark's promise of 2.5 million fans milling around downtown, the
Hirans are instead in a fight with the Harris County-Houston Sports
Authority, which wants a bus transit center on the lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``They look at us like, `You will make Texas Avenue look run
down,' '' Bruce Hiran said. ``They think we can't do anything that
will be congruent with Texas Avenue being a Main Street USA. They
don't think we're with the program and they bully us around.''
</P>
<P>
   Vignettes like this one have some downtown boosters worried that
Houston is re-creating the Astrodome downtown, essentially
surrounding the stadium with parking and public-use projects that
may not add to the ambience _ or economic vitality _ of the area.
</P>
<P>
   Eyeballing the critical two-block radius around the ballpark,
they see parking lots and other areas already dedicated for public
use. Less than half of the blocks are available to developers
expected to bring in bars, restaurants, lofts and other amenities
that have sprouted around similar ballparks in Denver, Cleveland
and Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the sports authority wants to eat up two more blocks
with a park and bus center.
</P>
<P>
   And Astros owner Drayton McLane Jr. is looking for possibly two
others for additional parking garages so his high-paying customers
don't have to walk far to games. Two years ago, McLane told
cautious voters that the ballpark would offer as much parking as
the Astrodome does.
</P>
<P>
   But, as is evident to anyone who goes to the Astrodome, building
a sports complex doesn't guarantee surrounding development,
especially when the area is rife with parking lots.
</P>
<P>
   ``That two or three blocks around the stadium are crucial,''
said Bob Eury, president of Central Houston Inc. and perhaps
downtown's biggest advocate. ``If they are filled with parking lots
and don't have a critical mass of bars and restaurants, fans drive
to the game, park, walk to the game and leave, just like they do at
the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It becomes that much harder to develop in the future if people
walk through parking lots to get to the ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   Eury warned that without an array of interesting buildings and
businesses to keep the attention of passers-by on non-baseball
days, it will be hard to sustain growth immediately around the
ballpark, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Denver is the best model,'' Eury said. ``There are businesses
all around Coors Field. It is active, even when the (Colorado
Rockies) aren't playing.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the area around Coors Field had a huge head start. It
was an old warehouse district that had attracted substantial
residential developers from new urban dwellers seeking a change
from the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   But Denver did something unique, said Bill Mosher, president of
the Downtown Denver Partnership. The city imposed a ban on
destruction of buildings until after the end of the first season.
It was aimed at developers who were considering tearing down
buildings for parking.
</P>
<P>
   The result?
</P>
<P>
   The 3,500 parking spaces the team has to the north of the
ballpark are rarely filled though the team averages more than
48,000 in attendance to each game. Mosher said fans prefer walking
through the neighborhood to the park, stopping for a drink or bite
to eat, rather than driving in and out.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, more than 40 bars and restaurants have sprung
up since the facility opened in 1995 as businessmen take advantage
of the fans who walk through the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``People complained that we were taking away property rights,
but we didn't want a bunch of parking lots. The whole beauty of the
baseball stadium is that it is part of the ambience of the area,''
Mosher said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you end up with a sea of parking, you end up with a bunch
of cars. And when the game isn't on, the place is dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston doesn't have many quaint buildings around its ballpark.
Of 39 blocks immediately around it, 15 are now either surface
parking lots or parking garages, including enough for the Astros to
park roughly 2,200 cars next to a stadium that will hold 42,000
people.
</P>
<P>
   Of the other blocks, 16 have buildings readily available for
development and eight are dedicated to structures like a church, a
youth league park or apartments for low-income dwellers.
</P>
<P>
   That can cause a problem with immediate development because
there are not many of the older buildings that small developers can
turn into a single establishment, said developer C. Richard
Everett, head of Century Development Co.
</P>
<P>
   Parking lots produce steady revenue and are relatively cheap to
build and maintain. That makes them costly to convert into other
uses. In addition, it costs more to build new from the ground up
than to place a bar into an existing building, he said.
</P>
<P>
   That makes it harder for people like the Hirans to get a
toe-hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``What usually happens is the small guys first do a lot of work
in an area like that around the ballpark,'' Everett said. ``Once
they have made it, the big guys come in and throw around the big
bucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a lot of places available for the small guys, it may
be hard to take that first step.''
</P>
<P>
   Many believe there will be a natural progression of development
toward the ballpark from Main Street six blocks to the northwest.
Main Street has become the focus of lofts, restaurants and other
development catering to an influx of residents.
</P>
<P>
   But without focus on the blocks around the ballpark, there is
some question of whether that development will span the entire six
blocks.
</P>
<P>
   The administration of Mayor Lee Brown, who campaigned on making
downtown a top priority, is working on street and sidewalk
improvements along the northern half of downtown. Among the most
important parts of the project is creating head-in parking which
will give shoppers easy access to shops expected to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Called Cotswold 2000, the $33.7 million project will initially
focus on Prairie, Texas and Crawford so the streets leading to the
ballpark are ready when it is scheduled to open in April 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But the administration is doing no other planning for the area
immediately around the ballpark, said Al Haines, Brown's chief
administrative officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't been a priority,'' Haines said.
</P>
<P>
   It has, however, been a priority to the sports authority, which
has been bullishly planning the area.
</P>
<P>
   The sports authority chairman, Jack Rains, said he is not overly
concerned about anything stifling the private sector. Land that
appears unusable now will thrive once money flows into the area, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been my experience in development that the site
(selection) may include demolition of what is there now,'' Rains
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When there is an attraction, development will occur.''
</P>
<P>
   Led by Rains, the authority wants to use eminent domain to buy
two blocks, one for a park and the other for a bus station that
Metro has promised to build. In addition, the authority is
considering asking surrounding property owners to create a scenic
district around the park which would be able to impose restrictions
on businesses.
</P>
<P>
   He fears that strip joints and other less desirable businesses
might be attracted to the area.
</P>
<P>
   But Rains' actions have drawn criticism that the authority is
thwarting private developers who don't want to face further
regulations and who fear their land might be condemned by the
authority.
</P>
<P>
   People look at the Hirans and wonder if that will happen to them
should they want to develop there.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to control everything,'' Bruce Hiran said.
</P>
<P>
   Rains said that while he respects property rights, he is looking
to the long-term needs of the area. It is possible the sports
authority may use eminent domain for other acquisitions, he said,
though he was not specific.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the sports authority has no plans to back down
on acquiring land for a park or a bus station.
</P>
<P>
   ``When building a stadium financed by 30-year bonds, it would
seem prudent, if not now, but certainly within the life of the
facility, that a mass-transit station would be needed,'' Rains
said. ``On traveling to other sports facilities, mass-transit
facilities have been integrated into and become a vital component
of the successful functioning of the facilities.''
</P>
<P>
   With the ballpark to open in less than 16 months, few developers
are yet taking actions. Most officials believe that the serious
development will occur after the ballpark is opened, like it did in
Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Left to be known is whether the Astrodome experience will be
repeated downtown, or if the ballpark really will stimulate a
revival in the immediate area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be very easy to wipe out the ambience,'' Eury said.
``We're constantly competing with two demands, moving traffic and
keeping a neighborhood feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important that the first doesn't defeat the second.''
</P>
</TEXT>
