<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MERCHANTS AND ANALYSTS PREDICT SOLID HOLIDAY SALES
</P>
<P>
   Largely undistracted by the impeachment of President Clinton and
the bombing of Iraq, U.S. shoppers appear to have spent freely from
wallets that still feel pretty fat, giving retailers a bright, if
not stellar, holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   Though industry figures will not be officially reported until
early January, retail analysts and merchants are predicting that
December sales in big chain stores open at least one year will rise
for the second year in a row by as much as 4 percent to 5 percent.
Other retailers are expecting solid gains as well.
</P>
<P>
   DAIMLER FORECASTS '98 RESULTS
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler, the world's fifth-largest automaker, said that
its 1998 combined sales would rise more than 13 percent and that
profit would exceed last year's figures of the combined
Daimler-Benz and Chrysler.
</P>
<P>
   NO NEED TO TOUCH THAT RADIO DIAL
</P>
<P>
   The promise of a crisp radio signal that can be heard anywhere
in the United States, considered a pipe dream a decade ago, appears
to be only about a year from reality. Two companies with government
licenses to bring satellite-delivered broadcasts to radio _ CD
Radio and XM Satellite _ have lined up technology and programming
partners and plan to introduce the services in 2000. Both would-be
satellite-radio broadcasters say they can build a business from
fee-paying listeners, who would need a satellite-radio adapter and
a palm-sized antenna, like the one held by Hugh Panero, the chief
executive of XM, to pick up the signals.
</P>
<P>
   TV GUIDE INVESTIGATES CNN REPORT
</P>
<P>
   In a departure from its usual editorial fare, TV Guide is
running a four-part, 20,000-word investigative series about CNN's
decision during the summer to broadcast and then retract a report
that the United States used nerve gas in Laos in the Vietnam War as
part of a secret mission to kill American defectors.
</P>
<P>
   WEB SITE FOR SENDING THE VERY BEST
</P>
<P>
   Amid this year's holiday bustle, Felicia Lindau opened
Sparks.com, which she bills as the ``world's largest greeting card
store.'' The store is actually a Web site, and it allows users to
browse through an online selection of more than 5,000 cards from
hundreds of publishers. In contrast, a typical neighborhood card
store carries 300 to 600 cards, usually from one major publisher.
</P>
<P>
   E.T. TO URGE SAFE DRIVING ON EARTH
</P>
<P>
   E.T., the alien whose exile on Earth and journey home were
chronicled in the popular 1982 film ``E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial,''
will be the focus for a coming campaign by Arnell Group Brand
Consulting in New York for Progressive automobile insurance. The
campaign is intended to sell safe driving rather than insurance
policies.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE SALES INTENSIFY TAX PROBLEM
</P>
<P>
   Online sales exceeded expectations during the holiday season,
bolstered in part by the Internet Tax Freedom Act, which declared a
three-year tax moratorium for online sales. But the Internet only
intensifies a problem for states that has been brewing for decades
in the mail-order business: how to tax purchases that cross state
lines to prevent the erosion of revenue.
</P>
<P>
   TELECOM ITALIA TO SELL STAKE IN UNIT
</P>
<P>
   Telecom Italia, the world's eighth-largest telecommunications
company, has agreed to sell up to 80 percent of its Stream pay-TV
unit to Rupert Murdoch's News Corp. for as much as $118.8 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
