<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAGGLING-TIPS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITENESS GOES A LONG WAY IN DEALING FOR DISCOUNTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Most consumers -- Saturn owners excluded --
wouldn't dream of buying a new car without trying to talk the
dealer down in price. But they'll turn around and pay full sticker
for home appliances, jewelry, hotel rooms and virtually everything
else.
</P>
<P>
   Big mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything's negotiable. And what do you have to lose if it's
not?'' explained Selwyn Gerber, president of Gerber Financial
Management in Beverly Hills. Gerber, who lectures corporate
purchasing agents on the art of negotiating, said the key to
successful haggling is to show a little class.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a way to negotiate that is respectful,'' Gerber said.
``If done right, it can lead to an ongoing relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Courtesy and communication are key.
</P>
<P>
   If, not will
</P>
<P>
   Be polite, but never tell a salesperson you plan to buy
something. Always ask a tentative, if-derived question. For
example, ``If I were to buy this radio, what sort of discount could
you offer me?''
</P>
<P>
   Back for more
</P>
<P>
   Whatever price they come back with, tell the salesperson it
really isn't good enough. Tell them to please go back and do
better.
</P>
<P>
   Explain why
</P>
<P>
   The more a salesperson understands your position, the better
your chances of getting a discount. Don't say you want to pay $100
for an item. Say you need to because of your budget. People respect
needs far more than they respect wants.
</P>
<P>
   Lowball-plus
</P>
<P>
   If you have a target price that you want to pay for a negotiable
item, wait to see what price the salesperson asks. As much as their
figure is over the amount you hope to pay, counter with an offer
that is much below your target. In other words, if you hope to pay
$10,000 for a car, but a salesperson offers $11,000, come back with
$9,000. That way you're always headed toward your price, not
theirs.
</P>
<P>
   Think local
</P>
<P>
   Independent local stores are more willing to negotiate than
large chains. And it won't hurt your karma to give them your
business.
</P>
<P>
   No-tell hotel
</P>
<P>
   When booking a hotel or motel room, always ask the ``rack'' or
standard rate. Then ask if there are any discounts they can offer.
Finally, ask to speak with the facility's corporate sales
representative. Taking these steps alone can usually save you
between 10 percent and 30 percent off the standard nightly rate.
</P>
<P>
   Help them help you
</P>
<P>
   When shopping for clothes at discount outlets such as Ross Dress
for Less, a scuff or snag on a shoe or sweater is usually all the
excuse a floor manager needs to knock the item's price down a few
or several dollars. Considering how picked over the goods in such
stores can be, you'll often be able to find such minor flaws.
</P>
<P>
   Know when to say when
</P>
<P>
   Just because you can haggle over something doesn't mean you
should. ``If you're buying flowers for your wife on your
anniversary, pay the $65,'' Gerber said. ``But if you're buying
flowers for a wedding and need a couple dozen place settings, be
sure to negotiate.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
