<SLUG> BC-ECONOMICS-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEFORE YOU INVEST, TAKE SOME ADVICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Each year's Stock Trader's Almanac is filled with
pithy quotes offering investment advice from the most successful
investors and traders in Wall Street history. Here, for our holiday
weekend ruminations, are some of the best words of wisdom that
publisher Yale Hirsch has offered in recent editions:
</P>
<P>
   In this game, the market has to keep pitching, but you don't
have to swing. You can stand there with the bat on your shoulder
for six months until you get a fat pitch. (Warren Buffett)
</P>
<P>
   Ninety-nine percent of what most people see on television about
business is not only irrelevant but possibly damaging. (George W.
Goodman, a.k.a. Adam Smith)
</P>
<P>
   It's a buy when the 10-week moving average crosses the 30-week
moving average, and the slope of both averages is up. (Victor
Sperandeo)
</P>
<P>
   News on stocks is not important. How the stock reacts to it is
important. (Michael Burke, BEGIN ITAL Chartcraft END ITAL)
</P>
<P>
   Better to sell too late than too soon in a momentum-driven
market, as stocks often go much, much higher. Let your stock hit at
least two lower tops and bottoms before you sell. (Jordan Kimmel)
</P>
<P>
   Beware of inside information ... all inside information. (Jesse
Livermore)
</P>
<P>
   With enough inside information and a million dollars, you can go
broke in a year. (Warren Buffett)
</P>
<P>
   Markets are constantly in a state of uncertainty and flux, and
money is made by discounting the obvious and betting on the
unexpected. (George Soros)
</P>
<P>
   Spend at least as much time researching a stock as you would
choosing a refrigerator. (Peter Lynch)
</P>
<P>
   The first rule is not to lose. The second rule is not to forget
the first rule. (Warren Buffett)
</P>
<P>
   I'm always turned off by an overly optimistic letter from the
president in the annual report. If his letter is mildly
pessimistic, to me that's a good sign. (Philip Carret)
</P>
<P>
   The people who sustain the worst losses are usually those who
overreach. And it's not necessary: Steady, moderate gains will get
you where you want to go. (John Train)
</P>
<P>
   Most periodicals and trade journals are deadly dull, and indeed
full of fluff provided by public relations agents. (Jim Rogers)
</P>
<P>
   You try to be greedy when others are fearful, and fearful when
others are greedy. (Warren Buffett)
</P>
<P>
   I measure what's going on, and I adapt to it. I try to get my
ego out of the way. The market is smarter than I am, so I bend.
(Martin Zweig)
</P>
<P>
   The worst mistake investors make is taking their profits too
soon and their losses too long. (Michael Price)
</P>
<P>
   If you can buy all you want of a new issue, you do not want any;
if you cannot obtain any, you want all you can buy. (Rod Fadem)
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing wrong with cash. It gives you time to think.
(Robert Prechter Jr.)
</P>
<P>
   A bull market tends to bail you out of all your mistakes.
Conversely, bear markets make you pay for your mistakes. (Richard
Russell)
</P>
<P>
   Almost any insider purchase is worth investigating for a
possible lead to a superior speculation. But very few insider sales
justify concern. (William Chidester)
</P>
<P>
   Your emotions are often a reverse indicator of what you ought to
be doing. (John F. Hindelong)
</P>
<P>
   Buy a stock the way you would buy a house. Understand and like
it such that you'd be content to own it in the absence of any
market. (Warren Buffett)
</P>
<P>
   The stock market is that creation of man which humbles him the
most. (Anonymous)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
