<SLUG> BC-NECKTIE-FASHION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENEGADES ESCAPE THE NECKTIE NOOSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MAN FULLER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ They're the ties that
bind.
<TEXT>
<P>
   No, not ropes or wedding vows _ neckties, those polyester and
silk nooses that millions of men around the world get for Christmas
and knot around their necks every day.
</P>
<P>
   A Dutch prince recently revolted, however, ripping off his tie
at a fashion gathering and tossing it to the ground, issuing a
rallying cry for men the world over to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   As the tie lay at the feet of his wife, Queen Beatrix, Prince
Claus snarled: ``A snake around my neck!'' That brought the crowd
to its feet in a chorus of cheers.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, men throughout the Netherlands were rallying to the
prince's call. On the news that night, a television anchorman
stripped away his tie as he reported the story. The sports
broadcaster did the same while reciting soccer scores.
</P>
<P>
   Call it the lose-the-noose movement.
</P>
<P>
   In the Netherlands the clamor is known as ``Claustrophilia,''
named after the 73-year-old Prince Claus.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Andersen, executive director of the Neckwear Association
of America, dismisses the prince's necktie revolt as rubbish.
</P>
<P>
   Women, Andersen said, find ties sexy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans buy 90 million to 95 million ties a year,'' Andersen
said. ``They're not going to stop just because some impervious
prince says he doesn't want to wear a necktie anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Andersen acknowledged that sales of ties in America already had
dipped from earlier this decade. A record number of ties _ more
than 100 million _ were sold in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   And while casual-dress Fridays probably have something to do
with the decline, Andersen said, a more likely explanation is that
men are buying fewer but better ties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of spending $20 or $30 on a tie, they're now spending
$40, $50 or more for a tie,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year men, women and children spent $1.4 billion on ties for
their fathers, husbands and brothers. Twenty percent of them were
bought in the December holiday season, and women bought more than
half of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ties are one of the few ways that men have of expressing
individuality when it comes to office attire,'' Andersen said. ``It
allows them to express themselves, whether subtle or bright.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry Robinson, a vice president at the Federal Reserve in
Kansas City, smirked when he learned how much Americans spent on
ties last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``$1.4 billion? What a ridiculous thing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said that in the fall of 1997, the Federal Reserve
decided to adopt a business-casual standard of dress for those days
when no outside meetings or groups of visitors were scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Robinson said he always had a tie in his office _ the one
hanging with the suit jacket on the back of his door for
office-attire emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the change in dress code, Robinson said, he has
bought only two or three ties in the last year, compared with five
or six a year in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Ditto for Lynn Mitchelson, a senior vice president at
NationsBank.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do like them from a fashion standpoint, but I'm a lot more
comfortable without one,'' Mitchelson said. ``I still like shopping
for a tie, but I buy fewer of them than I used to.''
</P>
<P>
   That is because his office also has adopted a business-casual
dress code for those days when no out-of-office meetings are
scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   So whose bright idea were these neck-stranglers, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   Some cite the Sun King, Louis XIV, who when visited by a group
of Croatian mercenaries at the royal palace admired their silk
scarves. The French word for tie, BEGIN ITAL cravat END ITAL, is
thought to be a derivative of ``Croat.''
</P>
<P>
   Ties evolved in various forms in the United States and abroad
until after World War II, when ties as we know them today emerged.
</P>
<P>
   In 1948 that arbiter of American men's style, BEGIN ITAL Esquire
END ITAL, introduced the Bold Look _ a wide-shouldered jacket with
oversized lapels and a wide, spread collar, all topped off by a
5-inch-wide tie.
</P>
<P>
   By the late 1940s ``narrative'' ties were all the rage, with
themes ranging from atomic bombs to man's best friend. Some men
chose garish Hawaiian ones with hula girls, including naked ones on
the back. Van Heusen produced ties in three sizes _ small, medium
and WOW.
</P>
<P>
   Today ties can be equally weird. A search on the Web turns up
dozens of sites selling them.
</P>
<P>
   Among the offerings are Rubber-Necker ties made from recycled
tires. Touted as the only ones that are dishwasher-safe, the
Rubber-Necker ties can be ordered in black, whitewall or
raised-white-letter styles.
</P>
<P>
   But with demand for ties declining, are they destined for
obsolescence?
</P>
<P>
   Andersen, who acknowledges that ties serve no real function,
says he doesn't think so. They're too ingrained in our society, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   And if men find themselves uncomfortable wearing one, they
shouldn't curse the tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buy a shirt with a bigger neck,'' Andersen said. ``If your
pants are too tight, you don't take off your pants _ you buy bigger
pants.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-98 1803EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
