<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BE WARY OF PARTY INVITATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   We are passing through the obligatory round of year-end parties.
Some of these are the soul of innocence and good cheer but some _
and I am thinking here particularly of office parties _ contain
much danger.
</P>
<P>
   Bosses and their underlings sit at table together and partake of
disabling beverages and make discreet eyes at one another's wives
and husbands. A sense of comradeship and equality is created which,
though brief, is quite convincing. Liberties are taken and matters
get out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   At some office parties there are skits and other entertainments.
Preparation of this material ordinarily is left to younger
employees, creative and impetuous types who have not yet learned
the healthy uses of fear. It is a heady business.
</P>
<P>
   My observation has been that captains of industry, although they
may manage thin smiles for the record, do not really enjoy being
cleansed in the white fire of their hirelings' humor. They may not
bellow much as the wound is administered. But like a gut-shot Cape
buffalo, they are apt to wait later in the bushes.
</P>
<P>
   So I have gotten leery of parties, especially office parties in
this season. But not BEGIN ITAL just END ITAL those. The worst one
I ever saw followed a wedding.
</P>
<P>
   I had worked that year with a crew of tree trimmers, and as the
summer drew toward an end one of our crewmates announced his plans
for marriage. He was a tow-headed, solitary giant of a man,
self-contained and all but wordless. Once I saw him climb a huge
sycamore tree that was splitting at its crotch, overhanging
high-voltage lines, houses and garages with cars locked inside.
</P>
<P>
   There was no time for the electric company to disconnect the
power. So very matter-of-factly this silent, agile man crept out
without safety line, above the live wires, onto the sagging main
fork _ the tree making terrible screaming sounds below as the split
widened _ and attached a cable which held until it could be
dismantled and lowered in pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Never before or since have I seen so amazing an act of reckless
courage.
</P>
<P>
   Tree trimmers were then _ may still be _ a carefree, boisterous
and sometimes rowdy breed, as I would imagine lumberjacks to be.
Their excesses stemmed from high spirits, not from meanness.
</P>
<P>
   Well, the wedding was held upstairs in the bride's small house.
The event afterward was in the basement.
</P>
<P>
   Washtubs of iced beer were emptied. Additional cases were sent
out for. The groom lost all the money he had in the world in a
craps game. Good-natured but violent fistfights erupted. Eyes were
closed and lips split.
</P>
<P>
   On toward midnight the wedded couple set out on their honeymoon,
carloads of the groom's colleagues in fast pursuit. Thirty minutes
out of town he turned his machine upside down on the turnpike,
without injury, and they all came back together to sleep it off.
</P>
<P>
   I often wondered afterward how that marriage worked out.
</P>
<P>
   The point is that parties, however well-intentioned their
planning, do not have a uniformly joyful result. And that is why,
if it should ever happen that I am asked to join in the lampooning
of my betters at some office gathering, I will instantly and
cravenly decline.
</P>
<P>
   The season of merriment passes and the parties end. But the
wounds fester.
</P>
<P>
   I have not survived this long and made a safe little career by
going into the bushes after Cape buffalo with only an electric
typewriter and a felt-tipped pen.  &LR; txr:ITAL BEGIN Editor's note:
C.W. Gusewelle's regular column will resume Jan. 10. While he's
away,/} The Star /{is reprinting some of his favorites. This column
was published in 1979. END ITAL
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
