<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICS-D.C.-3RDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ oriented college
course.
<TEXT>
<P>
   BREAKER HEAD ``ROOTED IN PARTISANSHIP''
</P>
<P>
   These days intense partisanship is inbred in House members
almost from the moment they arrive in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Vince Snowbarger, the Olathe Republican who lost his seat in
Congress last month, recalled his freshman orientation in 1996
shortly before assuming office. What struck Snowbarger was how
Democrats and Republicans were kept apart. In the nearly two-week
orientation, members of the two parties spent only about two hours
together.
</P>
<P>
   ``In essence, Republicans and Democrats are separated at
birth,'' Snowbarger said.
</P>
<P>
   That's only one cause of the ongoing rancor. Snowbarger also
cited the narrow Republican House majority of just a dozen seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the Democrats are within striking distance of retaking
the House, there's no incentive for them to cooperate,'' Snowbarger
said.
</P>
<P>
   The emergence of evangelical Christians as a potent political
force adds another complication, said Jim Slattery, a former
Democratic congressman from Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats have trouble dealing with conservatives who feel
they are on a mission from God to impeach Clinton and defend the
country against a decline in cultural values, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Liberal Democrats don't understand that,'' Slattery said.
</P>
<P>
   Wright puts much of the blame on weak and outdated
campaign-finance laws that allow political parties to raise money
in $100,000 chunks. The money, in turn, is used to buy
hard-hitting, 30-second political ads. While many of the ads are
technically true, they are often misleading _ and terribly
divisive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best buy in a TV ad is to destroy your opponent by saying
something in 15 seconds that puts him on the defensive in a way
that he can't explain in fewer than 15 minutes,'' Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   The idea that any action can be blown out of proportion makes
many members edgy and wary. ``They don't trust each other,''
Volkmer said of the two parties.
</P>
<P>
   Some say a lack of sharp disagreement on major issues is another
contributor to the negative politics. Differences on key issues,
such as Social Security, really are minor when viewed from a
distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't have a sharp difference of opinion, then it's
easy for the politics of personal destruction to fill the void,''
Slattery said.
</P>
<P>
   Most incumbents feel free to shoot partisan spitballs because
their seats are theirs for the keeping, for almost as long as they
want. In November, for example, 395 of 401 incumbents who sought
re-election won.
</P>
<P>
   Partisan harassment has become a cottage industry in Washington.
Dozens of groups on both sides of the political spectrum seek to
raise money to fight what they consider the evil doings of their
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can bet your bottom dollar that the liberals don't want us
to learn the truth about Clinton's role in the Whitewater,
Travelgate, FBI Filegate and Kathleen Willey scandals,'' proclaims
a recent fund-raising letter from a conservative group known as
Radio America.
</P>
<P>
   ``You and I may be Starr's only chance to hold Clinton
accountable for his outrageous behavior. Please, send what you can,
but send it today!''  &LR; brk:What is lacking  &LR; tx:If there is a
solution to ending the unceasing warfare, it seems to be a
restoration of two rare commodities _ respect and reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a balance of judgment on both sides,'' said former
Sen. Nancy Kassebaum Baker of Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt of St. Louis agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way to stop this spiral is for all of us to finally
say, ``Enough,' '' Gephardt said in a speech on the House floor
earlier this month. ``Let us step back from the abyss, and let's
begin a new politics of respect and fairness and decency.''
</P>
<P>
   Others say the expected refinement of the independent counsel
law will help.
</P>
<P>
   But with Flynt's January issue looming and the impeachment
process continuing in the Senate, few people expect a more civil
environment anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was a Democrat up there now, I wouldn't hesitate if I
found out something about a Republican to go after him,'' said
Volkmer, who lost his seat in 1996. ``You're fair game. After all,
look what you've done to my president.''
</P>
</TEXT>
