<HEADLINE>
IN D.C., AN ANGRY POLITICS PREVAILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ When Texas Democrat
Jim Wright resigned as speaker in 1989 over ethical questions, he
stood in the well of the House and decried the spirit of ``mindless
cannibalism'' that had lawmakers preying on each other's
reputations.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Let me give you back this job,'' he said. ``Let that be a
total payment for the anger and hostility we feel toward each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright's hope of ending the ceaseless backbiting through his
sudden departure was a ``foolish expectation,'' he says now.
</P>
<P>
   For good reason.
</P>
<P>
   The frenzied, ever-deteriorating culture of personal assault has
persisted in Washington, undermining many public officials.
</P>
<P>
   For some, such as Gary Hart, Clarence Thomas, Henry Hyde, Barney
Frank, Henry Cisneros and Robert Livingston, the weapon was their
sexual histories, true or untrue. For others, such as John Tower
and Douglas Ginsburg, it was alcohol or marijuana use. For still
others, such as Newt Gingrich and President Clinton, it was a
combination of alleged sins.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, some of the officials committed dubious acts, others
used questionable judgment, and most deserve little sympathy. But
each case illustrates the new way of doing business in Washington
that emphasizes investigations and lawyers and endless hearings
over more chivalrous deliberation and compromise.
</P>
<P>
   In short, if you can't beat your political opponents, destroy
them. The new way even has its own names _ ``toxic politics,''
``sexual McCarthyism'' and ``the politics of personal
destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Ginsburg, a Johns Hopkins University political
scientist, has tabbed it ``the politics of R.I.P.: Revelation.
Investigation. Prosecution. And rest in peace for those caught up
in it.''
</P>
<P>
   This angry form of politics is prompting some Washington
lawmakers to say they've simply had enough and will not run for
re-election. It has driven a mile-wide chasm between Republicans
and Democrats, particularly in the House. And it is stifling
progress on important legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Damaging as it is, observers say the carnage still may not be
over.
</P>
<P>
   For many reasons, the politics of personal destruction has
become embedded in Washington culture. Political parties have
become more ideological, making compromises harder to forge. The
end of the Cold War meant the loss of a common enemy and a powerful
unifying force.
</P>
<P>
   Putting television cameras inside the Capitol placed a premium
on tough talk. The media haven't helped. Want to get quoted in a TV
or newspaper story? Trash someone.
</P>
<P>
   And Congress, in its post-Watergate zeal to clean up government,
instituted a slew of ethics laws aimed at ensuring purer lawmakers.
But the move added potent new weapons to the political wars _
investigation and prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   One of those new laws was the much-maligned independent counsel
statute that gives prosecutors unlimited freedom. The law led to
Kenneth Starr's exhaustive investigation of Clinton and other
multimillion-dollar probes that, in some cases, came up empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Which office do I go to to get my reputation back?'' asked
former Labor Secretary Ray Donovan, who was cleared following a
1980s investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, Larry Flynt, publisher of /{Hustler}/ magazine,
announced that he soon would produce a special edition of his
magazine that would offer new details about Livingston and other
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is a result of his offer of up to $1 million for
anyone producing ``evidence of illicit sexual relations'' with top
federal lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   The politics of personal destruction rolls on. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
