<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: FAMILY TIES; NAMESAKE; TAKING AIM: SETTING SAIL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Maine, Calif., Penn., D.C.)  (nk) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER 
  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Her name is Maxine. She is a search-and-rescue pilot
patrolling the snowy mountains of Maine, hunting for an abducted
12-year-old girl and coming to grips with the death of her mother.
When Ellen McLaughlin's play ``Tongue of a Bird'' begins previews
on Sunday at the Mark Taper Forum in Los Angeles, Maxine will be
portrayed by the Tony Award-winning CHERRY JONES in a cast that
also includes Ashley Johnson as the little girl, Tony
Award &UR; - &LR; winner Marian Seldes as Maxine's eccentric Polish immigrant
grandmother, Diane Venora as Maxine's mother and Sharon Lawrence as
another spectral presence. Directed by Lisa Peterson of the Taper
and bound for the Joseph Papp Public Theater in Manhattan, ``Tongue
of a Bird'' plays through Feb. 7. Information: (213) 628-2772.
</P>
<P>
   NAMESAKE
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday night at the Zoellner Arts Center at Lehigh
University in Bethlehem, Pa., Harry Connick will croon to the music
of the Nelson Riddle Orchestra in ``A Salute to Frank Sinatra.''
But this Harry Connick is the man who has been district attorney of
New Orleans since 1973. He is Harry Connick Sr., father of the
actor and singer Harry Connick Jr. The elder Connick, a devotee of
big-band-era music before choosing a career in law, has been
returning lately to his first love. He appears at Lehigh after
performing with the orchestra on New Year's Eve at the
Waldorf-Astoria Hotel &UR;  &LR; in New York. Information: (610) 758-2787.
</P>
<P>
   TAKING AIM
</P>
<P>
   Some say they don't write musicals the way they used to. For an
example of that art, the place to be is the Kennedy Center for the
Performing Arts in Washington, where a revival of Irving Berlin's
``Annie Get Your Gun'' opens a pre-Broadway engagement Tuesday.
Literally speaking, here's the score: songs like ``There's No
Business Like Show Business,'' ``You Can't Get a Man With a Gun''
and ``Anything You Can Do.'' This tale of Annie Oakley and her
competitive relationship with the dashing vaudeville marksman Frank
Butler in ``Buffalo Bill's Wild West Show'' stars BERNADETTE PETERS
and Tom Wopat. The show continues through Jan. 24. Information:
(800) 444-1324 or (202) 467-4600.
</P>
<P>
   SETTING SAIL
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With romantic sailors and ghosts among its crews and
characters, the New York Gilbert and Sullivan Players will open the
winter repertory portion of its 25th-anniversary season on
Wednesday at 3 p.m. with a performance of ``H.M.S. Pinafore'' at
Symphony Space. ``Pinafore'' and ``Ruddigore'' will play for a
total of 21 performances through Jan. 24. The opening performance,
the troupe's very first Wednesday matinee, is designed for children
and includes a 2 p.m. pre-show introduction and post-show backstage
tours. Information: (212) 864-5400.
</P>
</TEXT>
