<SLUG> BC-OWEN-FOOD-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS HOLIDAY, TRY WELCOMING FLAVORS OF THAILAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   According to government estimates, 95 percent of Thai residents
are Buddhists. Most of the others are Muslim. Yet if you walk into
a Bangkok tourist hotel this month you are liable to hear ``I Saw
Mommy Kissing Santa Claus'' being played over the sound system.
</P>
<P>
   The Thai love tourists. But these days, due to the financial
collapse of Asian markets, there are not nearly enough tourists to
go around.
</P>
<P>
   Patronize a restaurant in the Montien Riverside Hotel and you
will notice as you are seated at an outdoor table on the bank of
the Chao Phraya that you are surrounded by tuxedoed waiters.
</P>
<P>
   The food is excellent, dishes cost as little as $4, and you are
treated to an unexpected fireworks show (part of a birthday
celebration for the 71-year-old monarch, aka Rama IX). Yet the
restaurant is almost deserted.
</P>
<P>
   At the Oriental _ acclaimed as the finest hotel in Asia _ an
excellent jazz combo performs in a terrace bar. But there is a
musician for almost every patron in the place.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to lure more tourists, prices on package tours to
Bangkok are unbelievably low. Upon arriving, tourists learn that a
cab ride will usually cost less than $3. And they can order crispy
noodles, chicken satay, hot-and-sour prawn soup, sauteed shrimp
with asparagus and mushrooms, roast duck curry, marinated chicken
wrapped in papadan leaves and jasmine rice for 300 baht (about $8)
per person at the Ban Chiang restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Nareerat Srisawat is an executive for the Bangkok's Montien
hotels. She still owns a residence in Kent, Wash., and occasionally
returns to visit the friends she once treated to home-cooked Thai
feasts. Srisawat and her husband moved to Bangkok when Thai
Airlines moved its West Coast headquarters from Seattle to Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   She still maintains an avid interest in Seattle and in spreading
the gospel of Thai cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   And what do the Thais eat during that season of the year when
Mommy might be seen kissing Santa Claus?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, we don't have turkey at holiday,'' confesses one of
Srisawat's friends, a Bangkok tour guide known as Toy. ``I bring
home Kentucky Fried Chicken.''
</P>
<P>
   Which probably means that in Seattle, we should serve Thai
chicken during the holiday season. This is a variation, using
ingredients readily available in local markets.
</P>
<P>
   Thai Chicken
</P>
<P>
   2 whole chicken breasts
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons soy sauce (divided)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cornstarch (divided)
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons oil
</P>
<P>
   { cup peanuts (salted or unsalted)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon (or more) crushed red peppers
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon minced ginger root
</P>
<P>
   { cup chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 red bell pepper
</P>
<P>
   { pound snow peas
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons water
</P>
<P>
   Skin and bone the chicken breasts and slice the meat into
strips. Mix together 3 tablespoons of soy sauce and 1 tablespoon of
cornstarch and moosh the chicken strips in this mess. Let
everything sit for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the red bell pepper in half, discard the seeds and cut into
strips.
</P>
<P>
   Heat a tablespoon of oil in a hot skillet or wok and quickly fry
the peanuts and dried red peppers. After you have sneezed twice,
remove from the pan.
</P>
<P>
   Add the remaining 2 tablespoons of oil to the pan and stir-fry
the chicken and ginger until the meat is slightly browned. Add the
broth, vinegar, 2 tablespoons of soy sauce, the wine and sugar. Mix
this around once or twice, cover the pan and simmer 3 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the red pepper strips and pea pods and stir-cook another 2
minutes. Mix the remaining tablespoon of cornstarch with 2
tablespoons of water, mix in and cook until everything thickens
slightly. Add the peanut mixture and stir again.
</P>
<P>
   This should serve four to six, with rice.
</P>
<P>
   Phad Thai
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons cooking oil
</P>
<P>
   3 cloves garlic, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces sen lek noodles (flat, dry, rice noodles)
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons fish sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons roasted peanuts (divided)
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons dried shrimp, pounded into powder (divided)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chili powder
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped preserved turnip
</P>
<P>
   1 cup bean sprouts (divided)
</P>
<P>
   4 green onions cut in 1-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   Chopped cilantro leaves
</P>
<P>
   Soak the noodles in water for 20 minutes or until soft. Drain.
</P>
<P>
   In a wok or skillet, heat the oil to medium-high and add the
garlic.
</P>
<P>
   Break the eggs into the pan, stir and cook for 5 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Add noodles and stir-cook 1 minute.
</P>
<P>
   Add, in order, the lemon juice, fish sauce, sugar, half the
peanuts, half the dried shrimp, chili powder, preserved turnip,
half the bean sprouts and the green onions.
</P>
<P>
   Stir-cook a few seconds until the noodles are done, then scoop
onto a platter and add the remaining peanuts, dried shrimp and bean
sprouts. Scatter cilantro leaves over the top. This should serve
four.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to add chicken cubes or thin beef slices to your
phad thai, cook them in the pan with the garlic and, when done, add
the noodles and other ingredients.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
