</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-MIAMI28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons fly beyond expectations with win over Miami
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On the chance the Atlanta Falcons' 14-2 record isn't
enough to spin heads from coast to coast, perhaps Sunday's 38-16
victory against the Miami Dolphins was enough to do the trick.
</P>
<P>
   The NFC West champion Falcons scored touchdowns on their first
plays in both halves, took leads of 21-0 and 38-6, forced six Miami
turnovers and were never threatened by a team that six days earlier
stymied the Super Bowl champion Denver Broncos, 31-21.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody could have predicted Sunday. Nobody could have predicted
Atlanta would be just the sixth NFL team in the last 10 years to
win 14 or more games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't ever realistically go in thinking you're going to be
14-2, but we definitely had some momentum based on the way we
played at the end of last year,'' quarterback Chris Chandler said
when referring to the Falcons' 6-2 finish last season after a 1-7
start. ``Very few people in their NFL careers get this opportunity
for happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   It would have been a good game to rest key players in
anticipation of a home playoff game Jan. 9 against Dallas, Green
Bay or San Francisco, just like head coach Dan Reeves sat this one
out _ not counting his pre-game lecture to the team.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, who is recovering from heart by-pass surgery, gave his
speech and left.
</P>
<P>
   His team remained, and left the Dolphins in a heap.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just said to us, 'Any time they're keeping score, the game
means something,''' Chandler said.
</P>
<P>
   Miami spent all but 24 seconds in the rear-view mirror of a
Falcons team that won its record-tying ninth straight game while
finishing the season undefeated at home for the first time in their
33 years. Atlanta is 20-4 since the middle of 1997, the best record
in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   When it ended, the team mascot, Freddie Falcon, bore a sign
reading, ``Miami Bound.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not meant for the Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   That was a reference to the fact Super Bowl XXXIII will be
played in Miami in four weeks, and the Falcons are one of the
stronger candidates for participation.
</P>
<P>
   Such a thought is only a little more mind-boggling than the way
the game unfolded before a raucous sellout crowd of 69,754.
</P>
<P>
   Although Atlanta could gain nothing in terms of playoff
positioning with a victory, defensive end Lester Archambeau was the
only starter to take the day off because of complications with a
broken thumb.
</P>
<P>
   It looked like Miami (10-6) was playing the scrubs.
</P>
<P>
   On the first play, Chandler faked a handoff to Jamal Anderson,
and rolled right. He passed to tight end O.J. Santiago, who ran 62
yards for a touchdown. Santiago, a second-year player, added a
3-yard touchdown pass with 11:08 to play, and the rout was on.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler left the game after that play after straining his lower
back, but he said afterward that the injury isn't serious.
</P>
<P>
   On the Dolphins' next possession, quarterback Dan Marino was
intercepted by Falcons cornerback Ronnie Bradford, who ran 11 yards
to give the Falcons a 21-0 lead with 7:00 left in the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Game over.
</P>
<P>
   For all the fuss made before the season of how this team's
success was predicated on the health of Chandler, the Falcons are
4-1 in games he missed or left with an injury.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, they were 0-6 in those games.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta outscored Miami 24-16 with Steve DeBerg at quarterback.
DeBerg, 44, completed five of 10 passes for 85 yards, including a
35-yard touchdown pass to Tony Martin on the Falcons' first play of
the second half.
</P>
<P>
   That was good for a 31-6 lead.
</P>
<P>
   After a Miami fumble, Anderson, who rushed for 103 yards to
finish with 1,846 for the season, ran 36 yards for a touchdown and
a 38-6 lead.
</P>
<P>
   It's not clear what role Reeves will have this week or in the
week before the playoff game. He probably will make several
appearances at team headquarters in Suwanee.
</P>
<P>
   ``He probably snuck out of the house,'' free safety Eugene
Robinson said when referring to the pre-game talk. ``He probably
told his wife (Pam), he was going to take out the garbage. We told
him, 'Go home. We don't need you now; we need you for the
playoffs.''''
</P>
<P>
   As evidenced on Sunday, the garbage of 25 non-winning seasons
appears to have been carried out of the Georgia Dome. Some people
are not surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``The confidence in this locker room from the beginning of last
year to now is a complete opposite,'' center Robbie Tobeck said.
``It's been great to be part of the change, to see the guys coming
together. This team is just a bunch of hard-working guys,
blue-collar guys, really, guys coming out of nowhere to play great
football. It's been a very special, fun year.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
