<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-27 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7740 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-PEACHNOTES28-COX     12-27 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-PEACHNOTES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bailey center of attention at Peach Bowl press conference
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Like he surely will be Thursday when Virginia and
Georgia meet in the Georgia Dome, Champ Bailey was the center of
attention at the Peach Bowl's first joint press conference Sunday
at the Atlanta Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia sportwriters in town to cover the bowl were
particularly fascinated by the Georgia junior's ability to stay on
the field for practically every play of every game. Bailey, who
starts both at cornerback and wide receiver, played more than 100
plays in six of the Bulldogs' 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how he does it,'' said Virginia coach George
Welsh. ``I think it's remarkable. We've had some players we thought
about doing it with in the past, but it's so hard just to practice
both ways. We tried that with Ronde' Barber a few years ago but
never did it in a game. I think it's remarkable.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia coach Jim Donnan was asked if he thought it endangered
Bailey by playing him so much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we played him enough,'' he said. ``It's a
mistake every time we take him out of the game because it hurts us.
... He's easily the best all-around player in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Welsh said the Cavaliers would make no special arrangements to
deal with Bailey on offense, where he has caught 47 passes for 744
yards and seven touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't key on him; he's not a tailback,'' Welsh said.
``They run so many different formations and do so many things to
get the ball to him, we just have to play zone or man-to-man and
hope everybody executes.''
</P>
<P>
   What they're playing for
</P>
<P>
   Virginia will be shooting for 10 wins, an accomplishment matched
by only the 1989 team in school history.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 10 wins is the thing I'm thinking about,'' said junior
running back Thomas Jones, who leads the Cavaliers with 1,303 yards
rushing and 13 TDs. ``Ten wins is a great season for any team.
Plus, it gives us something we can build on for next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia looks to rebound after a 21-19 last-second loss to
Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you lose a game like we did to Georgia Tech, it's
tough to swallow,'' Donnan said. ``This game can give us some juice
going into the off-season and for recruiting.''
</P>
<P>
   They said it
</P>
<P>
   Welsh on the differences in the '95 Georgia team the Cavaliers
defeated 34-27 three years ago and the one his team will face
Thursday: ``Georgia has learned how to win again, I'd say that's
the biggest difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Donnan on lineman Keith Stephens' late arrival from Columbus:
``He said he had a flat tire, but I think it's because he's been
eating too much. He probably drove the air out of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia QB Quincy Carter on his remarkable freshman season:
``Dropping the ball off to Champ and watching him run 80 yards is
not too hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Donnan on the stress-free environment of a bowl game: ``When you
live in this state you don't get a chance to be stress-free. We're
on a one-game losing streak.''
</P>
<P>
   All-America matchup
</P>
<P>
   One of the best matchups of the Peach Bowl will feature Georgia
tackle Matt Stinchcomb against Virginia defensive end Patrick
Kerney. Both are first-team All-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Kerney, a 6-6, 265-pound senior, came to Virginia on a lacrosse
scholarship in 1995 but gave that up in order to walk on with the
football team. He tied former Virginia All-American Chris Slade for
quarterback sacks in a season with 15 this year.
</P>
<P>
   Stinchcomb will leave Georgia as one of the Bulldogs' most
decorated players of all time. The 6-6, 291-pound senior began the
season as a Playboy preseason All-American, was a finalist for the
Lombardi Award and won the SEC's Jacobs Blocking Trophy, which
annually goes to the league's top lineman.
</P>
<P>
   What's next
</P>
<P>
   Georgia and Virginia will practice again this morning, the
Bulldogs at Marist High School and the Cavaliers at Georgia Tech.
After another media conference at the Chamber of Commerce, the
teams will visit local children's hospitals this afternoon. The
Bulldogs will go to Scottish Rite and Virginia will go to Egleston.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling right at home
</P>
<P>
   Virginia is undefeated in three trips to the Peach Bowl. The
Cavaliers beat a Purdue team led by Jim Everett and Rod Woodson
27-24 at Atlanta-Fulton County Stadium in 1984 and defeated Georgia
34-27 at the Georgia Dome in 1995. ... Virginia has played a game
in Atlanta five of the last six years. The Cavaliers are 11-9
all-time in Atlanta and 3-0 against the Bulldogs. However, they
lost a 41-38 heartbreaker to Georgia Tech on their last trip to the
city on Oct. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Big-time players
</P>
<P>
   NFL draft expert Mel Kiper Jr. said more future pro football
players will be in action in the Peach Bowl than in the Fiesta
Bowl. He claimed Virginia and Georgia could field up to 17 draft
picks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fiesta Bowl may have the best teams but their talent is
young. If I could go to any bowl, I'd book my ticket for Atlanta,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
