<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jackson dives into the fray for first time since injury
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ Notre Dame quarterback Jarious Jackson,
who's fighting his way back from a partially torn medial collateral
knee ligament, saw his first action in full pads on Sunday since he
injured the knee Nov. 21 against LSU.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The knee) feels great now,'' Jackson said. ``I'm doing
basically everything I want to, everything I feel comfortable
doing. Things I don't feel comfortable doing, I'll be gradually
working toward in the next couple days.''
</P>
<P>
   What he's not doing much of yet is sprinting and not running the
option. If he's unable to do either in the Gator Bowl, it will
severely limit his strengths, since he, like Georgia Tech
quarterback Joe Hamilton, is most dangerous because of his
quickness and versatility. But on Sunday, Jackson and his coach
were feeling good.
</P>
<P>
   ``We let him loose,'' coach Bob Davie said. ``He had bodies
flying around and he was involved in some slight collisions. I
think from a confidence standpoint, it had to help him. I know his
teammates' confidence rose because it looks like he's going to be
able to play. But once again, it's still a day-to-day situation.
It's how he responds after this practice if he comes back tomorrow
and has no setbacks, no swelling, I think he'll be able to play on
Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   Familiar surroundings
</P>
<P>
   Gator Bowl practice surroundings may feel surreal for most of
the Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets, but not for sophomore receiver Dez
White.
</P>
<P>
   Playing on a high school stadium field at the Bolles School _
among the palm trees and the stucco _ in front of a bench painted
Florida Gator blue and orange that says ``Welcome to Bulldog
Country,'' it all feels normal for White. Except maybe he feels
like playing soccer instead of football.
</P>
<P>
   White attended Bolles, where he was a standout in both soccer
and football. It's a short drive from his home in Orange Park, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of my teammates complain about the grass and
shinsplints, but I feel at home, comfortable with the field,'' said
White, who explained that the grass at Bolles is thicker and the
surface softer than the fields at Tech. ``I guess things never
change.''
</P>
<P>
   The school had put up a banner over the breezeway on the home
side of the stadium welcoming Bolles graduates White and Mike
Verlander, a freshman walk-on safety. White also said his mother
Desiree received a letter from Bolles president Harry Demontmollin
saying how proud he was White came through the Bolles program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to know we have that kind of support,'' said White,
who should expect more of the same at Alltel Stadium on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   More Irish injuries
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame received bad news Sunday when senior offensive guard
Jerry Wisne (6 feet 7, 298 pounds) aggravated a knee injury in
practice. Wisne suffered a similar injury to Jackson's _ a
partially torn MCL _ but was a week farther along in his recovery
since his injury occurred Nov. 14 against Navy. Davie will hold
Wisne out of practice today and Tuesday and re-evaluate him on
Tuesday. Junior Mike Gandy (6-4, 296) replaced Wisne in the
starting lineup against LSU and Southern Cal and would do the same
against Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Punt returner Joey Getherall, a sophomore, has suffered a
strained hamstring and is questionable. Getherall is averaging 7.8
yards on 20 returns, including a 68-yarder against Navy.
</P>
<P>
   If he's unable to go, Notre Dame would likely have to rely on
tailback Autry Denson, a move the Irish don't want to make given
his importance.
</P>
<P>
   Denson, who averages 106 yards rushing and leads the Irish with
15 touchdowns, is the key to Notre Dame's offense, especially
considering Jackson's status.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
