<HEADLINE>
NEW YEAR'S EVE WILL BE NO HOLIDAY FOR THE JETS
</HEADLINE>
  (With FBN-JETS-PATRIOTS) 
(ms) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Jets have three days off with the bye week. But
Coach Bill Parcells is bringing them back on Thursday, New Year's
Eve, for the start of three days of workouts. Next week they will
have four days to prepare.
</P>
<P>
   Their divisional playoff game at Giants Stadium in East
Rutherford, N.J., on Jan. 10 will start at 12:30 p.m.. If the
Jacksonville Jaguars defeat the New England Patriots, the wild-card
opponent, on Sunday, the Jets would play Jacksonville. If not, then
the Jets will play host to the winner of the Miami Dolphins-Buffalo
Bills game, which will be played in Miami on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   If the Jets are hosts for the American Football Conference
championship game, the National Football League's headquarters
hotel will be the Waldorf-Astoria. That is in sharp contrast to the
franchise's first headquarters, back in 1960, when they were the
Titans: the Park Avenue apartment of their owner, Harry Wismer.
A Streak Ends &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the Jets' opening play Sunday against the Patriots, a kickoff
return, the club's stretch of penalty-free special-teams play
suddenly ended. Chad Cascadden was flagged for holding. That halted
a five-game stretch for the special teams in which opponents
committed 15 penalties to none for the Jets.  &QL; 
Numbers of Note &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some notable numbers from the regular season:
</P>
<P>
   Keyshawn Johnson caught 10 touchdowns, the most for a Jet since
1986, when Wesley Walker snared 12.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's 83 catches were fourth-highest for a single season in
club history.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets' total of 416 points was 3 under the club record set in
1968.  &QL; 
Shifting the Defense &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Corwin Brown, a special-teamer who comes in on dime defenses,
made a rare start at free safety in place of Jerome Henderson. ``We
wanted someone to tackle Edwards in case he got loose,'' said
Parcells, ``and Corwin's a good tackler.'' Robert Edwards, the
Pats' 1,000-yard rookie rusher, was held to 47 yards on 12 carries,
and that included an 18-yard run. Actually, Pepper Johnson wound up
as the club's leading tackler, including assists. He had a total of
six, even though he alternates quarters with Dwayne Gordon.
Defensive end Anthony Pleasant got the game's only sack, one of his
five tackles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
