<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: GOOD-TIMES BUDGETING IN NEW YORK  
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, Dec. 28:
</P>
<P>
   The boom on Wall Street and rippling prosperity in the region
have again brought a bounty of budget surpluses to New York City
and New York state. The good times guarantee, in turn, that the new
year will begin with temptations at City Hall and the state Capitol
to spend the money on expanded programs and tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   But as Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Gov. George Pataki put the
final touches on budgets due in January, they need to remember that
deficits and mounting debts remain a long-term threat to the fiscal
health of the city and state. The surpluses of today should be
husbanded as a cushion against the day when the economy turns down.
</P>
<P>
   As state Comptroller Carl McCall reported earlier this month,
New York City is likely to end the current fiscal year with a $1
billion surplus, which is certainly positive news. But he also
noted that spending is growing at a rapid rate, largely because of
salary increases for city workers negotiated four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the city is projecting a budget deficit of nearly
$3 billion in two years, while debt service is scheduled to consume
19 percent of the budget by the year 2002. City Hall regards
McCall's projection as overly pessimistic. Even so, Giuliani has
sensibly asked city agencies for possible budget cuts for the next
year.
</P>
<P>
   The city's sobering budget outlook would get worse if the Wall
Street boom faded, which many experts fear is likely. In addition,
the last contract of District Council 37, the largest municipal
union, was unpopular with its members but approved in what turned
out to be a rigged election. Employees are certain to demand bigger
wage and benefit hikes in the next round of talks.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani may be running for higher office by then, but he needs
to begin making plans to ensure that new wage increases are
financed by changes in work rules to lower costs and improve
productivity. He should also take some of the current surplus and
use it for capital projects like school construction, or to pay
down existing debt to lower debt-service costs in the years ahead.
</P>
<P>
   In fiscal terms, the state is in more precarious shape than New
York City, largely because of the Albany addiction to enacting tax
cuts and spending programs that grow each year. Though the state is
also ending the current year with a surplus, estimated at $1.5
billion, it faces a deficit next year of $2.5 billion and more than
$5 billion the year after.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Joseph Bruno, majority leader of the
Republican-controlled state Senate, announced that despite the
projected deficit, he would push for a new program of
college-tuition tax breaks that, when fully implemented, would
drain $800 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic-controlled Assembly is expected to push for tax
cuts to encourage job growth upstate, and for more spending on
schools and early-childhood programs. Both sides have hinted that
they will seek money from the settlement with tobacco companies to
pay for their programs.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has not said what his own priorities will be. But as his
own office noted last week, it will be hard enough to preserve
previously enacted tax cuts and spending hikes without adding
costly new initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   The most prudent approach for the state would be similar to that
for the city: using the bonanza of surpluses to lower debts and
invest in the state's infrastructure, avoiding a lurch from deficit
to deficit and a scramble to make ends meet when the good times
stop rolling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-98 2048EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
