<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA'S KOCHER SKIPS TO HEAD OF THE CLASS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When UCLA's heralded freshman class gathered for
training camp in August, the unspoken consensus was that tailback
DeShaun Foster would become the first rookie to start. He had
superb talent and played a position without a returning starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the obvious choice, because you'd heard so much about
him,'' freshman nose guard Ken Kocher said. ``I certainly thought
it would be DeShaun.''
</P>
<P>
   Kocher didn't give himself much chance _ if not Foster, he
figured, then perhaps linebacker Robert Thomas or guard Mike Saffer
_ but he should have.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Micah Webb's career-threatening knee injury, Kocher
has beaten his classmates to that elusive first start and will join
the lineup against Wisconsin in the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's awesome,'' he said. ``It's too bad Micah got hurt, but it
put me in this position and I'm really excited. I can't wait. I'll
be pumped up like crazy, but I've got to think about it like any
other game and try not to let it get to me. I'll have to settle
down and concentrate.''
</P>
<P>
   An All-American last year at San Diego's Patrick Henry High,
Kocher was as well-regarded nationally as Foster, Thomas and
Saffer. He's big (6-foot-4, 295 pounds) and strong and moves well
for his size. He has split time with Webb since the second game and
is considered UCLA's run-stopper of the future.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, Kocher must help UCLA slow Wisconsin tailback
Ron Dayne, who rushed for 1,279 yards this season. That means
improving his separation skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to learn to separate from the offensive line and run
to the ball,'' Bruins coach Bob Toledo said. ``He has a tendency to
stay locked up (with linemen).''
</P>
<P>
   My brother the Badger: Reserve tight end Bryan Fletcher rooted
for Wisconsin over UCLA in the 1994 Rose Bowl, and for a very good
reason: his brother, Terrell, was a tailback for the Badgers and
rushed for 64 yards in Wisconsin's 21-16 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher did not attend the game for financial reasons but
watched it with siblings in his living room in St. Louis. He was a
freshman at Hazelwood East High School at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a gung-ho Badgers fan, and to me, UCLA was the bad
guy,'' he said. ``I never thought about coming to school here until
my senior year, when I got a (recruiting) letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd been to California to visit my brother (who plays for the
San Diego Chargers), and I liked the lifestyle and atmosphere. Then
I visited campus and decided this was the place for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher, a redshirt freshman, has played sparingly this season
behind seniors Mike Grieb and Ryan Neufeld. But he's the best
athlete among UCLA's seven tight ends and is expected to compete
with Gabe Crecion and Randy Hakes for the starting job next season.
</P>
<P>
   Injury update: Linebacker Brendon Ayanbadejo practiced this
weekend and will play in the Rose Bowl, although the sprained
ligaments in his left knee have not healed completely.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Pete Holland probably will play despite sprained
ligaments in his elbow that may require postseason surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Fullback Durell Price broke a rib against Miami and missed
several workouts following the game. A Sylmar native, Price will
play but has been replaced in the starting lineup by Westlake
senior Craig Walendy.
</P>
<P>
   Aliotti update: Toledo confirmed Sunday what he indicated two
weeks earlier _ that Nick Aliotti will be retained as the defensive
coordinator if he agrees to play more zone defense. They'll meet
after the Rose Bowl to discuss the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be some changes made,'' Toledo said. ``That's
something we have to talk about....
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't foresee any changes in the staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo update: UCLA chancellor Albert Carnesale, who spoke to
the Bruins after Saturday's practice, supports a new contract for
Toledo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is everybody wants it to happen, and
I'm confident it will,'' said Carnesale, who declined to give
details on length or dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said Toledo will receive a six- or seven-year rollover
deal worth approximately $600,000 per year, making him one of the
highest-paid coaches in the Pacific-10. (He's currently ninth, at
$453,000 per season.) However, it may be several weeks before the
contract is finalized.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-98 2056EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
