<HEADLINE>
`PATCH ADAMS' FILLS WINNING PRESCRIPTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The opening of Robin Williams' medical comedy
``Patch Adams'' generated healthy returns over the Christmas
holidays in the final weekend of a record-setting year for
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   The comedy brought in an estimated $25.5 million at 2,714
theaters during the Friday-Sunday period, continuing 1998's ongoing
strong performances from a wide variety of genres that have
generated close to $7 billion in domestic ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patch Adams,'' featuring Williams as a doctor using humor to
heal, represents the first hit for Universal Studios since ``The
Lost World: Jurassic Park'' opened in May 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``This certainly gives Universal a strong ending to a sour
year,'' said Robert Bucksbaum, president of the Reel Source
forecasting service, who predicted the film will eventually gross
$160 million.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Arthur Rockwell agreed that ``Patch Adams'' had
performed admirably, noting that six other films had taken in at
least $10 million over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a solid opening, particularly considering all the
competition,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Bucksbaum also pointed out that the ``Patch Adams'' victory
reflects moviegoers' strong appetite for comedies and noted that
``There's Something about Mary,'' ``Rush Hour'' and ``The
Waterboy'' have all posted results well above expectations during
the second half of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Sony's ``Stepmom,'' a drama with Julia Roberts and Susan
Sarandon, finished a strong second with $19.4 million at 2,358
theaters and will probably reach $100 million by the end of its
run.
</P>
<P>
   Studio spokesman Ed Russell said ``Stepmom'' beat internal
estimates and drew well from audience segments outside its core of
adult women.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of held-over films performed well in their second
weekends, with Warner Bros.' ``You've Got Mail'' finishing third
with $18.2 million at 2,759 screens, dropping just 1 percent from
last weekend, and DreamWorks SKG's ``The Prince of Egypt'' with
$15.4 million at 3,218 screens, representing a 5 percent gain.
</P>
<P>
   Bucksbaum said both had rebounded well after their results were
held down during the opening weekend by the distractions of
President Clinton's impeachment and the bombing of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Miramax's opening of ``The Faculty'' finished fifth with a
respectable $11.3 million at 2,365 screens as the battle between
high school students and teachers possessed by evil forces drew
well from teen-age moviegoers.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's family adventure ``Mighty Joe Young,'' an update on the
1949 original about a 15-foot gorilla, came in sixth with $10.5
million at 2,502 theaters. That edged out Disney's sixth weekend of
``A Bug's Life'' with $10 million at 2,456 screens, giving the
comedy $114 million overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think many people expected `Mighty Joe Young' to perform
better, but there were a lot of films for families,'' Rockwell
said, ``It was still a very good weekend with no major disasters.''
</P>
<P>
   Bucksbaum said the coming week should see continued strong
business among family films, adding, ``as long as there's no more
bombing or impeachment hearings, it will be smooth sailing.''
</P>
<P>
   Paramount's third weekend of ``Star Trek: Insurrection'' landed
in eighth place with $7.5 million at 2,677 theaters, followed by
Disney's sixth weekend of ``Enemy of the State'' with $5.2 million
at 1,505 screens and Warner's third weekend of ``Jack Frost'' with
$3.9 million at 2,142 theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Miramax's drama ``Down in the Delta'' posted lukewarm returns in
its opening with $1.7 million at 4,116 theaters. A pair of
well-received dramas performed well in their qualifying runs for
Academy Award consideration -- 20th Century Fox's ``The Thin Red
Line'' with $275,000 at five theaters and Disney's ``A Civil
Action'' with $67,000 at two theaters.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
