<SLUG> BC-RAC-SANTAANITA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAVONNIER RETURNS IN WINNING STYLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA _ Cavonnier, a footnote in Kentucky Derby lore, earned a
whole chapter in horse racing's veterinary history Sunday when he
rallied to win at Santa Anita in his first race in 2{ years.
</P>
<P>
   The one-length victory in the $81,225 Ack Ack Stakes culminated
an on-again, off-again comeback for the gelding who was pulled up
with a right-front-tendon injury in the June 8, 1996 Belmont
Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   It was an emotional return to the Santa Anita winner's circle
for the team of jockey Chris McCarron, trainer Bob Baffert and
breeder-owners Robert and Barbara Walter, for whom Cavonnier won
the '96 Santa Anita Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reached over and felt Chris McCarron's heart and it was
pounding away,'' Barbara Walter said. ``And I was going to say to
him, `Here, feel mine,' but ... I don't think Mr. Walter would have
liked that.''
</P>
<P>
   After his upset win in the '96 Santa Anita Derby, Cavonnier lost
by a nose to the fast-finishing Grindstone in the closest Kentucky
Derby finish in 38 years, and he might have won if he hadn't been
struck across the face by another horse's whip.
</P>
<P>
   Cavonnier finished fourth in the Preakness before getting hurt
in the Belmont. The injury was expected to end his career.
</P>
<P>
   But the Walters, who live with their horses on a ranch near
Santa Rosa, spent money and patience on an experimental treatment
for Cavonnier's bowed tendon. A drug with the abbreviated name
BAPN-F, injected by UC Davis veterinarian Carol Gillis, allowed the
tendon to heal with its elasticity intact.
</P>
<P>
   BAPN-F has since been put on the market and then withdrawn _ at
least temporarily _ because the first commercial batch caused undue
swelling in some horses.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Cavonnier was next to last in the five-horse field
before going around and between the leaders to win ahead of Sidon
and favored Tibado. The 5-year-old ran a solid 1:35.79 mile and
paid $6.
</P>
<P>
   McCarron said he couldn't remember winning with a horse coming
off such a long layoff.
</P>
<P>
   Said a relieved Baffert: ``It's very emotional for me to see a
horse like that come back. Everybody was worried, `Will he hold
together? What if something happens out there?' But I never would
have entered him if I thought there was a slight chance he'd
reinjure himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Walter spoke optimistically of challenging top horses in
the races leading to the March 6 Santa Anita Handicap. Baffert was
more cautious: ``I'm just going to play it by ear.''
</P>
<P>
   Later on Day 2 of the Santa Anita season, Baffert-trained
Magical Allure survived a stewards' inquiry to win the $200,000 La
Brea Stakes for 3-year-old fillies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
