<HEADER>
A7799 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GIRLS-SFCHRON-GIRLS &LR;      12-27 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIRLS-SF </SLUG>
 CHRON - GIRLS  
 GETTING GIRLS INTO THE BOYS' CLUB  &HT;     By Ilana DeBare 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Richard Tingey is proud to have half the seats in his computer
programming classes filled by girls.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't happen by accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get that many girls in the class, you have to recruit,''
said Tingey, who teaches computer science at Carlmont High School
in Belmont. ``I send them letters. I call them up. I tell them it's
a class about problem-solving, that a lot of kids do well in it and
that it gives them a big advantage in life.''
</P>
<P>
   Tingey is one of a small but growing number of Bay Area
educators who are actively working to involve girls in computer
programming _ trying to ensure that girls have an equal shot at the
technical jobs that are increasingly central to America's economy.
</P>
<P>
   These educators are facing a steep challenge. Nationally, only
17 percent of the students enrolled in advanced-placement (AP)
courses in computer science are girls.
</P>
<P>
   The California numbers are just slightly better: About one of
every four AP computer science students in this state is a girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Girls still tend to use computers for word processing rather
than for programming or for applications, which is where we believe
the careers of the future will be,'' said Maggie Ford, president of
the American Association of University Women Educational
Foundation, which issued a report this fall warning of a gender gap
in technology  &QL; 
education.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers who have studied technology education say there are
several reasons for the paucity of girls in computer classes and
clubs:
</P>
<P>
   _Most computer and video games still have violent themes geared
toward boys. So girls don't grow up routinely playing electronic
games and don't feel as comfortable as boys do when it comes to
experimenting with computers.
</P>
<P>
   _Despite the rising number of female high-tech executives,
computer programming still carries a stereotype of being a male
``geek'' profession.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; _Many schools teach computer programming as an end in itself,
divorced from other subjects. That's an approach that experts say
alienates many girls, who want to know how computers can be used in
their daily lives.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The result? Situations like the one at at Saratoga High
School, which offers more than a half-dozen elective computer
classes.
</P>
<P>
   Girls are well represented in Saratoga High's introductory
computer classes that teach basic keyboarding _ the 1990s
equivalent of typing.
</P>
<P>
   But only about five of the 30 students in Saratoga's Web design/
HTML class are girls, according to technology coordinator Mel
Holliday. Only three or four of the 30 students in its class on
computer-assisted design are girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think, `Gosh, here are all these boys, where are the
girls?''' said Holliday. ``We don't really have an answer. We think
about trying to change this, but we're not sure which way to go
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The picture isn't as bleak everywhere in the Bay Area. For
instance:
</P>
<P>
   _Presentation High School, an all-girls Catholic school in San
Jose, has students flocking to take its computer-art and desktop
publishing courses. It expanded its programming class from 20 to 30
students this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two of our graduates just wrote to tell me they've decided to
major in computer science because of our programming class,'' said
Adrienne Renner, technology coordinator at Presentation High.
</P>
<P>
   _Alvarado Elementary School in Union City launched an
after-school computer academy several years ago just for girls _
and the girls ended up teaching the rest of their classmates, male
and female, how to use the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   _Two dozen girls took part in an all-girls computer camp last
summer run by a Burlingame nonprofit called the Backyard Project.
Several now are working on after-school computer projects and
planning to major in computer science in college.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing to look at what computers are doing to the world
around us,'' said Roma Jhaveri, a senior at Carlmont High who
attended that  &LR; the computer camp and wants to pursue a career in
technology. ``They're revolutionizing the world. I want to be part
of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the Bay Area, the most ambitious initiatives to involve
girls in computers are coming from all-girl schools like
Presentation High and from nonprofit groups focused on girls, such
as the AAUW, Backyard Project or the YWCA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do a lot of work with low-income girls who don't have
computers at home and who have had no reason to think this field is
accessible to them,'' said Lauren Creamer of the Mid-Peninsula YWCA
in Palo Alto, which will hold a daylong technology workshop for
girls next month. ``We want to give them another option for their
lives besides cosmetology.''
</P>
<P>
   At coed public schools, the picture is much more spotty. Some
schools have individual teachers like Tingey who make an effort to
reach out to girls, but many don't.
</P>
<P>
   Other schools, like Alvarado Elementary, launch programs for
girls but drop them a couple of years later when funding runs out
or priorities change.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, few high-tech companies have taken a lead role in
trying to bridge the computer gender gap in schools.
</P>
<P>
   One local exception is Autodesk, which offers internship and
mentoring programs aimed specifically at girls.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers remain appalled at how little coordinated effort
is being made to give girls the technical skills that will be
central to the 21st century economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I was discouraged by was the lack of a lot of outcry
after the AAUW report,'' said Roberta Furger, a contributing editor
at PC World who recently wrote a book titled, ``Does Jane
Compute?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame to think that because of the choices we let girls
make in middle school or high school, they're closing off options
they might otherwise explore in college.''
</P>
<P>
   Others are more optimistic. They predict that educators will
rally to close the computer gender gap the same way they rallied to
increase girls' participation in math and science classes.
</P>
<P>
   During the past decade, numerous teachers and schools mounted
special efforts to keep girls involved in math and science
throughout high school. Those efforts paid off: The AAUW's recent
report noted that more girls enrolled in classes such as chemistry,
algebra and calculus in 1994 than in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we pushed in chemistry, biology and math, the numbers
have become close to even,'' said Jo Sanders, a researcher at the
Washington Research Institute in Seattle who has studied girls and
computers for more than a decade. ``Some things just need pushing,
and this is one of them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-98 2131EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
