<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981227.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-27 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7800 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GIRLSIDE-SFCHRON-GIRL     12-27 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIRLSIDE-SF </SLUG>
 CHRON - GIRLS SIDE  
 HOW TEACHERS ARE GETTING GIRLS PSYCHED UP ABOUT COMPUTER SCIENCE  &HT;     BY Ilana DeBare 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's the secret to bridging the gender gap in technology
education?
</P>
<P>
   For starters, girls often need a little extra encouragement to
become involved in computers.
</P>
<P>
   That can take the form of individualized recruitment, like
teacher Richard Tingey does at Carlmont High School in Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   It also can take the form of girls-only computer clubs or
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought an all-girls camp was going to be horrible, but it
was fun,'' said Kristen Russell, a Carlmont High senior who
attended just such a program an all-girls computer camp  &LR; last
summer run by the Backyard Project. ``It's less intimidating trying
to speak up. It's easier to ask questions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's less judgmental,'' added another camp attendee, Christina
Louie.
</P>
<P>
   Once they've managed to get girls into a computer club or class,
educators suggest a variety of teaching tactics:
</P>
<P>
   _Bringing women programmers into the classroom as role models.
</P>
<P>
   _Defusing girls' fears that they may break the computers by
experimenting or tinkering with them. For instance, Cathaleen (CQ)
 &LR; Hampton forced the members of her girls' computer club at Alvarado
Elementary School to solve small computer glitches themselves
rather than automatically asking for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before we started the academy, if there was a problem, they
were not comfortable attacking it themselves,'' Hampton said. ``I
called it a `learned helplessness.' So I had them work on fixing
little things like unplugged keyboards.''
</P>
<P>
   _Encouraging students to work together to solve computer
problems _ an approach that is more appealing to girls than the
stereotype of the lone programmer glued to a terminal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Computing should be a social activity and feature
communication just as much as the speedy finding of immense numbers
of resources,'' said Cornelia Brunner, associate director of the
Center for Children and Technology in New York.
</P>
<P>
   _Helping girls become technology leaders who train their
classmates or help run the school network.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can explain something to someone else, it does wonders
to boost your confidence,'' said Jennifer McGrath, a Stanford
University graduate student who has taught at both coed and
all-girl computer camps.
</P>
<P>
   _Integrating computer skills into other subjects such as history
or biology.
</P>
<P>
   This is particularly important, researchers say, because girls
get excited about computers when they see how they can be used to
accomplish real-world goals.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, computer camp alumnae Russell and Louie currently
are involved in an after-school project building a Web site to
promote a documentary film on successful businesswomen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; And at Presentation High School, a girls' school in San Jose,
students use computers in every aspect of academic life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our students use the computer for everything they do here,''
said Adrienne Renner, the school's technology coordinator. ``They
use the Internet for research, Powerpoint for oral reports,
multimedia programs for multimedia presentations. Girls take to it
like water, and it becomes just another tool.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-98 2131EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
