A7809 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-MOISE-NYT &LR;      12-27 0344
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MOISE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDWIN EVARISTE MOISE, 79, MATHEMATICS SCHOLAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La., Mich., Mass., S.C.)  (lb) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Edwin Evariste Moise, distinguished professor of
mathematics emeritus at Queens College and an author of textbooks,
who helped decipher German and Japanese military signals in World
War II, died Friday at St. Vincent's Hospital. He was 79 and lived
in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was complications following heart surgery, his family
said.
</P>
<P>
   Moise (pronounced mo-EEZ) specialized in topology, the
mathematical study of those properties of geometric figures that
remain unchanged under distortion, as with a Mobius strip.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote ``Introductory Problem Courses in Analysis and
Topology'' (Springer, 1982), ``Elementary Geometry from an Advanced
Standpoint'' (Addison Wesley, 3rd ed., 1990), ``Number Systems of
Elementary Math'' (Addison Wesley, 1966), ``Calculus, Part I''
(Addison Wesley, 1966) and other textbooks.
</P>
<P>
   Moise served on the faculty of Queens College from 1971 until
1987, and then devoted his time to studying 19th-century English
poetry.
</P>
<P>
   Born in New Orleans, Moise graduated from Tulane University in
1940 and received his Ph.D. in mathematics from the University of
Texas in 1947. During World War II, as a cryptanalyst in the Office
of the Chief of Naval Operations, he decoded enemy communications.
</P>
<P>
   From 1947 to 1960, Moise taught at the University of Michigan,
eventually becoming a professor. He was a professor of mathematics
at Harvard University before arriving at Queens College.
</P>
<P>
   He was a temporary member of the Institute for Advanced Study in
Princeton, N.J., (1949-51), and was also president of the
Mathematical Association of America and vice president of the
American Mathematical Society, as well as a fellow of the American
Academy of Arts and Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Moise is survived by Mary Leake Moise, whom he married in 1942;
a daughter, Claire Moise of Manhattan; a son, Edwin, of Clemson,
S.C.; and a grandson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
