<HEADER>
A7811 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTEL-SFCHRON-INTEL &LR;      12-27 1686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-EMPLOYEE TAKES ON INTEL IN COURT BATTLE OVER E-MAIL &HT;    BY DAN FOST
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - INTEL  c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle &HT;    Citrus Heights, Sacramento County _ Ken Hamidi was living the
<TEXT>
American dream, the one he fantasized about when he was a young man
in Tehran.
<P>
   He had a great engineering job with a company he loved, Intel
Corp. He traveled all over the world. He lived in a big house on
3.8 acres with a private lake.
</P>
<P>
   The dream didn't last. In the aftermath of a job-related auto
accident eight years ago and a bitter workers' compensation fight,
he lost his health, his job, his house. He declared bankruptcy,
mulled suicide, checked into a psychiatric hospital.
</P>
<P>
   But he still believed in the American dream. And now, as the
zealous foe of the company he once loved, Hamidi is locked in
constitutional battle against Intel of Santa Clara.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is whether Hamidi has the right to send thousands of
e-mails critical of Intel directly to Intel employees at their
offices.
</P>
<P>
   In a case that some First Amendment advocates fear could have a
broad chilling effect on free speech on the Internet, Intel already
has won a court order forbidding Hamidi from sending any more mass
e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   The case has pitted the world's most dominant maker of computer
chips, with revenues of $25 billion a year, against a bitter,
bankrupt ex-employee who can't even afford legal counsel.
</P>
<P>
   But in a way, Hamidi presents a formidable match.
</P>
<P>
   He was well-trained by Intel, and in his current battle, he is
calling on the very qualities that the company values.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, he is rigidly determined. Dave Hurd, a
Placerville attorney who has been helping him pro bono, refers to
his ``maniacal devotion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am obsessed,'' Hamidi said. ``Obsessed with freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Obsessed, also, with Intel.
</P>
<P>
   Like Intel's Chairman Andy Grove, who wrote ``Only the Paranoid
Survive,'' Hamidi maintains an abiding wariness. (Investigators
hired by Intel captured Hamidi on videotape changing tires, at a
time when Hamidi pursued a workers' compensation claim against the
company; he believes that the investigators slashed his tires to
obtain the footage.)
</P>
<P>
   Also like Grove, who is a former Hungarian refugee, Hamidi is an
immigrant who achieved success in America that he could only dream
of in his homeland.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Ken Hamidi is not Andy Grove. Grove's brilliance is
legendary, and during his tenure as Intel's chief executive,
revenues grew eightfold and the stock price grew 120 times. He
escaped first the Nazis and then the Communists; today, he holds
roughly $250 million in Intel stock.
</P>
<P>
   Hamidi said he earned $50,000 in his peak days at Intel, which
is not even particularly high by engineering standards.
</P>
<P>
   Court records in Hamidi's workers' compensation case indicate
that he has had some problems telling the truth. The state Workers'
Compensation Appeals Board found that Hamidi had lied to his
doctors numerous times. The board also found that he had lied on a
home-loan application, in a letter to a court seeking dismissal of
a speeding ticket and even in a deposition.
</P>
<P>
   The board said Hamidi covered up business failures, a lawsuit
his wife had filed, his wife's miscarriage, the extent of his
disability, his reckless driving and the circumstances under which
he lost his home.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hamidi offered various explanations for his statements,
including his desperation to keep his job and to gain his doctors'
sympathy, he also said his honesty is not at issue in this latest
case, as both he and Intel agree that he sent the offending
e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   In the case at hand, Intel does not make an issue of the content
of Hamidi's e-mail. But outside the courtroom, the company says
Hamidi _ in his e-mail and on his Web site at
 &LR; www.igc.apc.org/faceintel/ &LR;  _ is spreading lies.
</P>
<P>
   For example, while Intel recently announced it would reduce its
workforce by 3,000 people, in an e-mail Hamidi insists that the
actual number is 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   In an open letter on the Web site, he tells Intel CEO Craig
Barrett: ``Mr. Barrett, if you really want to thank and appreciate
your employees just stop lying to them, cheating them, and do not
axe them to show higher profits.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had people named in there who are defamed,'' said Coeta
Chambers, Intel's human resources attorney. But suing Hamidi for
defamation is ``a much more difficult issue,'' she said. ``If you
sue over the Web site, all that would do is draw more attention to
the Web site. Then he would withdraw the material that was
defamatory. He would repost it and change one or two words to say,
`This is my opinion.'''
</P>
<P>
   Intel has asked Sacramento Superior Court Judge John R. Lewis
for summary judgment. On December 18, Lewis set a court date of
April 15 to give Hamidi time for discovery.
</P>
<P>
   By then, Hamidi may have legal counsel. The American Civil
Liberties Union and the Electronic Frontier Foundation will meet
next month to decide whether they want to jump into the case on his
behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Hamidi is a handsome, well-dressed man. At 51, some gray has
crept into his temples, but the rest of his perfectly combed hair
remains inky black.
</P>
<P>
   He rents a comfortable two-story stucco house on a corner lot in
Citrus Heights, a Sacramento suburb 10 miles from Intel's Folsom
campus, where he used to work. In one living room, a Persian rug
and a Christmas tree accent tasteful decorations. Down a few steps
in another living room, his daughter and two friends cuddle on a
couch and watch a wide-screen TV.
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs, Hamidi maintains a small cluttered office. News
clippings of his fight against Intel are piling up. At his Compaq
computer, he works on his Web page for his loosely knit
organization, Former and Current Employees of Intel, or FACE Intel,
which he says has about 100 participants.
</P>
<P>
   As he discusses his case, he lapses into cliches. He evokes 1776
and the American revolution and says he's a ``pioneer on the new
frontier, the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This case is going to determine if all of us, if any one of
us, have any right to freedom of speech on the Internet or not,''
Hamidi said.
</P>
<P>
   Like many immigrants, he believes that Americans take their
freedom for granted. As a naturalized U.S. citizen, he attributes
his fervor to his experiences in Iran.
</P>
<P>
   As a boy in Tehran, Hamidi's father was a real estate agent and
his mother a housewife. He married his high school sweetheart in
1971, and they now have two daughters, ages 23 and 14.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the Iranian Air Force when he was about 20 years old.
He said he signed up for a four-year tour of duty but was kept in
beyond that term and fought for eight years to get out.
</P>
<P>
   He ultimately left the Air Force in 1978 at age 31. With his
wife and daughter, he moved to California and became a travel agent
specializing in trips to Iran.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  By the following year, the Shah of Iran had been toppled and
U.S. embassy employees were taken hostage. Although Hamidi was
safely in the United States, his travel business shriveled:
Iranians were no longer visiting their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   He took night classes at National University in Sacramento,
earning a bachelor's degree in manufacturing technology and a
master's in business administration.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, he started work at Intel's Folsom plant as Intel's
liaison to European automakers, selling them on using Intel chips
in their cars and resolving manufacturing problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very sensitive work, and I was very good at it,'' he
said. ``I worked very, very long hours. I was extremely dedicated
and extremely loyal to the company. I loved Intel very much.''
</P>
<P>
   Intel attorney Chambers wouldn't discuss Hamidi's work record,
except to say there were ``no employment issues.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; While at Intel, Hamidi bought a 4,200-square-foot house in
Loomis, on 3.8 fully landscaped acres with a small lake, a boat, a
waterfall. He had a 2,500-square-foot barn, three cars, a truck,
two tractors and animals.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 20, 1990, as he drove back from a conference in
Arizona, his car was rear-ended. ``Unfortunately, I was still at
work,'' he said. ``I was on company time. And that is what
destroyed my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite back and neck injuries, he didn't take leave from his
job, he said, working for 18 months even though he was taking large
doses of the pain-killer Vicodin and suffering from sleep
deprivation, pain and depression.
</P>
<P>
   His duties were reduced, and he ultimately went on leave. In
1995, Intel notified him that he was terminated.
</P>
<P>
   He fought back, filing a wrongful-termination suit, which he
later withdrew, and a workers' compensation suit. Although he won
the first round of the workers' compensation claim, Intel won on
appeal, and Hamidi's appeal to a higher court was rejected.
</P>
<P>
   But Hamidi had other weapons, especially as the Internet sprang
to life. He began to attack Intel on his Web page, and he
periodically sent mass e-mails to Intel employees.
</P>
<P>
   Intel has cut off employees' access to his Web site, and each
time he sent an e-mail, Intel then blocked mail from that server.
But Hamidi, undaunted, kept using different computers and host
accounts to send his messages.
</P>
<P>
   When Hamidi sent his sixth e-mail, in March, Intel warned him to
stop. In October, he sent a seventh message, to about 29,000
employees, and Intel filed suit.
</P>
<P>
   The suit is all he has at the moment; his wife works part time,
and he is unemployed and still taking Vicodin. He's probably
unemployable because of his increasing notoriety _ What company
would look at Hamidi's Web site and invite him to work for them?
</P>
<P>
   Which begs the question: Why does he do it? Why doesn't he move
on with his life? How can he spend his daughters' college-education
money in order to pursue his quest?
</P>
<P>
   ``This happened to a person who is passionate about his
freedom,'' Hamidi said. ``I am not only concerned with material
things. I have the desire, drive and determination of a pioneer. I
talked to my family. I will fight this injustice up to the point
I'm alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way I can live with myself,'' Hamidi said, ``is if I
fight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
