<HEADER>
A7812 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTELSIDE-SFCHRON-INT     12-27 0485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTELSIDE-SF </SLUG>
 CHRON - INTEL  
CRUX OF INTEL CASE _ IS IT SPAM OR TRESPASSING? &HT;    By Dan Fost
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR; In Internet jargon, spam is defined as massive, unsolicited
commercial e-mail. Most Internet users agree: Spam is bad.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's protected as free speech under the Constitution and
whether it can be defined by its content, are questions that are
arising in legislatures and, possibly, in court as part of the case
of Intel Corp. versus Ken Hamidi.
</P>
<P>
   On seven occasions, Hamidi sent mass e-mails to as many as
29,000 Intel employees. He wasn't hawking pornography or
get-rich-quick schemes, the most common types of spam.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he offered his spin on Intel policies and actions _ and
Intel found his opinions as obnoxious as any smutty spam.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Intel doesn't like what Hamidi has to say, however,
the company's lawsuit is not focusing on his content. Instead,
Intel claims that Hamidi's spam trespasses into the company's
computer system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think he's crossed that line between free speech and
invasion of private property,'' said Intel spokesman Chuck Mulloy.
</P>
<P>
   The Electronic Frontier Foundation and the American Civil
Liberties Union are considering entering the case on Hamidi's
behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't see it as spam,'' said Shari Steele, an attorney with
the San Francisco-based Electronic Frontier Foundation. ``We see it
as Intel upset about someone with a message for their employees. It
wasn't like he was using their resources. He didn't hack into their
system. He used the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Intel human resources attorney Coeta Chambers said that just
because the company is connected to the Internet ``does not
transform our workplace into a public forum, any more than the fact
that I can drive onto a city street means you can drive onto our
property and distribute leaflets.''
</P>
<P>
   If Hamidi were to send his messages via the U.S. Postal Service
_ ``snail mail,'' in the lingo of the digerati _ Chambers said
Intel would not be obliged to deliver it to employees. ``We're not
required to use our internal system to deliver mail to
individuals,'' Chambers said.
</P>
<P>
   That may be true, said Barry Steinhardt, the outgoing president
of the EFF and an associate director of the ACLU.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nor are they under obligation to deliver his electronic
mail,'' Steinhardt said. ``The question is, could they go to court
prohibiting Hamidi from using the U.S. Postal Service to deliver
his mail? The question is, can Intel invoke the power of the
government?''
</P>
<P>
   Steele, the EFF attorney, said Hamidi's case is different than a
typical spam case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually when you are talking about spam, you are talking about
a marketer who doesn't really know the people he's sending messages
to. The message is random,'' she said. ``This was a directed
mailing. It was not for marketing purposes. Instead, it was a
criticism.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-98 2138EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
