u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OCTUPLETS-DEATH-HNS &LR;      12-27 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OCTUPLETS-DEATH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEART, BREATH TROUBLES CLAIM TINIEST OCTUPLET/
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  A SECOND HAS INTESTINAL SURGERY; TWO OTHERS BACK ON VENTILATORS
<TEXT>
<P>
   By T.J. MILLING &QL; 
c. 1998
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
HOUSTON CHRONICLE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The tiniest of Houston's octuplets, the girl Chijindu
Chidera, whose name meant ``God has my life,'' died Sunday, while a
sister recovered from surgery and two other siblings had to be put
back on ventilators.
</P>
<P>
   The other four were breathing on their own but still in critical
condition, according to a Texas Children's Hospital statement.
Mother Nkem Chukwu was strong enough to visit her infants shortly
before her fifth-born, nicknamed Odera, died of heart and lung
failure at 3:23 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very saddened by the passing of our beloved baby,
Odera,'' said a statement from Chukwu and the octuplets' father,
Iyke Louis Udobi. ``She is now safe with God in heaven, and we
remain most grateful to Him for having blessed our lives with hers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our sincere gratitude goes out to the doctors, nurses,
therapists and others who worked tirelessly to help Odera in her
battle for life against what turned out to be overwhelming
obstacles.''
</P>
<P>
   Odera, who weighed 10.3 ounces or 320 grams at birth, was the
size of a Beanie Baby, doctors have said _ 124 grams lighter than
the smallest baby ever to survive at Texas Children's.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors believe her underdevelopment may have been caused by
crowding in her mother's womb.
</P>
<P>
   Odera's condition began to deteriorate Saturday afternoon, the
hospital statement said, six days after she, four sisters and two
brothers were born by Caesarean section. Another girl was born
naturally two weeks before the seven, making them the first known
set of surviving octuplets.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors had moved Odera from a conventional ventilator to an
oscillator in an attempt to increase the oxygen in her blood, the
statement said. The treatment failed, her heartbeat began to slow,
and neither medication nor manual chest compression could save her.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the youngest infant, Gorom, was recovering from
surgery Saturday to repair a hole in her intestine, the statement
said. In addition, Ebuka, the girl born Dec. 8, and Ikem, the first
boy born Dec. 20, had to be put back on mechanical respirators.
</P>
<P>
   Chukwu had miscarried triplets earlier this year. Like the
octuplets, they were the product of powerful fertility drugs,
doctors said.
</P>
<P>
   Fertility specialists maintain that improper administration of
the drugs is to blame for multiple fetuses that pose major health
threats to mother and children.
</P>
<P>
   When Chukwu became pregnant again with so many embryos, she was
referred to obstetrician/gynecologist Brian Kirshon, who
specializes in high-risk births at St. Luke's Episcopal Hospital.
Kirshon has said that Chukwu was offered a ``reduction'' _ a
procedure to remove some of the embryos to give the others a better
chance of surviving _ but declined.
</P>
<P>
   Chukwu, 29, and Udobi, 41, whose name appears as Iyke Paul Louis
Jr. on his driver's license, are naturalized U.S. citizens from
Nigeria. He has said that they were married about five years ago in
ceremonies both in Nigeria and before a judge here.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 22, when Chukwu was four months' pregnant with the
octuplets, Udobi was charged with misdemeanor assault in an
incident involving Chukwu's mother, Janet.
</P>
<P>
   Houston police records show that he was arrested at the couple's
home in the 8600 block of Dawnridge on suspicion of hitting and
biting Janet Chukwu and of threatening to break Nkem Chukwu's hands
and kick her in the back.
</P>
<P>
   He was released on $1,500 bail a week later. Trial is set for
Feb. 8. The maximum punishment for a conviction would be a year in
jail and a $4,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   Udobi has called the incident a misunderstanding that was worked
out.
</P>
<P>
   About two weeks after the incident, Chukwu was admitted to St.
Luke's and put on drugs to stop her uterus from contracting,
doctors have said. She also was kept on an incline with her head
down to take pressure off her cervix and delay birth as long as
possible, which would improve the infants' chances of survival.
</P>
</TEXT>
