<SLUG> BC-NETFILES-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NET FILES/JON SWARTZ  
 EXPERTS GIVE GLIMPSE INTO NET'S FUTURE
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - THE NET FILES   &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The information age is on the cusp of the millennium. Are you
ready for robotic Internet search engines, voice-activated Web
surfing and airtight online security?
</P>
<P>
   Before you laugh off these potential technical advances as
sci-fi drivel, consider this: Many of these ideas and concepts are
being hashed out by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), an
international organization of 250 companies, government agencies
and universities that sets the technical blueprints for many of the
Internet's advances.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Microsoft, IBM and others closely follow the W3C and
produce their own products based on its schematics.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, we asked Web luminaries to drag out their
crystal balls and offer a glimpse into the immediate future. Here
is what they see:
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Bots.  &LR; Imagine individualized search engines on personal
computers that roam the vast expanses of cyberspace in search of
specific information on other personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   A user in San Jose, for example, would program their PC to find
references to 1962 Ferrari GTO models for sale. Meanwhile, users in
other parts of the country who are attempting to sell that model
would program their computers to find prospective online buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Search engines powered by independent agents on each PC then
would index information over the Web and make a match between
corresponding computers.
</P>
<P>
   The ``bot'' concept, short for robotic computers, isn't too
farfetched, says Tim Berners-Lee, the MIT professor who is one of
the Web's founders. He calls the technology illustrative of the
so-called Phase II of Internet communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phase I is about people communicating over the Web,''
Berners-Lee says. ``Phase II is about computers interacting with
one another over the Net with no human intervention.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Security.  &LR; W3C currently is working on something called
Platform for Privacy Preference, which will allow Netizens to
dictate how much information is collected by Internet service
providers about their online shopping habits, according to
Berners-Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Berners-Lee says online security is now more of a
dilemma for governments because individuals can communicate
secretly. ``It's nearly impossible for somebody else to find out
what you're saying,'' he says. ``The biggest problem with applying
security isn't that the technology isn't strong enough _ it's that
governments are so frightened of it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; XML.  &LR; Widely regarded as the successor to HTML, the Web's
``lingua franca,'' XML is a formatting language for ``tagging''
documents. It will let consumers perform detailed online searches
at neck-snapping speed and efficiency, says Don DePalma, an analyst
at Forrester Research in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Web surfers will be able to conduct extremely narrow searches,
DePalma says, because specific items will be listed under themed
categories. For example, someone looking just for search results on
the movie ``Frenzy'' would click on a topic group called ``Alfred
Hitchcock.''
</P>
<P>
   This technology already is in limited used by search engines and
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Work-flow technology. &LR;  Software that automates business
operations eventually will be heavily used to expedite Web
site-publishing processes.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; High-tech hodgepodge.  &LR; Other potential technologies on the
horizon: voice-activated software for Web surfing, and
more-sophisticated server software for e-commerce transactions.
Market researchers also predict a quantum leap in blur-fast cable
modem sales next year, from about 500,000 units in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Whiz-bang &UR;  &LR; gadgetry aside, Internet observers caution that
consumers shouldn't get too caught up in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corporations and consumers are equally concerned about
increasing the Net's stability before making technological
advances,'' DePalma adds. ``They want to make the best use of
existing technology.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Cyber bumper sticker.  &LR; Speaking of the immediate future, a San
Francisco man with no political affiliation to Vice President Al
Gore has registered the following domain names:  &LR; gorebradley.org &LR; , &LR; 
gorebradley2000.org &LR; ,  &LR; gorefeinstein.org &LR; ,
 &LR; gorefeinstein2000.org &LR; , &LR;  goredaley.org &LR; ,  &LR; goredaley2000.org &LR; ,
 &LR; gorekerry.org &LR;  and &LR;  gorekerry2000.org &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   His point? Ted Weinstein, a 36-year-old high-tech communications
consultant, spent about $1,000 for the naming rights before they
got into the hands of political dirty tricksters. And he wants to
pass them onto Gore, an early champion of the Web _ but not
necessarily a practitioner of registering domain names.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised that someone touting himself as Mr. Tech Savvy
has not locked up these names for use on the Web during the 2000
presidential campaign,'' Weinstein said. ``Gore has been prepping
(for the presidency) his whole life, and yet he has ignored a basic
element of his campaign. I'd just like to pass these names on to
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Geez, my 67-year-old father has his own domain name,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   A vice presidential spokesman did not return phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Sites of the week. &LR;   &LR; If you're in the mood for monkeying
around, check out &LR;  www.chimpnet.com &LR; . Better yet, get a unique view
of Monica Lewinsky at  &LR; www.bossdog.com/java-photo-lab &LR; 
 &LR; /mona.html &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-98 2141EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
