<HEADLINE>
IRAQ VOWS TO CANCEL OIL-FOR-FOOD PLAN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Iraq ratcheted up its confrontation with the United
Nations Sunday, vowing to end the internationally monitored
oil-for-food program and to eject the UN personnel running it.
</P>
<P>
   Eight days after President Clinton halted a military strike
against Iraq, Saddam Hussein's government defiantly refused to make
concessions to critics and gloried in sympathetic words from a
meeting of Arab legislators.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's pronouncement followed a threat Saturday to shoot down
US and British warplanes patrolling no-fly zones in northern and
southern Iraq. The United States said it would knock out Iraqi
antiaircraft batteries if fired upon.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, the White House called Iraq's latest move an
example of how the international community cares more about Iraq's
people than does Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman P.J. Crowley also said the Iraqi comments
served to justify US support for Iraqi groups seeking to topple
Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we are supporting the Iraqi opposition,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The comments, by Trade Minister Mohammed Mehdi Saleh, did not
specify when it would stop the humanitarian program or force out
the UN employees overseeing it. The next part of the oil-for-food
deal, created to avert hunger and disease, is scheduled to expire
in four months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Iraq refuses the continuation of this project and demands the
lifting of sanctions,'' Saleh said as he called for the ``ouster''
of 400 UN personnel administering the program.
</P>
<P>
   Under the oil-for-food program, Iraq is allowed to sell oil and
use the money to buy staples abroad. Iraq views the program as
interference by the United Nations, but the United States maintains
that strict controls are necessary to keep Iraq from using oil
money to buy weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The two-year-old program will allow Iraq to sell $5.2 billion in
oil in the six-month period that ends in April. One-third of the
money is reserved to pay for the UN monitors and to help victims of
Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait and the Persian Gulf War that
followed.
</P>
<P>
   Also Sunday, Iraqi Vice President Taha Yassin Ramadan reiterated
that antiaircraft gunners were prepared to target the American and
British planes that make regular overflights above the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Violating Iraqi airspace is an aggression,'' he said. ``The
so-called farce of no-fly zones must end. The so-called no-fly
zones only exist in the British and American imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   Iraq reportedly fired at a British jet after it was out of
range, and US officials said they take the threats seriously. A
senior US official responded to Ramadan's warning by saying, ``The
Iraqis know what the rules are.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As President Clinton said at the end of Desert Fox, we will
enforce the `no-fly' zone,'' the official told the Los Angeles
Times. ``Our pilots will take all actions necessary to protect
themselves, and we take this as a very serious matter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hussein wants to maintain a sense of confrontation,'' another
senior administration official said. ``He's trying to create a
sympathy card. It also helps to keep alive a sense of Iraq, the
unconquered.''
</P>
<P>
   Other provocations, including Baghdad's rejection of all UN
weapons inspections after the punishing four-day air attacks by the
United States and Britain and its refusal last week to allow any
more UN planes to fly to Iraq, had already led Washington to
conclude that a second confrontation is virtually inevitable. The
only issues are timing and the specific flash point, The Los
Angeles Times quoted US officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
   The no-fly zones were established after the Persian Gulf War in
1991 to stop Saddam Hussein's air strikes against Shiite Muslims in
the south and Kurdish rebels in the north.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq has already said that it will not allow another group of UN
inspectors, who monitor arms production and storage, to return to
work.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators from 16 Arab countries harshly criticized the
70-hour bombing of Iraq, saying it made life worse for ordinary
Iraqis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The aggression on Iraq represents a dangerous policy which is
against international law and shakes regional and international
security,'' Fathi Sorour, the head of the Arab Parliamentary Union,
told an emergency session of the group in Amman, Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Kuwait, which is suspicious of Hussein, did not participate. In
Cairo, a newspaper said that Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
blamed Hussein for provoking the four days of airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, Republicans have toned down their
criticism of the airstrikes, which several leaders had suggested
were timed to deflect attention from impeachment hearings. So, too,
have officials from Republican administrations.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on Fox News Sunday, former secretary of state Lawrence
Eagleburger said he initially found the timing odd, but was
satisfied after a talk with the current secretary, Madeleine K.
Albright.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Material from the Associated Press also was used in this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
