<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-BAND-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAIN BRINGS STARRING ROLE IN ROSE PARADE FOR STUDENT BAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVID R. BAKER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Musical notes spattered into the cold morning air
above Dodger Stadium as members of the All-District marching band
tried to warm up their lips.
</P>
<P>
   These top student musicians were selected from high schools
throughout Los Angeles for the honor of marching in the Tournament
of Roses Parade. But one day last week, they stood shivering in the
stadium parking lot, while their friends slept. They ran through
tunes for the parade and marched circles around the empty stadium
to build stamina, while their classmates shopped for presents.
</P>
<P>
   Tough work under any circumstances, but well worth it, the
students insisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that you're seen around the world -- that might scare
some people,'' said drum major Chris Johnson, 18, from Chatsworth
High School in the suburban San Fernando Valley area of Los
Angeles. ``But when you're out there and the band's all behind you,
you don't think about anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Come rain, frost or Santa Ana winds, somehow the band always
pulls together by parade day, organizers and players say.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least we don't have lips sticking to mouthpieces or
anything like that,'' said Reggie Smith, one of the band's
directors.
</P>
<P>
   For 26 consecutive years, the best brass and percussion players
from throughout the Los Angeles Unified School District have
marched in the parade as a single band, technically known as the
All-District High School Honors Band but usually called All-City.
For brass, getting there takes a recommendation from a high school
music director. For percussionists, drum majors and flag carriers,
admission to the band comes only through an audition.
</P>
<P>
   Those who make the cut face months of serious work. Saturday
rehearsals in October and November give way to daily practice once
break begins. District buses collect students from across the
sprawling city and deposit them at 9 a.m. on the cold concrete
parking lots. Practice lasts six hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go home, get in bed at 8, wake up and think, not again,''
said Jennifer Johnson, 18, a senior at Chatsworth High School.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the pain brings a big payoff: a starring role in a parade
televised across the globe and seen by several hundred million
people.
</P>
<P>
   The parade route runs six miles, so the students march around
the stadium for hours at a time to build up strength. Directors
work their musicians with a mixture of encouragement and abuse,
constantly pushing for a cleaner, sharper sound.
</P>
<P>
   Slacking off won't fly. Catching one trombone player noodling
aimlessly during practice, director Gregory Robinson sent him
running to the far end of the parking lot, perhaps 200 yards away,
with instrument in hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take a lap!'' Robinson yelled.
</P>
<P>
   The band's five tunes for the parade are taken apart, worked
over measure by measure, then reassembled. If trumpets have
problems with the syncopated swing of ``Jump, Jive and Wail,'' they
don't move on until they can play it clean.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard an extra note in there,'' Robinson called. ``You're
gonna go to Hades for that.''
</P>
<P>
   The players know the weak spots. Alberto Guardado, 15, a
sophomore at Monroe High School in the San Fernando Valley
community of North Hills, said the group needs to tighten up its
turns and its high-stepping marching technique, a more rigorous
style than most schools use.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting there,'' he said, noting in the next breath that
one of his friends is on a cruise to Mexico while he practices.
</P>
<P>
   But the drills pay off. After several hours of play Wednesday,
the musicians warmed up literally and physically, some of them
sweating in the cold. The notes came out cleaner. The band sounded
bigger, tighter, louder.
</P>
<P>
   And for its players, anticipation of parade day, with its
television cameras and immense crowds, was already building.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I work this hard, I'd better be seen,'' Jennifer Johnson
said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
