</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BEST IS YET TO COME _ MAYBE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Again, we bow down to whoever choreographed
nineteen hundred-and-uh-ninety-eight, the greatest sports year in
history.
</P>
<P>
   -According to Sports Illustrated, the greatest sports magazine
in history.
</P>
<P>
   What's left to say about it except...
</P>
<P>
   (Take a deep breath)...
</P>
<P>
   Now get over your bad self.
</P>
<P>
   In this hole, we !ital!predict rather than !ital!reflect _ it's
all in the title _ so anything that happened in the last 12 months
is all fine and dandy and sweet as candy, but we've got better
things to look ahead to.
</P>
<P>
   Or do we?
</P>
<P>
   Let's just say if we were headed to, say, Debbie Reynolds'
Vegas-Style Sports Book of Exotic Dancers and/or Wagers with a
handful of those new counterfeit-looking $20 bills, we'd have no
trouble putting down a wager or two on the stuff we see as
guaran-darn-teed to happen in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Like:
</P>
<P>
   _The NFL awards the next expansion franchise to Los Angeles. The
city embraces the news with overwhelming apathy, wrought with
ambiguity....
</P>
<P>
   _Kevin Brown claims the National League Cy Young Award based on
his 26 wins, 1.18 ERA and 287 strikeouts. The Dodgers, who average
0.51 runs every time Brown takes the hill, finish second in the NL
West behind Orel Hershiser and the poor, penniless San Diego
Padres....
</P>
<P>
   _The Denver Broncos and John Elway pull it together, beat _
who's it gonna be, Minnesota? _ in Super Bowl
Whatever-Roman-Numerals-They-Throw-Up-There, and No.7 finally
retires to become the Cal Worthington of the Rocky Mountains....
</P>
<P>
   _Tyson-Holyfield III, but only under Marques of Queensbury
rules....
</P>
<P>
   _The Raiders move to Florida and retire....
</P>
<P>
   _Doug Flutie's NFL career goes soggy....
</P>
<P>
   _ Dan Dierdorf leaves ``Monday Night Football.'' Pig Latin
becomes a disappearing dialect....
</P>
<P>
   _Shaquille O'Neal's next CD effort, ``Rap-sody in Shaq,'' comes
up short of gold or platinum sales, but he's content with steel....
</P>
<P>
   _Michael Jordan cologne starts to really stink....
</P>
<P>
   _Dennis Rodman begins dating again....
</P>
<P>
   _Howie Long's next movie _ co-starring with Jean-Claude Van
Damme in ``Damn, We're Good'' _ fails again to get him a People's
Choice nomination....
</P>
<P>
   _George Seifert turns in his CBS microphone, but when the NFL
jobs aren't there, he decides to co-host ``The New Almost Anything
Goes!'' with Charlie Jones....
</P>
<P>
   _The WNBA goes on strike....
</P>
<P>
   _The CBA goes on strike....
</P>
<P>
   _David Stern has a stroke....
</P>
<P>
   _Kobe Bryant grows all the way up....
</P>
<P>
   _The New York Yankees repeat as baseball's champions, but Joe
DiMaggio isn't around to enjoy it....
</P>
<P>
   _Professional snowboarding becomes a year-round sport....
</P>
<P>
   _Mark McGwire replaces Whoopi Goldberg as center square during
the two months he misses from the season to rehab his back....
</P>
<P>
   _Kareem Abdul-Jabbar finally gets his star on the Hollywood Walk
of Fame for his work in ``Slam Dunk Ernest.'' Bruce Jenner cries
for justice, claiming he was in both ``Grambling's White Tiger''
and ``Can't Stop the Music''....
</P>
<P>
   _The U.S. House, Senate and Supreme Court censure Karl
Malone....
</P>
<P>
   _The estate of Harry Caray uncovers 157,000 unused Budweiser
Points, which are cashed in for 39 foosball tables....
</P>
<P>
   _Bud Selig doesn't reinstate Pete Rose, but allows him to praise
the ground Selig walks on....
</P>
<P>
   _And it's time you face it: the Publishers Clearing House Prize
Patrol will not crash your Super Bowl party. Again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
