<HEADLINE>
KING NEED ONE GOOD STREAK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Among the Los Angeles Kings' many problems this
season has been a distressing inability to beat the teams they most
need to beat, namely the other four teams in the NHL's Pacific
Division.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings are 0-2 against the Mighty Ducks, 0-1 against San
Jose, 0-1 against Dallas and 0-3 against the Phoenix Coyotes. The
Coyotes defeated the Kings 2-1 on Saturday night and the teams meet
again tonight in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, en route to a 38-33-11 record and their first
playoff berth since 1993, the Kings recorded precisely half their
victories against the Pacific Division, which last season included
Colorado, Edmonton, Calgary and Vancouver and did not include
Dallas and Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings were 19-11-2 in 32 games against the Pacific Division
last year, compared to this year's miserable 0-7 start. The Kings
have 17 games remaining against their division this season,
including tonight's game and Wednesday's visit by the Sharks.
</P>
<P>
   But more than anything, the Kings (10-21-3) must soon embark on
a lengthy unbeaten streak if they are going to get back into the
race for one of the final Western Conference playoff berths.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to make a move,'' coach Larry Robinson said,
``we're going to have to put a bunch of wins together.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one hot streak can carry a team for an entire season, as
the Kings learned just last year. One timely 13-game stretch in the
82-game season got the Kings into last year's playoffs. From the
start of last season through Jan. 10, the Kings were a mediocre
17-19-8. From Feb. 28 through the end of the season, the Kings were
an equally uninspiring 11-13-1. But from Jan. 12 through Feb. 26,
the Kings were 10-1-2, a stretch that made up for the doldrums of
the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, right around this time, we went on a long streak,''
Robinson said. ``That's what we kind of need right now.''
</P>
<P>
   New assignment: The Kings are expected to assign rookie winger
Josh Green to Springfield of the AHL today. He did not travel with
the Kings to Phoenix. In 26 games, Green has one goal and three
assists. He was a healthy scratch the past three games.
</P>
<P>
   Expectant dad: Winger Dan Bylsma did not accompany the Kings on
the trip, either. Bylsma's wife, Mary Jane, is about to give birth
to the couple's first child.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-98 2249EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
