<HEADLINE>
TROJANS FEEL HORNED HEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL PASO _ The teams have barely met, but there's already some
tension between USC and Texas Christian as they head toward
Thursday's encounter in the Sun Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   During a barbecue Saturday night, the teams' first official
introduction to each other, they started to get on each others'
nerves.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were a little cocky,'' linebacker David Gibson said.
``Which will be nice. It'll be more fun to play them now.''
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment was echoed by quarterback Carson Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a little bit of hostility,'' he said. ``You can tell
it's going to be a good game.''
</P>
<P>
   Such predications will be a relief to the Sun Bowl, which has
been taking heat for providing a mismatch on paper between the 8-4
Trojans and 6-5 Horned Frogs.
</P>
<P>
   TCU players, who are thrilled to experience the school's first
bowl game in four years, have been constantly asked if they are
surprised that USC players were not feeling similar joy after
receiving their bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea how USC feels about this bowl game, but all I
can tell you is we're happy to be here,'' TCU linebacker Joseph
Phipps said.
</P>
<P>
   USC coach Paul Hackett said he didn't believe the Trojans were
ever lackadaisical toward the Sun Bowl or TCU.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's all a bunch of bunk,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson sprains ankle: Gibson left practice early after spraining
his ankle, but said he thinks he'll still be able to start.
</P>
<P>
   Tailback Chad Morton did not practice to rest his sore ankle.
Defensive tackle Aaron Williams (sprained ankle) will probably be
available for only limited duty, Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Soward statement: Wide receiver R. Jay Soward admitted last week
that he is leaning toward turning pro, but doesn't want anyone to
think his mind is made up yet.
</P>
<P>
   He's been put off by speculation recently that he has already
decided to turn pro.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want you guys to write it is not true and my intention is to
come back with the Trojans,'' Soward said.
</P>
<P>
   Doubting Thomas: Although freshman quarterback Jason Thomas
officially did not make the trip because of a sore ankle and
illness, several sources confirmed that he also stayed home because
he had missed at least one practice without permission last week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
