<P>
   GERM-WARFARE _ A look at the state of germ weapons after the
collapse of the Soviet Union. By William J. Broad and Judith
Miller.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Map has been sent to NYT graphics clients. Photo
[NYT2) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   HAMAS-INTERVIEW (Gaza City, Gaza Strip) _ An interview with
Sheik Ahmed Yassin, the leader of Hamas, freed from house arrest by
the Palestinians, and a look at his mystique and his role as a card
to be played by both sides in the peace negotiations. By Deborah
Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT1) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-SUCCESSION _ Nelson Mandela's designated heir goes to
his home village in an effort to raise his profile. By Suzanne
Daley.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Map has been sent to NYT graphics clients)
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-AIDS-KILLING (Johannesburg, South Africa) _ A volunteer
working to convince South Africans not to discriminate against
HIV-infected people was beaten to death last week by her neighbors,
who accused her of bringing shame on their community by revealing
that she was HIV-positive. By Donald G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-HOSPITALS _ Although the effect of sanctions is evident in
every aspect of Iraqi life, there are few places where it is more
poignantly visible than at hospitals. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-ANNAN (United Nations) _ An interview with the
Secretary-General Kofi Annan, focusing on why he has felt it
helpful to deal with the devil, so to speak, during the crises with
Iraq and in other instances. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-TV-BLONDES (Rome) _ The biggest television phenomenon in
Italy is what they call a ``soubrette,'' borrowing a French term
for a nubile maid in a theatrical comedy. But to Italians, the
ideal TV soubrette doesn't necessarily sing or dance. She is almost
always tall, blond and Californian, and speaks adorably fractured
Italian. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT5) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO-UNIVERSITY (Chicago) _ Ever since its creation on the
south side of Chicago in 1892 with a pile of Rockefeller money and
a group of top-flight scholars, no academic institution has
exemplified intellectual seriousness quite like the University of
Chicago. But with colleges today viewed increasingly as employment
credentialing stations, the University of Chicago is in the midst
of a painful identity crisis. By Ethan Bronner.
</P>
<P>
   NY-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE _ More money than ever is cascading into New
York campaigns, but the system of regulating these funds to curb
their influence on politics and policy has all but broken down. By
Clifford J. Levy.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   MASS-NATIVITY (Boston) _ A profile of Elma Lewis, a 76-year-old
black woman who has run a live nativity show in Boston for decades.
By Sara Rimer.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-OTTERS (San Francisco) _ Southern sea otters, the playful
darlings of the central California coast, appear to be diminishing
in number at a rate that perplexes and worries scientists.
</P>
<P>
   NY-FOXHUNT (Millbrook, N.Y.) _ Where the hunt is a way of life,
friends of foxes begin to fight back. By David W. Chen.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT4) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-REPUBS _ Depite post-impeachment polls showing that the
Republican Party's standing has sunk to its lowest level in years,
leading Republicans insist they are not worried that the party will
suffer longterm damage, because they expect the Senate to settle
the matter quickly. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAY-SPENDING _ Largely undistracted by the impeachment of
President Clinton and the bombing of Iraq, U.S. shoppers appear to
have spent freely from wallets that still feel pretty fat, giving
retailers a muscular, if not stellar, holiday season. By Leslie
Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL-TV _ Digital technology _ which enables the television
signal to be compressed to carry far more information _ is ushering
in this new age, when perhaps 1,400 or 1,500 choices will be on
parade. Some of those choices will take forms people now associate
with the computer rather than the television set, like bringing
data to the screen, or Internet access, or interactive shopping,
banking or video games. By Lawrie Mifflin.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-EVOLUTION (Undated) _ Centralized intelligence,
accessible via fast computer networks, would pose a threat to the
dominant role of personal computers. That challenge to the PC seems
to be at hand. But whether that shift is the beginning of a
revolutionary transformation or an evolutionary progression is a
matter of fierce debate. By Steve Lohr and John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients. Photo
[NYT10) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ In the Internet business, the
forces propelling the leading companies like America Online, Yahoo
and Amazon.com remained the same throughout the year _ even if the
pace picked up faster than anyone might have expected. And yet the
tumultuous year does seem to yield at least five lessons about the
Internet industry and the stocks associated with it. By Saul
Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SERIOUS-ANIMATION-MEDIA (Undated) _ ``The Prince of Egypt'' was
to be a movie with a serious theme that audiences would recognize
as raising the art of mass-market animation to a new level. While
the Christmas weekend ticket sales kept hopes alive for the
animated story of Moses, many people in Hollywood say that two
weeks after its release, the movie is not showing signs of becoming
a megahit. By Geraldine Fabrikant.
</P>
<P>
   DIGICOM-COLUMN _ Those who successfully pushed for passage in
October of the Internet Tax Freedom Act, which declared a
three-year tax moratorium for online sales, have reason to cheer.
But the long-term implications could be troubling. By Denise
Caruso.
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL-RADIO-MEDIA _ The promise of a crisp radio signal that
can be heard anywhere in the nation, considered a futuristic pipe
dream a decade ago, now appears to be only about a year from
reality. By Andrea Adelson.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT8,9) have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MTV-TEEN-SCREAMERS (New York) _ ``Sometimes you say you're not
going to scream, but then you do,'' said Karen Lopez, 14, as she
angled for a glimpse of a wayward elbow, a Fubu jacket or anything
else signifying the presence of the group 'N Sync, which was
gracing the MTV studios one story above her in Times Square. On a
regular basis young fans, most of them teen-aged girls, regularly
line the streets of Broadway hoping to glimpse the acts that show
up for MTV's ``Total Request Live,'' from 3:30 to 4:30 p.m. ET. By
Peter Applebome.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT 7) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   JEWISH-MUSEUM-FRANCE (Paris) _ In a country already crowded with
museums dedicated to every imaginable topic, it was at the very
least strange that until now France had no Jewish museum worthy of
the name. This month, President Jacques Chirac inaugurated the new
Museum of the Art and History of Judaism in the Marais, the old
Jewish quarter of Paris. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   BARRY-WRITER-PROFILE (Undated) _ Although novelists have written
plays, and playwrights have written novels, it is rare for a writer
to be equally adept at both arts, with one definite exception being
Samuel Beckett. But at 43, Beckett's countryman Sebastian Barry
seems well on his way to such an accomplishment. By Mel Gussow.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT3) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   RADIO-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Until I read Gerald Nachman's
captivating, highly personal book, ``Raised on Radio,'' I didn't
realize _ or remember _ just how much a generation was conditioned
by that ubiquitous box of sounds, or how radio shaped our language,
conversation and dreams. Reviewed by Mel Gussow.
</P>
