<SLUG> BC-GEN-CSUN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE'S HEINLE DOES FINE HARRIS IMPRESSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Inside or outside. Post-up or face-up to the
basket.
</P>
<P>
   That was the scouting report on Cal State Northridge power
forward Rico Harris entering the season.
</P>
<P>
   It's turned into the scouting report on CSUN's 6-foot-9
sophomore, Brian Heinle.
</P>
<P>
   Since Dec. 3 _ when Harris injured his hip, from which he has
yet to return _ Heinle has been remarkable. Not to mention what the
Matadors (7-4) need.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to keep it simple and stay within the system, and
if my shots come then I'm going to shoot it,'' said Heinle, who's
averaging a team-best 14.7 points and 6.8 rebounds per game. ``With
Rico out we need to pick up the offensive scoring a little bit, and
I feel I can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past six games, in which CSUN is 4-2, Heinle's averaging
18.3 points. He's scored in double digits each time and was named
the PowerBar Invitational MVP at the University of Hawaii
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Heinle, who averaged 6.9 points last season, scored a
career-high 23 points in the first round of the BYU Classic against
Southern Utah and is shooting 42 percent from 3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we recruited him, because we knew he could shoot
the ball on the outside,'' coach Bobby Braswell said. ``Besides the
UCLA game (Dec. 19), he's been a force on the inside for us. He's
not afraid to bang in there, which is the thing that hurt him last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``As he continues to mature and his body gets bigger and
stronger he's going to be a tough kid to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Women face big test: CSUN's women's basketball team will learn
quickly how it compares with the best of the Big Sky. Instead of
easing into conference play, the Matadors (6-4) vault into it
against Northern Arizona on Wednesday (7:05 p.m.) at home.
</P>
<P>
   The Lumberjacks (6-4) are coming off a 22-6 campaign, in which
they went 15-1 in the conference.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors were picked to finish third in the conference but
have been plagued by inconsistency since beginning the season 3-0.
However, the return of sophomore forward Neda Milic bolstered the
rebounding game against Oral Roberts last week and should help
balance things.
</P>
<P>
   Football schedule update: Matadors football coach Ron Ponciano
still doesn't want to play Southern Utah in the season opener next
Sept. 4, but a replacement game may not be so easy to find.
</P>
<P>
   Most schools are keeping their schedules open until after next
month's NCAA meetings because conference affiliations could change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shoot, I still think someone out there will give us money to
come play them,'' Ponciano said. ``I'm not worried about that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors want to play a Division I-A team, but that creates
another quandary. Southern Methodist is already on CSUN's schedule,
and the thinking in the football offices is the Matadors will have
to go 8-3 or win the Big Sky to make the playoffs. Playing two
Division I-A teams leaves very little margin for error.
</P>
<P>
   A scenario discussed in the past was a game with San Jose State,
if Stanford decides to drop the Spartans from its schedule next
season. It would cost CSUN $10,000 to break the game with Southern
Utah, but a guarantee from the new opponent would cover it.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN wants to break the contract for fear of the players'
safety. The Matadors lost three defensive linemen to leg injuries
in an Oct. 3 win over the Thunderbirds. Each injury occurred on an
illegal chop block.
</P>
<P>
   However, Thunderbirds athletic director Jack Bishop said no one
from CSUN has contacted him about dropping the game in Cedar City,
Utah, since Oct. 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was all straightened out,'' Bishop said. ``I know
they are still on our schedule, and as far as I know, we're still
on their schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Simmons update: Former Matadors men's basketball player Jabari
Simmons made the grade at Southern California College and is
eligible for the second semester.
</P>
<P>
   Simmons was CSUN's second leading scorer last season at 12.3
points per game but transferred after disciplinary measures caused
him to miss the final five games of the 1997-98 season. Simmons was
also second on the team with 6.3 rebounds per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll make us stronger inside, but if he doesn't buckle down
and play defense he's going to wind up hurting us,'' Southern
California College coach Cameron Dollar said. ``He's got to do
that, which he has to understand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
