<HEADLINE>
PREDICTIONS FOR '99
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Sidebar to Hoffarth column) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With all the preposterous predictions that can be made about the
world of sports in 1999, at least go to the source: Mystic Meg, the
seer for the supermarket tabloid The Globe.
</P>
<P>
   We don't know her accuracy rating, but based on some of the
actual things she wrote in the Dec. 29 issue, we're not about to
call her the Gary Anderson of Visionaries.
</P>
<P>
   For example:
</P>
<P>
   _Frank Gifford is delighted when he awakens to newspaper
headlines declaring ``ABC Wants Gifford for Monday Night
Football.'' But he's shocked to read that the Gifford they want to
do play-by-play is wife Kathie Lee, not him!
</P>
<P>
   _Road-rage bully Mike Tyson finally meets his match. After a
fender-bender in Beverly Hills, he storms out of his car to tear
the other driver limb from limb. But he relaxes when he realizes he
rammed Zsa Zsa Gabor's new car. Mike sticks out his hand to greet
her, but the Mad Hungarian fractures his skull with her heavy
purse.
</P>
<P>
   _Baseball heroes Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa are cast in a major
motion picture to play two convicts known only by the numbers 70
and 66. While chained together at the ankle, they escape and return
to their tiny hometown to prove their innocence. The movie thriller
is named ``Home Run.''
</P>
<P>
   _``Tonight Show'' legend Johnny Carson faints in the Royal Box
at Wimbledon during a heat wave and is revived by mouth-to-mouth
resuscitation, by lesbian tennis veteran Martina Navratilova, who
was a guest in the next row.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
